Title: Best Casio I've owned
Text: Arrived fast and I couldn't wait to setup everything which was easy .I highly suggest to watch a YouTube video on how to program if you've never programmed a Casio watch before. Reading the manuel is small and it'll be hard. I have 6 Casio watches, two of which are G-Shock. This is my favorite out of all of them. It seriously feels like I'm not even wearing it right now, wait am I?! Yes. Had to double check. Lol. Very comfortable watch and damn it looks good. One of the main reasons I bought this was not the price but because it's one of the very first G-Shock watches they made in Japan. And I was watching Speed movie and noticed this was the watch Keanu Reeves is wearing the entire movie. And this is the watch where they had a hockey player slap shock it and it didn't break. That's how it got popular and it still is. There's a reason for that, it lasts! Every Casio watch I own gets worn everyday as I switch them out depending on what I'm doing through the day. If I'm working on my truck, I'll wear the cheapest Casio watch so if it gets dirty, I don't really care but can still tell the time while I'm working on my truck or doing something. At work, I wear my Casio DW3502AE and that's one of my favorite watches to wear no matter what I'm wearing and got only $20 bucks, you'd think you paid more. I also have the Casio G shock DW9052 but it's pretty bulky and hard to read. I like the look but i hardly wear it. I love Casio and they make extremely reliable, slick and durable watches for anyone, casual, miliary and law enforcement. They're just indestructible and they have something for anyone.

Title: I love it
Text: I got this to see if I like the G-Shock square. Yeah, its the best! New to watches, but I thought I wouldn't like it as much as the smaller f91w. The increase premium feel makes me not want to wear the f91w! I thought it might feel/look too big. It's fine. Great simple look. Hourly chime is soft and not loud. I like that. I sync it up using time.gov every week and it keeps perfect time. Edit: I love this watch so much I decided to get the GW-5000u-1jf. I honestly just couldn't vibe with the color so I sent it back after a day. I preferred the look of this one. Plus this watch was basically in the movie Speed! After trying the Gw-5000u-1jf I like the softness of the band a lot. I wanted to put the same band on this watch but its around $48 and that's about how much I paid for the watch. So I settled on the Thailand band part number 10512401 for about $20 here on Amazon. It is a step up from the band that comes with this watch. It feels a bit better now... more soft. Not that it was bad before. The color looks like it actually blends better with the bezel now too. I hope they keep making this one. If they made a GW-5000U level watch with this color scheme id be all over it!

Title: Great looking, super comfortable, and well built
Text: I love this watch. I was on the fence with all the G-Shock square face variants. I chose the lowest cost, most basic model thinking I’d be unhappy with the screen contrast or build quality. Not at all! They’ve done a great job making this very nice watch for little money. I prefer not having the Bluetooth but the one thing I’d like is the rough solar. But not for the extra $100. Ended up liking the subtle color touches of the dw5600e face and I find the band comfortable. The whole watch is extremely light, making it easier to wear than my metal case watches. The case size is perfect too - not too big and not too small. Really happy with this watch and hope to have it for many years to come :)

Title: Best watch I'll ever own
Text: I bought the dw5600 in an Army PX for $40 the year I turned 18. I've had four copies of this model in a row for 33 years since. I read that they are designed for 10 year life but I'm rough on them - I've used the case to hammer nails and crazy stuff like that. I have no need for any of the features or cost of the more expensive versions. I left the stopwatch running for a month once. I use the heck out of the light. Didn't seem to drain the battery much at all. I won't stop wearing them until I'm dead. They go surprisingly well with my business attire.

Title: Great watch for a simple but complicated person

This watch gives me a break from that electric current. Allowing me to relax in simplicity and enjoy life without the electric noise from my devices when I want to unplug. Also this watch is tough and I has no issues in the cold. Which my smart watch sometimes have when it’s gets to cold out. Well most electronics act up when it gets to cold out.

Title: I love it!

It’s not drastically huge either, I looked at other G-shocks and they looked ENORMOUS!!! This is my first one and it’s perfect. I had the Casio (non Gshock) just like this growing up so it brings back memories. Super happy with my purchase.

Title: Simple, perfect for what it is.
Text: This watch is absolutely great for what it is and the price point. It shows me what time is, and after one month it has stood up to prolonged digging, grinding concrete, busting out drywall, crawling around under a house, crawling around in a 80 year old attic, Jack hammering, drilling, regular hammering, rain, sweat, blood and all the other rigors that come with my line of construction (which includes a bit of every trade but hvac). Plus, my wife thinks it looks very handsome on me. I just turned 30 today and I’m fairly fashion forward, especially considering my profession. I like to look nice and this watch is just slim enough for me to get away with wearing it with slacks and a tie, but also rugged enough to not break or scratch when I throw the earth at it. I bought it for $41 and it is worth every penny. I’d knock off a star if I had paid $80. One of the buttons is a little more inset than the rest (and it doesn’t appear to be intentional). Luckily I don’t use the buttons.

Title: Perfect Watch
Text: I bought this to replace a cheap but loved Casio Wave Ceptor I just lost. Was hesitant to leave the Radio function but it has proved no problem. This has a built in calendar up to 2099 and keeps time beautifully so was easier to give up than thought. As for ruggedness and durability, this has handled 12 beach and pool days in a row, gym, biking (sweat) all with aplomb so far. It honestly fits any outfit with the black and brownish hue of screen and touches of white and blue. Size wise it wears absolutely perfectly for 6.75 in wrist - felt this immediately and didn’t have to “get used to it” I was initially considering the ~$100 one with multi-band 6 but didn’t feel price was worth it and glad I picked up this instead. One other note is that this has timer function down to seconds - which is NOT SUPPORTED in Multiband 6 variant - starts at minute. This is handy when doing 30-45second timed workouts.

Title: NIce! But... Pushers are too hard to push!
Text: There probably isn't much that I can add to what has already been said about this widely respected basic Casio G-Shock.  But I would mention a couple things that irritate me: 1.  The recessed 'pushers' (that control digital functions, on the outside corners of the watch) really are extremely difficult to 'push'.  A vocal minority of DW5600E owners will doubtlessly insist that the recessed pushers are just as they should be because this prevents them from being accidentally pushed.  Well, that is certainly not going to be a problem, I agree, but I think it should also be possible to push them intentionally, which for me at least requires taking off the watch and positioning a fingernail at just the right angle on a slippery, small metal surface and positioning another finger on the opposite side of the case to generate a sufficiently large amount of squeezing pressure to push the little circular pin-head like pushers far enough into the watch to engage.  With great effort I can sometimes push them with finger-tips, but my finger-tips become quite sore if I have to push them this way more than a couple times a day - it's ergonomic sadism!  I"m decking the watch 1/2 review star for the poor design of the pushers.  Yes, they shouldn't get pressed accidentally (at least not too easily), but they should be MUCH easier to push (and possible to push conveniently without taking off the watch). 2.  at least half the vertical space that is available for the LED is taken up by marketing blurbs that seem to be trying to get users to forget the word "Indiglo" and learn to call the glow in the dark feature "ELECTRO LUMINESCENT BACKLIGHT"  and to recognize this item as an ILLUMINATOR model.  Personally I'd rather have an LED that's twice as tall so the digital numerals showing time/date and other information is easier to read.  I bought a digital Timex Expedition watch at the same time as this Casio, which has almost exactly the same amount of space for an LCD.  The Timex watch has it's own branding elements, (though not of the same crude tacky sort), but keeps them on tabs above and below the bezel, and also moves the pusher 'hints' (like stop/start) etc. off the LCD and onto the bezel.  The result is a digital readout that's about twice as large as this Casio's.  I guess it wouldn't be the DW-5600 classic anymore if Casio did something (sensible/useful) like that. If this were not otherwise such a nice watch, the inefficient use of available LCD space here would be penalized more than the 1/2 star I'm taking off. Otherwise, I think this is a very nice item.  The case is substantial, pleasantly weighty,  and it's construction is obviously very high quality.  The build quality elements surprised me & greatly exceeded my expectations.  These watches will definitely survive the coming Zombie Apocalypse.  I have no major complaint about the rubber strap, though it could be softer and more flexible.  You can't lay this watch flat (face-up) -- the band is curved and too stiff to flatten out.  Digital features are basic, but reasonably intuitive and work just fine.  The manual is pretty well written IMHO.  Packaging is cheap, but I really don't care or expect much for $40.00. I especially like the "ELECTRO LUMINESCENT BACKLIGHT" on this watch.  The dark jade/green color is really beautiful and makes the Cyan Indiglo back-lighting on the Timex I got seem cheap by comparison. I had a little trouble figuring out how to set the date at first, becoming confused by a field that seemed to increment from 00 to 100, till I read the manual and found this watch has a perpetual calendar feature, so the value there is to enter the year (from 2000-2100).  So that's quite nice actually. Also noteworthy - the watch I received is also very accurate.  It's been running at a rate that extrapolates to  +2.66 seconds per month,  roughly ~1/2 a min per year.  It's quartz movement has rated accuracy of +-15 secs/mo.  Most other Casio watches in the same or even somewhat higher price range(s) are rated either +-30 secs or +-20 secs.  It's easy to forget that keeping track of the time is, at least to a considerable extent, the purpose of a watch, and it would be difficult at this price to find one that does a better job.

Title: Reliable and classic watch
Text: I just ordered and received this, my second DW5600E after the first one suffered bezel failure (the watch still works) after almost 12 years on the original battery.  When I tried to replace the failed battery I accidentally bent the (very stiff) original band too far the wrong way; my fault.  The resin is tough but it does get a little brittle with age.  That watch replaced a 1982 vintage DW200 that also still works, but also had the resin case crack after 28 years of nearly continuous use and multiple battery changes. I was delighted to receive a watch made in Thailand, not China, at this price point.  I look forward to another decade or more of flawless usage and utility.

Title: Casio G-Shock DW-5600E
Text: I've been an avid watch collector my entire life, but it wasn't until the past year or so that I've been seriously bitten by the "watch collector" bug. I realized that I didn't have a digital in my collection, and it just so happened that I had also been looking for a beater watch, something to just wear around casually. I always knew the G-Shocks had a big following, so I decided to hop on the bandwagon and I settled on the DW-5600. I chose this watch because, to me, it looks the most "classic" of the G-Shock line. I didn't really care about Solar or Atomic capabilities, which also helped out on the price. On Amazon's end, they did an adequate job. The watch arrived when it was supposed to, but the box was a little beat-up when I got it. The packaging wasn't all that great, either, because inside the box only one single "air-bag" protected the item. I was a little disappointed in the packaging of the watch itself. It didn't come in one of those cool gray tins that you see online, or even one of the bigger square black and red G-Shock boxes. Instead, the watch was packaged in a small rectangular box containing a plastic stand with the watch on it and the module book folded in half and stuffed underneath. Not a big deal, but a little neater package would be nice. Now, onto the watch itself. When I opened the box, I was surprised at just how nice it looks. Really, the watch looks much better in person that it does in any of the photographs I've seen. Like I mentioned above, the watch has a very classic digital look, with a very simple, rugged, "no-frills" design. The band is resin, and at first glance doesn't really look that comfortable. However, once you put it on, it feels nice and smooth on your skin. The watch is also incredibly light (60g, according to Casio's website), so much so that I barely even notice it's there. The build quality feels very solid, and I have the feeling that the watch could withstand a pretty tough beating. The case has a Casio branded metal plate on the backside and a metal buckle on the band. The readout has a positive display and isn't clogged up with useless information, so it's very easy to read. You've got the day and date on top, and time on the bottom. The backlight is nice and bright, although I wish it would stay illuminated for longer than two seconds. The four buttons are located on each corner of the case and I had no problem pressing any of them except for the "adjust" button, which is recessed so you don't accidentally bump it and reset the watch. This is my biggest complaint about the watch, seeing how sometimes I have to take the watch off just press the adjust button. But, luckily you don't have to use it that often, so it's not a deal-breaker. As for the features of the watch, they're all pretty standard. There's no barometric pressure gauge, tide readouts, or moon-phase indicators, just the standard features. Pressing the lower left button lets you scroll through the watches four modes: Time, alarm, countdown, and stop-watch. These modes are self-explanatory, and the time is viewable in each mode. The watch gives a resounding "beep" when changing modes, and a slightly higher-pitched chirp when returning to time mode. The volume on the alarm is adequate. I consider myself to be a heavy sleeper, and the alarm woke me up just fine. Overall, the Casio G-Shock DW-5600E is a solid watch. It's classic design, sturdy construction, and refreshingly basic features make it a must-have digital in any collection, especially G-Shock enthusiasts. And, at just over $40, it's an incredible value. 4.5/5 stars

Title: Awesome Classic G-Shock
Text: This is actually my first Square G-Shock.  I'm used to wearing the ones with the sensors, tough solar, and automatic time-keeping, and I didn't think I'd wear this one a lot.  But I actually wear it a lot!  This is the closest you'll get to the original 1983 DW 5000.  I can see why G-Shock fans love this watch. The light is pretty darn bright, and you also have a feature where you can make the watch light up whenever you have an alarm or the hourly time signal on.  Sure, it doesn't have auto-light, but hey, it's a classic G-Shock. It has the 3 basic functions: stopwatch with split time, a timer that runs 24 hours, and an alarm. Few things I need to mention for those considering getting this watch for the first time.  The stopwatch and timer both show the current time when you're in their modes.  This is one of the reasons I decided to get the DW 5600e.  I tried the GWM 5610 but I had to return it because both the stopwatch and timer would not display the current time. The timer: it runs 24 hours, and it displays the current time.  What's also cool about the timer is that you can also set seconds, and any amount of seconds is fine, whether you want 5 seconds or even just 2 seconds or so.  Very cool. As for the alarm, again, just one alarm.  An interesting thing about the alarm is that you can set an alarm for a certain month and day.  This would be cool if the watch had more than one alarm.  4 alarms would good for this kind of date feature.  I use a lot of alarms every day, so the month/day feature on the one single alarm is interesting. The beeps are pretty audible and it has that classic Casio sound.  However, keep in mind that the sound can't be muted.  Again, classic G-Shock. Unlike most modern squares, the adjust button is less visible on the side.  But it's not difficult to press.  In fact, all the buttons are easy to press. Also, whenever you play around with any of the modes of the watch, when you press the mode button, you automatically go back to the current time.  Since there's only 3 basic features and the buttons are easy to press, this isn't too big of a deal. Lastly, when setting current time, timer, and alarm, you only get one button to use after you press adjust, and it only goes forward.  I didn't like it at first, but when you hold the button down, the numbers more pretty fast.  I got used to it after a day or two. I've seen videos of people in Japan testing this particular watch, and man, it's a tough guy!  I've seen it been dropped from several stories high, crushed by machinery, sunk 200 M below the sea, and I've even seen it completely covered in mud.  It's almost as tough as a basic Mudmaster. The strap is extremely comfortable and the watch is so light you sometimes forget you're wearing it. The watch stays on beat almost all the time.  I never have to worry about adjusting the time once in a while or have it be off by a few seconds. Overall, this is an awesome watch and one that everyone, especially G-Shock fans, should have at some point in their lives.  There, I think I've covered everything I could.

Title: Only one thing I'd change
Text: Why oh why did they put the stopwatch and timer reset at the top left reset button? It's too hard to get to because it's recessed a bit. Should have just put it on the light button. Oh well, still works, and you'll figure out how to get to the button a bit easier (tip, use your fingernail). Other than that, it's an amazing watch!

Title: Water Resistant...For Awhile, Anyway
Text: For wristwatches, I'd like to think that I don't have a lot of requirements, especially if I'm spending less than fifty bucks. For my little bit of money: the watch needs to stay on my wrist, keep time reasonably accurately, and possibly illuminate if I need to tell the time in the dark. Oh, and there needs to be some water resistance, since I don't take off the watch when I wash my hands, or take showers, or wash dishes, or do any of the other stuff that involves, well, water. Casio's G-Shock watches are, historically, amazing little gadgets that keep on keeping on even when you live everyday life while wearing them. However, as with so many other consumer brands, Casio's taken a giant step backward. For several months, the watch worked perfectly. Setting the time was a breeze, the illumination was nice and bright, and I did my daily things without worrying about killing the timepiece. When I say "everyday things," I don't mean swimming or cliff diving or otherwise spending lots of time in wet environments. I don't swim well, and therefore don't enjoy it, and try not to spend more time in water than necessary as a result. After several months of mostly dry life, the display started acting wonky. If I tapped it, the time would reappear, for awhile at least. Because I didn't really feel like messing with a warranty return - and because i wasn't sure if the product were even still UNDER that warranty - I figured I'd open up the back and see what I could see. Was there a loose part? A strange battery issue? A stranger problem that none of you would believe even if I shot a video for you? Nope. It was the teeny tiny bit of rubber serving as "moisture resistance" inside the watch, behind the metal plate that you remove to access the battery. Even though I let the watch dry out for a few hours before closing it back up, the next shower I took made the problem come right back. Perhaps I shouldn't have opened up the watch myself - it's entirely possible that I didn't properly replace the tiny little strip of rubber - but, to be fair, the watch had taken in moisture BEFORE I busted out my tiny screwdrivers. What a piece of junk. I bought a comparable Timex from another retailer and have been happy since I took it out of its box. Maybe the higher-end G-Shocks are still good, but I'm not spending money to find out.

Title: Great watch, and knew that because its predecessor, a Casio G-shock, was great and lasted forever.
Text: Started wearing it as my gym watch and then happily started wearing it full time, bravo.

Title: Great for small wrists
Text: I own another G-Shock (GWM500A-1, which is Solar/Atomic). My other watch is great except it isn't comfortable on my small wrist.  My wrist is 6" (15.25 cm) and this G-Shock is much more comfortable.  This band is more flexible, and the watch isn't as large as most of the other G-Shocks. Casio does make the Baby G-Shock line that is smaller (but sometimes has less water resistance). I didn't want "Baby" on my wrist, so this G-Shock fits my needs perfectly.

Title: Love the OG G-SHOCK
Text: This is the best 40.00 USD I can rember spending. For a G-shock, the watch wears smaller on wrist than I expected (very comfortable, really) and would remain on my wrist at all times (sleep, showers, etc.) but not for an automatic that needs worn to remain ticking. The functions are fairly intuitive and there is no mistaking the Casio alarm sound. I have no fear of water damage (but haven't dived with it or tested that past splashes during daily activities). The illumination works well and the display is easy to read, even under full sun. I do think mine might be a bit defective bc the display actually shows more contrast at a slight angle (weird) but whatever, I'll get another for the sake of comparison. I sort of wish i'd have gotten the atomic clock-set + solar powered model, but for half the cost this one is great. I've heard the battery will prbly last about 5 yrs, the resin band may last 2x that long with daily wear; realistically, this could be the only watch i need for the next third of my life. And it looks awesome, a tidy little square with neat lines of text framing the functions. I like the nostalgic vibes (dads wore square Casios from Walmart - not G-shocks - when I was a kid in the 80s). I cannot recommend this or any G-shock highly enough. If ya know, ya know.

Title: Wrist band is small for above average people
Text: I hate being 6' 4". Those of you who wish you were tall, stop it. Tall people can't find clothes, eyewear, shoes, hats, or jewelry to name a few. They can barely fit in some cars. On to the watch review. The wristband is too small for someone who has an 8.5-inch wrist. I wear it on the first notch when my wrist is swollen and on the 2nd notch when it isn't. I do like the watch itself. My favorite part is the readout display. It shows the day of the week, month, day of the month, and the time all on one easy-to-read face. One look and I have all of the date information I need when filling out paperwork. I say that because not all watches have as much information on one display. At first, I didn't think I would like the Adjust button because it is recessed and stiff. However, I found that the more I use it the easier it gets. I don't know if the button needs to be used to loosen up or if I have trained my muscle memory to press it just right. Whatever the case, the adjustment button isn't as bad as I thought it would be. I would have liked a wriststrap to accommodate above-average people. Other than that, this watch is worth the price for sure.

Title: Nearly Ten Years of Service but Showing its Age.
Text: I have owned this watch since November of 2013. My two photos show how this watch has held up in nearly 10 years of being worn day in, day out at different jobs I've held. I've been in numerous pools and bodies of water including the oceans while scuba diving. I have rarely used the features such as the stopwatch, timer and backlight maybe once a year if that. Everything about it is original since day one including the battery which is starting to show its age. If I were to try to use the backlight now the display does light up with illumination but the date and time all blank out before coming back after the blacklight shuts off. This is telling me the battery is on its way out, I don't know how much more time I have with it but it definitely was worth the purchase price. For now I am going to ride out how much time is left on the battery until it finally dies. I currently have no plans on replacing the battery and restoring the waterproof feature when it does die as I lack the tools and skill to perform this work properly.

Title: An expensive rugged watch for weekend wear while doing chores
Text: This is an old design but, a good one.  I had a Casio like this on in the 1980s.  It was rugged and lasted a long time.  When I needed a basic watch to wear on weekends while doing chores or when I wanted to go hunting or fishing this watch came to mind. The rubber face for absorbing shock makes it more difficult to get to the buttons.  That may not be all bad since it prevents accidental pressing of buttons. The band was to small.  I had to ordered another band in order for the watch to fit.

Title: Great Watch (and a comparison to the Casio W800H)
Text: I collect watches and never thought I’d want a G Shock as all the G Shocks I’ve seen on my friends wrists did not appeal to me.  But I absolutely love this one and am convinced it is the best value of the entire G Shock  line.  I have been wearing a Casio W800H and I’m going to compare the two.  They are close in size (G Shock is bigger).  The G Shock is more comfortable to wear due to its pre-curved and higher quality strap.  The G Shock is also more attractive on the wrist due to a much better looking case and strap and a matte black finish.  G Shocks have a certain “street cred” that the cheaper Casio digital watches just don’t have.  It is also far tougher than the cheaper Casio, very well made and incredibly durable, probably indestructible, and the recessed mineral glass screen is far more protected than the acrylic screen on the W800H, which is quite vulnerable to scratches.  A very impressive 200 m water resistance (compared to 100 m on the W800), a superb back light (far better than the W800H) and if I ever get a chance to go to space, it is also NASA approved.  Bottom line: this G Shock is better looking, more durable, more comfortable and has more presence on a man’s wrist than the W800H.  It also wears nice and light for a watch its size, which is a big plus for me. The downsides compared to the W800H: is three times the price I paid for the W800H (but all these watches are extremely affordable), the digital numbers that tell the time in the display are smaller than the numbers in the display of the W800H (but still readable), battery life is lower, and the four buttons on the G Shock are very stiff and much more difficult to use than the buttons on the W800H (probably necessary to achieve the very impressive 200 m water resistance). I am choosing this G Shock as my daily watch this summer.  I am really happy with it.

Title: Good watch but decided on the DW5610 instead
Text: I like this watch - especially for the price! I wore a DW6600 for years and years until it finally got stolen a few months ago. I figured I'd just do what I did last time I lost my original 6600 over 10 years ago - go buy a New Old Stock one on eBay or Amazon. Well lo and behold, it turn out that Bradley friggin Cooper ruined that for me by prominently wearing one in "American Sniper"... Now all of a sudden a NOS 6600 was selling for over $200. Well screw that. I loved the 6600 but truthfully I often felt it was too big and it hurt my hand when I bent my wrist back. So I decided to see what else there was - and was delighted to find that Casio had re-released the original 5600. In the course of my browsing I also saw the 5610 and was interested to see how the two might compare. So I purchased both - and of the two and I ended up keeping the 5610. Here, briefly is why... This one has simplicity on its side - there are only the 4 traditional modes: Time, Alarm, Stopwatch, and Timer. The 5610 by contrast has another mode - a 2nd time mode that appears on the first click through the modes. This mode tells you the time in one of any of the other time zones in the world, and as far as I'm concerned this is a completely useless feature... I suppose if you are one of those people that always needs to know what time it is in Hong Kong and can't seem to remember how to add or subtract then this is great. Otherwise it's just a useless extra step I have to go through to get to the other modes. It's a small thing but it annoys me and so I consider this another mark in the 5600's favor. Another thing that stands out on the 5600 vs the 5610 is the length of time the EL stays lit. The 5600 stays illuminated for just over 2 seconds, the 5610 for maybe just 1.5 seconds - it maybe seem like a tiny difference but it is noticeable, noticeable enough that when I first got my 5610 I was annoyed by it. And lastly - the 5610 flashes it's EL when an alarm goes off. This is actually a pretty useful feature for me since I often work in noisy and dark circumstances. So why then did I decide on the 5610? Well - the 5610 has 4 alarms, which comes in handy for me. The build quality just feels way better to me. The numerals are larger. The screen is brighter - I mean even without the EL. It never has to have the time set - Atomic clock sync takes care of that. It is solar powered so will never need a battery replacement. It looks nicer (to me) with the red accents around the face. It's more flexible setting alarms and timers since you can go both up and down if you accidentally go past your alarm time (the 5610 only goes up). But the BIGGEST hit against the 5600 is this: the damn ADJUST button is SO recessed into the case that I can't even activate it with my fingers. Now granted I have big fingers and no nails, but that is probably true for a lot of guys who might buy this watch. And the fact that I need a friggin' toothpick or paperclip or a pen to press and hold it down is really a total deal killer. Both my old 6600 and the 5610 have a recessed button that can't be activated accidentally, but both can be easily activated by me despite my big fat fingers. So in the end I decided to spend the extra $40 and keep the 5610 and I'm pretty happy so far... *Note that the price difference seems to have gotten bigger since just a few weeks ago and now the 5610 is about $60 more.

Title: One Watch To Rule Them All
Text: It's the watch your dad had in 1989. It is cool for this fact because you are now the same age as your dad in 1989. You never understood this basic watch in your younger years since you always wanted a Rolex or Omega. You always wanted a Lamborghini or Ferrari too but guess what? You are older and drive a paid off Camry and just like that Camry this little beauty is the most practical thing ever and can probably survive WWIII. It can get beat up, neglected, you can leave it on at the neighbor's pool party and it will always be there to tell you happily that lunch time is in 10 minutes.Yeah 10 minutes can you believe that the morning went so quick for a Tuesday? Also remember it is now March. Yeah February kinda flew by right? It is a certain confidence that lets the world know you aren't compensating for any lack of character. It's not even solar. Keep of the light button and the battery will last 11 years no problem but, you will probably drop it on a cruse before then and have a archaeologist in 3789 C.E. find it in the now drained ocean and think it is a ancient symbol of our god 'Casio'. Yeah it is tougher than nails.  And yes button 'A' is recessed more than the other buttons so your grubby mitts won't accidentally hit it and engage the 'change time' mode and eff up you perfectly synced quartz Feng Shui. Casio has got you bro.

Title: Didn't feel right without it
Text: Had this watch for almost a year, wore it everyday. Just decided to buy another one because i got a bit of transmission fluid on it and it ruined the rubber/plastic. You'll never get the smell of it off either. You could get new bands and a bezel, but for the cost (and the smell of transmission fluid) you might as well just buy another one. This watch held up to pretty much everything I threw at it, just keep it away from harsh chemicals and automotive fluids. Hard to tell from the pic, but transmission fluid kind of made the bezel part swell up.

Title: A G-Shock for people who hate giant watches
Text: I originally bought this watch as a "beater" watch so that I wouldn't have to worry about destroying the Pro Trek my wife got me for my birthday (not likely but just in case) or my Bulova automatics while at work. I managed to pick up a "Casio Royale" on clearance locally for less than $5 that I was going to use as a beater instead, but I like it well enough that I didn't want to ruin that watch (or the other small cheap Casios I have) on the daily either. I've never been a fan of G-Shocks primarily due to only having really seen their giant 50+mm hypertacticool ones I see lots of military guys wearing, which put me off the brand / series for a very long time. Given the price, and having seen that this model in particular is one of the very few watches officially certified for the space program I figured I'd make the jump. Pros: - It's very lightweight, so much so that it's easy to forget you're wearing it. - The backlight works extremely well. - Having a countdown timer as well as an alarm and stopwatch are great. - It's certified for space travel! - It was less than $45 - Water resistance is phenomenal. - "Positive" display - I absolutely adore the look of the negative display, but for actually using as a tool watch and not a fashion accessory the positive display is much, much easier to read at a glance than the negative display models. Cons: - No motion activated backlight. I got spoiled with my Pro Trek and miss being able to check the time in the dark without having to press the button. - No frills. The more expensive versions of this watch with moon phase / tide data are really appealing, but as a sub-$45 beginning step into the foray of non-gaudy G-Shocks I can live with it. - No solar / atomic timekeeping. Again it's less than $45 and realistically battery changes aren't that frequent or difficult, but the peace of mind with solar is nice to have. - The adjust button (top left) is intentionally recessed to prevent accidental presses, but realistically for me at least it also appears to do an excellent job of preventing most intentional presses too. I'd imagine this will get easier as I use it but for now I prefer the Pro Trek's non-recessed and easy to press buttons. All in all I would purchase this watch again without hesitation. It is great value for money if you need a basic timepiece that is nearly impossible to destroy.

Title: 10/10 Best watch for the price
Text: Durable, easy to read, easy to operate, does not cost $100 and it's a g-shock. Thank you Casio.

Title: Great watch, great price.
Text: Love the watch, it is easy to read, and you cannot beat the price.  My last one lasted 15 plus years.  Just as easy to buy a new one as to pay the price for a band and battery and you get an unscared face to boot.

Title: Defective brand new G-shock
Text: The adjust/reset button did not work in this brand-new G-shock. I could press the button and see it move inwards but it would not function. Result of the adjust/reset button not working is one cannot set the time, reset the stop watch, reset countdown, etc. Very surprising because G-Shocks are known for their durability. I returned the watch and gave up on Chinese manufactured G-Shocks.

Title: The basic watch for all conditions
Text: I think both the Amazon and external reviews can agree – this is by far the most durable yet inexpensive watch a person can own.  For all the wristwatches I have gone through, I never considered a g-shock for inexplicable reasons but after my Luminox watch began displaying the symptoms of a dying battery (amid other problems) I figured it was time to move on. Now like so many other reviewers, I can corroborate all but the most sycophantic evaluations of the classic Casio G-shock. The Classic G-Shock DW5600E-1V is perhaps the most inexpensive digital watch entry of Casio’s most durable watch series. Designed in the early ‘80s as a watch that could survive a fall from 10 feet and be submersible up to 10 meters (a little less than 33 feet) of water, the result was a line of both analog, digital, and hybrid wristwatches.  Even in this most basic configuration, the watch is made of a tough plastic yet premium feel and weight that radiates toughness.  The watch is simple to use with only four features – clock, stopwatch, alarm, and timer – it is truly a no-nonsense watch for the person who only needs the basics. For no and low-light users, the entire display lights up in a bright light green. It is a great watch for the likes of myself who only needs to know the date and time.  First off, I think it’s important it has a water-resistance to 20 Bars and oddly for all its claims, I do not think it has any IPX rating – not that I have any doubts to its specifications.  In another of its undocumented features, multiple reviews (and I think Casio themselves) have pointed out that the recessed button design was intentional [to prevent accidental mode changes] and can be a problem for people who have large fingers or wearing gloves. The time setting button on the upper left is the most recessed of them all and will require someone with at least a modest fingernail or key tip to confidently press it – making matters worse that this button used to reset stopwatch and timer.  Somewhat surprisingly, Casio’s continued to integrate a proprietary fixed-curved watchband that prevents it from lying on a flat surface so don’t be too quick to throw away the stand it comes with. Nevertheless, I still think is a great watch.  Coupled with my purchase of a screen protector, I am looking forward to +15 years of punctuality (comparable to the Luminox watch it is set to replace). Between my work that discourages personal calls and my indifference to my smartphone, I can go days without my phone but not without knowing the time - with the simplest G-shock, knowing that is as simple as a flick of my wrist.

Title: A Tough  and Simple Classic
Text: I am very glad I didn’t buy this watch first when I started my Casio collection, because it would have been my one and only, and that is saying something since I’m such a watch nerd. It’s as close as you can get to the original G-Shock from 1983. Call it a spiritual successor. It’s rough and tough: mine came in a box that looked as if it had been ambushed by a Nile crocodile and it worked splendidly. But don’t take my word for it: this model is rated to be worn in outer space by NASA and it holds the Guinness World Record for most pressure applied to a digital watch.  Check out the YouTube video of this tough mommy fudger getting ran over by a 25 ton truck! I knew all about the toughness of the G-Shock brand, but I think what surprised me the most about this watch was just how damn good it looks on my wrist. It’s retro but still aesthetically valid. That’s a great description and it would probably sell a lot of watches, but it’s also the best way I can express my truth for this one. Take a look at the picture I’ve attached to this review. I have a half dozen Casio watches now, most of them G-Shocks. This is by far my favorite looking watch. Looks and legendary reliability aside, this watch has all the standard features you’ve come to know and to love from Casio. It’s got precisely what you need and not a gram more: a backlight that actually illuminates the whole screen, a stopwatch, an hourly chime, and just a single alarm, but you can get quite in-depth with it thanks to its many functions. You can set it to go off at any time of day, every day, every Monday, on the 17th of every month or on April 5th, 2063. For you sharp eyed fellow Star Trek lovers out there, yes, that is First Contact Day, when the Vulcans arrive on planet Earth. They probably find wristwatches illogical but if they were going to wear one it’d surely be this Casio G-Shock.

Title: Best at what it’s made for
Text: Everyone else has pretty much summarized it, this watch is a phenomenal invention, through the test of time and millions of owners you just cannot go wrong with this, my personal insight: it is NOT bulky at all, it felt smaller than I thought it would be but perfectly balanced on my 7 inch wrist, the resin is tough but feels very good quality wise, the straps feel like they can take a lot of beating, it’s a solid watch that feels good and offers more than watches ten times the price and more, you’ll have to try really hard to break it, and it just looks so damn cool, I got the bb but gave it to my nephew because he fell in love with it, I got this next and personally I’m liking the retro display with a gazillion things written on it even though I prefer all black watches, always. Absolutely love it, my other watches have been stored away for a month now ever since I got this, others being seiko, certina, spinnaker, Hamilton, garmin instinct and an orient kamasu.

I have high hopes for this inexpensive watch based on the positive reviews. I'll update my review after getting the replacement in.

Title: Works as advertised, has for 40 years of watches
Text: This is a replacement watch. Have been replacing every 5-7 years for 40 years. The watch has all the functions I need at a good price. All the watches have been reliable and relatively accurate. Working on the water and around lots of vertical wiring have ended up with some of them snagged and ended up in the water, but the price has made replacing them affordable. The 24 hour time readout has been invaluable for watch standing over the years. They have to be good if I keep coming back to them.

Title: Fantástico
Text: Simple y perfecto

Title: "THE" Watch
Text: At first I bought a casio f91w which after a couple of days I noticed it had something rattling in it so I started looking for something a little more robust. I remembered I once had a G-Shock I took to Brazil and thrashed it for a couple of years and even slept/ bathed in it and it was going strong till the day I gave it to my brother in law (who lost it)! It was a different model than the 5600e but lived up to the G-Shock name, which is why I bought this one. I wanted a watch that I could wear all the time and not worry about, unlike my more expensive watches that I have ended up selling because I was always afraid of breaking them. The added 1983 retro style it has is just an added bonus! This watch is much larger in size than the f91w and does not rattle. The green backlight is nice and this watch does everything a watch should. So accurate time keeping you could "set your watch to it." The best part of this watch is that buttons do mot get pushed accidentally. If you have anything of a stub of a fingernail you should be able to push these buttons just fine. I bought it from Amazon, and the ones they sell are authentic, but made in China. I guess they no longer produce these in Taiwan, and it seems almost everything these days is now made in China. I like to modify things so I have already converted mine to a reverse display (white numbers on black background- there are tutorials online how to do this) and when I had the case open it said "Casio China no jewels" so the movement is also made in China. It still seems built well, other than the top left adjust button is recessed a little more than the others (it was purposely designed this way) and the white "G Shock" and "protection" writing is actually more of a greyish hue compared to previous models; which doesn't matter to me because I also blacked it out to copy the much more expensive military version of the 5600e. Also, while I had the case open there is a small spring that if you pull it out the watch no longer beeps. For me this is a plus: I don't like my watches to beep since I prefer to wake up to my cell phone. But beware when changing batteries not to lose this spring if you value the beep. There are many tutorials online if you decide to change the battery yourself. The owners manual states the battery supplied will last about 2 years depending on backlight usage. If you never use the backlight, it could last up to 10 years on the same battery, but either way you can find replacement batteries very cheap on ebay. All in all this watch is the perfect size and weight, feels great, and so far has taken quite a beating over the 2+ years I have used it and is living up to the G-Shock name.

Title: Classic G-Shock
Text: Just what I expected from this classic G-shock.  Fast delivery with all of the paperwork and packaging included.

Title: This is not the Foxfire DW5600E version
Text: I had picked up this watch back in 2018/2019, in 2021 this classic version is not available in Canada as new, so I picked this up on the US Amazon site. $45 USD is still good price in 2021. However, one of the image on Amazon.com (US) for this watch show the Foxfire version, sadly the version of the watch when it arrived was the Illuminator version. This is not the Japanese version, Amazon should update the website photo AND  the watch arrived in a paper box and plastic display NOT metal tin. Need to update your photos guys. Overall, great watch, the timer can be set to repeat, great for a reminder to take your medication or when you need to be reminded and keep a busy schedule (new parents). Great for 'desk divers' where you need a more then durable and water resistant to 200 meters watch. This DW5600 will more than survive home life! Just rinse off the watch if it gets dirty, if your worried about scratching the mineral crystal, get a screen protector. There are videos to show you how to mod (modify) this watch (strap extension, so you can use nato straps, change out the bezel/case and to clean the watch module)? This is the second thinnest G-Shock next to GA2100 (Casi-oak) I'm wearing my DW5600 with my Casio Duro  MDV106 both on a nato strap and a strap extension with the 5600. This setup allows me to have alarm, chimes, analogue watch and track two time zones, I like my Duro! Hey you do you. Both are durable and have 200 meters of water resistance.

Title: aA good buy at the price
Text: good buy

Title: Comfortable all-terrain watch
Text: I'm not a lumberjack or a deep sea fisherman, but it's nice knowing there's nothing I'll be able to do to this watch that will wreck it. If I happen to fall in the lake while kayaking, or smother it in snow, or land wrist first on a rock it will be fine. I love the 80s style of a lot of Casio digitals and this one fits right in. It fits my small wrist. It's definitely bigger and heavier than my favorite, the W-93H, but not by too much, and it has all the same features, including a timer that auto repeats, which I always appreciate. The manual doesn't mention it but if you use the bottom right button while setting the timer, you can toggle the auto repeat, so that it will immediately start counting down again while the alarm goes off. It helps me know when I'm half way through a workout of a set duration. Display could stand to be sharper and clearer like the F105 but it's not a deal breaker. This is definitely the most durable wristwatch you're going to get for $40 and it has the added perk of looking like it teleported in from 1987. I'll probably stick to the W-93H most of the time just because it disappears onto my wrist better, but this will certainly be my hiking and kayaking watch.

Title: I finally found you~!
Text: This is what my husband has to say: Been reading online for the past two weeks trying to figure out which watch to buy. I became interested with the Invicta submariner homage, then moved my way over to Orient Mako, then to Seiko SKX173, and finally I was going to be happy with a Seiko Monster. However, by chance I saw a digital watch in one of the recommended listings on Amazon. I started thinking about the purpose of owning a watch and my conclusion was simple - to tell time...accurately. Automatic watches are great for people who appreciate the engineering involved in creating such timepieces. The only qualm I have with these watches is they are not precise...and they are delicate...and they need maintenance. Thus my search for the ultimate watch began. This week long journey ultimately brought me back to the first watch manufacturer I've ever owned - Casio. Growing up, my Casio would be on my wrist through many adventures, be it climbing a tree...then falling down shortly after, or swimming in the Pacific Ocean, or in a math test in class...I got an A by the way =) I started looking for a simple yet rugged Casio...and guess what? I finally found it~! The Casio DW5600E-1V is an amazing watch. When I got this bad boy out of the box, I was amazed by how much better it looks in person vs pictures online. Trust me everyone, the pictures simply don't do justice. I began setting the time and noticed the adjust button was recessed. This worried me because I thought I got a defective watch. But alas, after some research I found out this was the design Casio had intended. I strapped this new watch on and was blown away...again~! I love the fact that it's not overly bulky and does not dig into my wrist. The digits are big enough so that one can tell time in a glance. A plus about this particular model is that the day, date, and time are displayed on the same screen. The illumination is perfect. It was bright enough that I used it as my light source earlier this evening to help my wife differentiate the right key to open the door. I appreciate the fact that the countdown timer in this model allows one to adjust the second, minute, and hour. The other models...for some strange reason only has a 60 minute CTD...yet they have a stopwatch that can count till all the digits become 9. What gives? I do not plan on using the alarm on this watch very often, but in the moments that I do, I like how it's not overly complicated i.e. 5 different alarms. This watch is durable yet light and has a big screen to tell time yet does not dominate my 6.75 inch wrist. I've only had my DW5600 for two days but I know it will serve as my accurate and durable timepiece for many new adventures to come.

Title: it's true - all the great reviews nail it (update 8 months later)
Text: (8/18/2020 update - still wearing the same watch watch. Every. Day. All. Day.  Never take it off unless its covered in mud, muck, or blood. Yes, sometimes its mine too.  Daily workouts, dirt bike, canoes,  fishing boats, jeeping...tons of hard knocks.  Same watch, same battery.  Since basic training in 1985 I have basically worn the same kind of watch... I got my kids wearing these now too.  Best watch ever made to me) (updated 8/2013)  AMAZING WATCH!  I was thinking about how tough, light, and perfect this watch was the other day after I was finished with an appointment in my dress clothes...and thinking back to the weekend when I abused this watch repeatedly with action sports, bug sprays, paint thinner (after getting some overspray paint on it, had to clean it up) and just all manner of dust, mud, swimming, etc....just a 'normal weekend' for me...and this great watch. It still looks brand new.  It's classy and refined in a boardroom and tough as nails in the outdoors, I just love it.  I will probably buy myself a backup...but it hasn't come off my wrist in 8 months...and i doubt it will in 8 years!  I just LOVE the fact that everying I need is on ONE screen and a simple light for the dark.  I don't use anyting but the main screen I've found out...but the time, date, and day is essential to me filling out various financial forms...and this unit has it all - right there one the main screen.  I'm VERY happy with this watch. I can't say enough good things about the watch and the great reviews here on Amazon about it.  It's all I need and nothing I don't. I came off slightly over 5 years of constantly wearing an "outdoor computer" watch on my wrist...really big - had alti, compass, baro, temp, gobs of alarms, timers, and settings....I barely used any of them...and now with iphones, I can easily get most of those features as apps.... if I ever really needed them. What this watch is...is a nice change I didn't know I really needed.  I like that it fits under my shirt sleeve and suit jacket sleeve better.  It's as tough as they come, and I've been able to use it shooting all day, banging around woods and campsites, using the chainsaw and maul for firewood...you name it...it's been perfect.  I like the night-light feature, mine is a green shade, very easy to see...and I LOVE that the day, date, and time are what is displayed on the home screen (all I've ever used - all I need.) This watch is perfect from the backyard swimming pool to a boardroom presentation.  Which is perfect since I never, ever take off my watch anyway.

Title: 25 years later and I fall in love with Casio all over again...
Text: With over 300 reviews on this watch, and almost 94% of them either 4 or 5 stars....I really didn't know what I could say positively in a review that hasn't already been said before.  So to that, I'll give my own viewpoint(s). 1)  Like many, I wore basic cheaper Casio watches growing up as a kid, in fact I think I had one on my wrist 95% of the time from the time I was 8 or so up into high school.  They were durable, functional, efficient, and basically maitenance free. I even remember trying a few Timex watches back then and not liking them for several reasons, always going back to Casio. Fast forward 20 years and I now have tastes for Tags, Hamiltons, Omegas, etc...watches that cost 20x or more what a Casio costs and which I can wear to casual, work, and dress environments.  However I found the need to still have a beater watch with some functional capabilities that I could use in certain situations when working around the house or just getting dirty.  I immediately went looking for a Casio, quickly found my way to this basic G-Shock, and less than a week after it came in the mail and I wore it a few times, I almost didn't want to put any of my other "luxury" watches back on because the Casio had quickly become one of my top favorites.  I now remember why I always loved these as a kid and this particular G-Shock is just perfect in so many ways.  I'm not a huge fan of some of the larger more gaudy G-Shocks, but then again I'm not reveiwing those...I'm reviewing the DW5600E-1V...and if I could give it 6 Stars I would.  I won't get into the specifics of why I like it, you can read any of the other nearly 300 positive reviews for it, but for all the basic reasons it is near perfect. 2)  My other thought on this review was what could people knock this watch for?  So basically that small group of people that gave it 1 or 2 stars, what was their story?  I wanted to see it from their perspective.  What I found out is that most of them didn't like this watch for things that any informed consumer would've known prior to buying.  Their complaints were somewhat subjective (too small display;  too large on wrist;  buttons too hard to push;  functions not exactly to their liking; etc...).  A few were viable though, in that there wasn't the ability to have the background illumination on when setting alarms, or a few who noted the band had broken under common wear.  All in all I guess its impossible to please 100% of the people, but like I said earlier, with over 315 reviews and more than 290 of them positive...you know what you're getting.

Title: Buttons = NOT BAD
Text: The buttons are NOT that difficult to use. Don't be scared off by negative reviews about the buttons. For example, I was able to set the watch time while driving! I almost didn't buy this watch based on the reviews complaining about the recessed "adjust" button (top left) being too hard to use, but they are not that bad. When I opened the package, the watch box lid was open and the bottom of the box was torn. Inside, the watch was sort of haphazardly covered with a loose plastic bag. The time on the watch was an hour off, but the minutes were correct. This all gave me the impression this watch may have been previously owned and returned. Closer inspection of the box doesn't show any broken seals, tapes, or stickers and the watch itself doesn't have any blemishes. It seems odd that there isn't a "factory seal" on the box. Perhaps a brand new box is completely wrapped in plastic. Not sure. Hopefully, this watch doesn't have issues. I selected this watch because, for decades, this model and the G-SHOCK line have had a reputation for durability. I can wear a nice watch for those occassions that warrant one, but I need a beater watch that can keep up with my everyday lifestyle. After going through a few $10 bangers and a Timex Ironman, I decided to spend a bit more on a more durable product. Despite being relatively inexpensive and primarily selected for functionality, this watch makes a little bit of a stylish statement, too. I like the looks even better than I expected. Time will tell on the durability.

Title: Great
Text: This was my first G-Shock, and I love it.  It's light, comfortable, keeps decently accurate time (about +5 sec/month, so far), has all the basic features one would need (alarm, stopwatch, countdown timer, perpetual calendar until 2039, etc.) and is built for survival.  This is a no frills, no nonsense, dependable, functional watch.  It also features the classic square Casio design, which is timeless, in my opinion.  I love the DW-5600E so much that I also picked up a DW-5025B on eBay.  There's not much more to say in the way of praise - the G-Shock series is well-established and respected. On to some other things of interest: The 5600E has a plastic case underneath the resin bezel, with only a metal plate screwed on to the back.  It's no secret that Casio stopped producing fully stainless steel watch cases for their G-Shocks years ago.  Now, only limited edition, anniversary edition, and other special releases include one.  Some have argued that the plastic case is more shock resistant in comparison to rigid metal.  I am a bit neurotic, though, so it only took me a week or two before I went crazy about this plastic case business - I buy watches to last a lifetime.  That may sound silly considering it's a $40 Casio, but it's not silly to me.  If this is a disposable purchase for you, forget about the case and enjoy the watch. Another note about the pitfalls of a plastic case: bezel and battery swaps pose an issue, because the tiny screws are seated in plastic threads.  It's entirely possible to strip the threads if you're not careful (and plenty of people have done it).  Of course, there are also stories about people getting screws stuck in the metal cases, as well.  Either way, just be careful and pick up a JIS screwdriver, because those screws are not Philips.  People seem to like Hozan or Wiha tool brands. You can attach strap adapters to the 5600E in order to use Zulu/Nato straps.  This is a good option because nylon straps will last much longer than the OEM resin strap, are much stronger, and, to most, are more comfortable, too.  Installing the adapters yourself can be a major PITA (I'm speaking from experience) - read around watch forums for accounts of this.  You could even end up breaking something if you're not skilled, so it may be worth taking your watch to a professional.  The adapters are available from Casio Parts Department directly - call 1-800-223-2001 and order part #74243710 (you'll need to order two because they don't come in a pair).  I spent less than $7 for parts and shipping, as opposed to some other sources online which charge over double that.  Maratac and Timepiecerepublic on eBay offer the best Zulu/Nato straps. Hope this helps.  Join the 5600 club and be part of a legend!

Title: Great watch
Text: I've had this watch for a couple of months now and I love it. It isn't fancy but it does what it's supposed to, which is tell time. I work on the roads and I'm outside in all kinds of weather. One day I may be clearing trees after a storm and the next I may be paving. I wanted a watch that was easy to read, comfortable to wear and durable to handle the weather of the PNW as well as my work. It is very comfortable to wear, probably one of the most comfortable watches I've ever had. I can read it in direct sunlight without any issue. Rain and mud don't bother it. This is my first G-shock watch and I'm very happy with it. If you need a tough watch that will hold up and is comfortable, this is your watch. No watch is perfect though and this wouldn't be a fair review if I didn't discuss the cons of it. The only con I have discovered this far, is the buttons. Particularly the button that is for adjusting the time. It is pretty difficult to press, I actually have to use my finger nail to activate it. Is it a big deal, no. But it is something people should be aware of. Setting of time is very easy and straight forward though. Another minor issue which might be of concern to some is the alarms. This watch only has one. To me that is fine, because I don't use watch alarms. But some people like them. So if you're someone that is a frequent user of watch alarms, this watch only has one alarm. Overall this is a great watch,  and is an excellent entry into the G-shock line.

Title: A wonderful tool with a built-in watch!
Text: The Casio G-Shock series debuted in 1983 in the form of the DW-5000C, the watch that started a trend that which become a cultural icon for many. The DW-5600E-1V is the latest iteration in the traditional 'square' format (it's actually rectangular) of the family. With a water resistance rating of 200m and the ability to withstand a fall from 10m this watch is more than able to take a beating, especially if you keep it on your wrist!  While it lacks many of the bells and whistles of the modern G-Shocks like atomic signal reception and numerous sensors the 5600 makes up for it in pure simplicity with a easy to use interface and quick operation. Each mode is accessed, like its brethren, by pushing the mode button in the lower left. The modes on this model include (in addition to timekeeping) an alarm, a stopwatch, and a countdown timer. The alarm can be set to a specific day or during a specific month (or specific day of the month).  The stopwatch will run to 23:59'59 (that's 1 second shy of 24 hours) with accuracy to the 1/100th of a second for the first hour. The countdown timer can be set from 1 second to 24 hours with an optional auto-repeat function. Current time is shown in both countdown and stopwatch mode, a feature sadly lacking in many of the newer models. There is, of course, a wonderful backlight function that lights up the entire screen making it easy to read even in the darkest of situations. It can also be set to light up when an hourly signal or alarm goes off (this is that symbol above the seconds display). The light is actuated by pressing the lower right button. This positioning is different from the older models but I personally find it more useful as operating the stopwatch and countdown timer is done through the upper right button, a much more natural feeling for those of us who are perhaps used to traditional chronographs. This is also how the watch is adjusted to display in 12h/24h modes (when setting the time). Speaking of adjustment, adjusting modes only takes a single press of the adjust button, much quicker than the newer models! Oh yeah, it also serves as a great watch too; mine runs within 1-2 seconds a month of UTC, pretty impressive for a watch that costs less than $50. Battery life is rated at 2 years but unless you're constantly using the backlight you should be able to pull at least another year or two out of the watch before replacement. The 5600 definitely has that 80s vibe going on so it may not be your desired fashion statement, but if you're looking for a tough, reliable watch you can't go wrong with this classic G-Shock.

Title: DW5600E-1V Module 3229
Text: After owning my Luminox 3100 series watch for the past 10+ years and only one battery replacement, the carbon/stainless steel bracelet clasp has started to fall off (failing to lock). I am not comfortable wearing a watch that I may loose due to a faulty bracelet clasp. The crystal is also scratched pretty bad and the numbers on the bezel have all but worn off. I know I could get a replacement bracelet for the Luminox and possibly a new bezel, but I want a no BS watch. My Luminox will be retired as my EDC watch. My search is over! The DW5600E-1V arrived March 8th and I have worn it non stop (except showering, I just don't like to wear watches in the shower, even though the watch can handle it). Coming from a steel bracelet I was somewhat worried that the rubber strap on the DW5600 would irritate my skin and cause it to sweat. No problem in that department. The watch is very comfortable to wear and much lighter than the Luminox, which I used to remove before bed. In my opinion the watch is the perfect size. Not to big, but not too small. Just right and doesn't infer with clothing and hanging up on things. The functions of this watch are PERFECT and they have been getting a good test. I like that the menu structure is simple and to the point...no BS. The alarm could be louder as I am a deep sleeper, but I don't mind and it has been waking be up in the morning. The back light is more of a green/blue, which is perfect to read the time or other functions in the dark. As with the other posts here I do feel the Adjust button is sometimes hard to press, but I am getting used to that. I just reach over with my thumb nail and press it and it works fine. This watch is Made in China and uses Module 3229 for the extended calender to 2099. Even though I would have preferred the watch to be made in Japan, there is nothing wrong that I can see with this watch in terms of function, fit, and finish. I set the watch to time gov and the DW5600 is exactly spot on accuracy wise. I know it hasn't been long enough for a true accuracy test, but I am impressed so far. I will be putting this watch to the test this summer in Montana and will throw everything I can at it. If it survives summer, we'll have to see how this baby handles a Montana winter :) In all for $40 you can't go wrong with this piece.

Title: IMO the best G-Shock you can buy(other than the solar version)
Text: If you're on the fence, just buy it. The price, features, design, and history make it an awesome piece for any collector. Whether you wear it a few times a week, or daily, it won't let you down. I didn't want a round G-Shock, and I wasn't ready to pay $100+ for a digital watch, so this was the best bet. It's thin and very comfortable to wear. I even sleep in it sometimes. I'm hoping that the strap holds up. I'm sure they make some aftermarket ones, but I like it as is. It keeps time very well. The watch has stayed within a few seconds since I bought it. I love the ability to make the watch beep each hour on the hour. It's full of features and has all the information I could need right on the dial. I'm thinking about giving this watch to my dad and getting the solar version that syncs. It would be the ultimate no fuss watch for daily wear, but for the price....this thing just can't be beat (maybe a Casio Duro?). I may eventually get a GA2100, but for now this is my go to digital watch.

Title: Best watch Ive ever owned

Text: Great watch

Title: The only “must have” watch, period
Text: I used to be a strong believer that there is no such thing as a “must have watch.” It’s a very easy statement to throw around, and if you bought every proclaimed “must have” out there, you’d end up with hundreds of watches, which defeats the purpose... But, believe me, this IS the must have watch. It’s perfect. It’s my go to now, despite having an Orient Kamasu and a Citizen Nighthawk, both of which cost 5 times as much as this one. I have a few Timexes, but this is in an absolutely different league quality wise. The Timexes always feel hollow and cheap. I also have other Casios like the World Time (AE1200WH). I used to think that if you had the World Time, you wouldn’t really need a DW-5600E. The World Time is less than half the price and has more features. But this G-Shock is an absolute classic. This is literally the same design and case as the DW-5600C, which was released in 1987! The only difference is that this has electroluminescent backlight (hence the E in the end). The dial is an absolute classic with the blue and golden text. Also, this cheaper $40 square fits me better than the solar $100 GWM5610. I like that one a lot too, but the shorter lug-to-lug on that one means the strap holes are either a tad tight or a tad loose, whereas with this one, there’s a strap hole in the sweet spot. This is truly the only watch you need. No watch ever deserves that statement more than this one.

Title: Really like this watch.
Text: Its the perfect size and price. Easy to set, read, and i dont really care if it gets destroyed at work. I have a few nice and expensive watches, none of which i want to chance sacrificing with a labor job. So this was great compromise.  Nice enough to not feel like an 8 yr old kid, and cheap enough its not a big deal if something happens to it. Looks just like (close enough IMO) to their $100 - $300 models, and i personally think anyone that spends $300 on the “Japanese model“ digital watch like this is just burning their money. I agree they look nicer than this, and may be solar - but Casio makes much better looking watches for that price. Its still gonna be a $300 watch that looks like like a $40 one.  Gonna buy the black “casi-oak” model too - but NOT on Amazon. Sellers here are price gouging - selling them at twice what the actual retail is, so look somewhere else first before you buy that one. Anyway - I choose to wear this one with the watch face on my lower wrist (palm side of hand). Even though its a pretty slim case, it still gets caught on jacket sleeves and backpack straps wearing it face up. Its actually easier for me to turn my wrist to read it this way anyway. If youre looking for a cheap digital watch that looks nice, isnt huge, is comfortable, and isnt childish looking - this is great option.

Title: The Best you can buy at 50$
