Title: Just a G-shock.
Text: As others have mentioned the buttons can be hard to access, especially with arthritic fingers.  I'm not a big fan of digital watches either, as they can be hard to read in certain lighting.  This watch is not a bad one, just didn't work for me.

Title: The best $40 you'll spend on a watch
Text: I wanted to start a watch collection after being reintroduced to wrist watches via smartwatches. I liked the Pebble smart watch, just thought it was ugly. I liked the Apple Watch, just got tired of worrying about the $600+ computer on my wrist being charged or getting scratched/too wet. I hunted like crazy for watches. I wanted an automatic so I tried a few Seiko 5's, a Swatch Sistem51. I obsessed over Grand Seikos, perpetual oysters, co-axial Omegas, any watch that NASA deemed durable and accurate enough for space and that's how I began my DW5600 obsession. I always hated G-Shocks. They look like toys. The glossy band finishes and bright colors often found on the newer models just scream "DUUUUDE". But this $40 baseline model, modeled after the early G-Shock models, is everything I'll ever need in a watch.  Its design is simple, giving you a glance at the day, date, and time in an efficient use of LCD display screen real estate. The rubberized casing prevents the casual scratches and impacts to the tough mineral glass watch face. For $40 you aren't getting sapphire. No big deal. Throw your sapphire watch out the window of the third floor of a building along with this guy and you'll see which survives. And me, I jump out third floor windows on the daily when I leave my soul crushing day job. As a person with smaller wrists, I'd say the DW5600 is the perfect G-Shock. Other newer and larger models have watch straps that just suffocate my wrist leaving a sheen of sweat hanging out between my wrist and the watch all day. The larger cases often bring more weight to the watch which makes the little nubs under the strap dig into my wrist. Not so with the DW5600, the watch balances itself on the wrist perfectly and has just the right weight to feel substantial and durable while still fitting under a shirt sleeve. Did I mention this watch does 200m of water resistance, anti shock and has been subjected to torture tests you wouldn't even imagine (just check YouTube. A guy strapped his to his bicycle wheel and went for a ride.) Anyway, I obsessed over many a watch. Ultimately, I can't see myself walking around every day with an invisible force field around my wrist trying to protect a Datejust from a random scratch. I can't work out, play with my dog, or do yard work while worrying about the escapement and paw wheel being babied. But for $40, this watch has set me free.

Title: Functional.
Text: Let me start by saying that I couldn't ask for more from this watch. It's perfect for every day use. Very light weight and very comfortable. Function are basic but for the price you can't ask for more. I love the design and looks good in my wrist. It's easy to read. This is my fourth G-Shock and again didn't disappoint me. Some people are complaining about one of the buttons, but to be honest you can still push it without any problem. Definitely recommend it.

Title: Received with package and box open
Text: package and box were open on arrival. bad look

Title: Sometimes Simpler Is Better
Text: I bought this DW5600E after my Casio GW700 started to go goofy on me.  My first 5600 survived 28 years.  I thought the GW700 would do the same or better, what with Atomic TIme and Solar Power, oh my.  Like most reviewers have indicated, after about a year and a half the back light (way cool blue) started coming on with minimal arm motion, which drains the battery.  The Solar Power became less and less effective, meaning the bloody watch wouldn't hold a charge, regardless of how much direct sunlight the watch was exposed to.  I'm a soccer referee (albeit in Seattle where sunlight is precious) and often on the pitch from dawn to dusk (which you would think would be enough sunlight to charge the bleeding battery.)  Instead, in the middle of matches, the entire face would go black while the watch communed with the radio signal in Colorado or something, for 10-25 minutes at a time.  "Ref, how much time to play?"  Uh, I dunno, and run over to an assistant referee and tell him to give me a sign for when the half ends. So I was in the market for a waterproof (it rains a bit in Seattle, eh?), blast proof (G-Shock), low maintenance, relatively accurate watch, with some kind of stopwatch/timer that was easy to use, and built without even a nod to planned obsolescence (Sp?).  You know, kind of like my first G-Shock. 28 years is longer than most marriages these days.  Anyway, I read a blistering review on Amazon from somebody that refocused my priorities: day, date, time, and timer function.  And forget about how easy it is not to have to reset the time when changing time zones or going on Daylight Savings Time.  Forget about Solar Power which only lasts a year and a half.  And forget about way cool blue, that energy-sucking vampire light. Most difficult for me was giving up on aesthetics.  My GW700 came with a black metal band, a low profile round case, a black display, and a raised cool blue metal face guard.  The 5600E ain't changed in years:  grey display, black display numbers and letters, ultra-thin low-profie rectangular box shape, and too many print sizes and colors cluttering up the display, making for an ugly grandfather when seen next to the GW700.  But it works.  Reliably.  On and off the pitch.  I don't need a piece of art on my wrist.  I need a watch with a stopwatch function that works under any conditions.

Title: This is a great watch
Text: This is a great watch. If you’re even reading this review and thinking about getting one, just stop and buy one now and be done with it. It’s possibly the only watch you need in a one watch collection. Just don’t work in a stuffy office, with stuffy people.

Title: It’s the toughest watch you can buy
Text: This is the toughest watch you can own imo. I purchased this watch May, 6 2016 and I haven’t even had to change the battery to this day. I’ve been extremely hard on this watch, it’s something I bought so I wouldn’t have to worry about scratching it all up in small spaces or smashing it against something. It’s survived grease and oil being all over it on so many occasions. When it’s dirty you can just run soap and water on it and it’s good as new. My Dad was a cop for over 30 years and he always swore by these watches and it easy to see why. Buy this watch and you won’t be disappointed.

Title: Still a fan after all these years - and it's still the same!
Text: I had a last-minute revelation that the cost of a new one would be about the same as a new (original Casio) band and the cost of the additional outer shield (which says "G-Shock) and a jeweler's labor. So I decided on simply getting a new watch, complete with strap, for just a tiny bit more.. I read the reviews first, some pretty scary in talking about non-stainless steel cheapening, or non-functioning ("overly recessed") buttons or faulty light. I'd say this under oath (and have no vested interest in Casio!) - I've had at least 3 of this exact same model over the past 3 decades or so. All the watches still work, even if a few pins and casings got beat up eventually. Two have had the batteries changed every few years and a new strap once a decade. This watch is virtually the same exact watch in terms of appearance and function. I was concerned if the calendar included the 2010's, but no worries there. Set it right up, tested that buttons and light-feature are working (they are) and the countdown timer too. Just now I set an alarm and it also worked fine, as always.  So that is my experience - an exact-same watch, my "old friend" for snorkeling and day-to-day work  - with stopwatch, countdown, and clock all working just fine. As for manufacture, my last one (whose strap and front harness finally broke) was manufactured in Malaysia, and the one before that in Japan. All are marked with the same model # (different factory codes) and this Chinese incarnation is marked "St. Steel" rather than "stainless" and a few other minor shifts in the back engraving (adding info on the shock casing too). But, so far, wherever it was pieced together or however the parts are procured, this is a standard-issue G-Shock Casio watch, so far exactly the same in appearance and function as my others. The last thing I'd add is about the comments on skin irritation. Well, I've at times ended up with a red or dry patch on my wrist (especially underneath, as I'll flip the watch to see the front when snorkeling/diving underwater). It's a big piece of steel which may get warm (not from battery; from sun or activity), and the steel back and/or buckle is what has sometimes done a number on my skin too. So I give it a brief rest. For the moment (two days constant wear), no irritation, no difference than any other Casio G-Shock. It's true (but no doubt individual) that the watch and band (bulky and metallic as they are) can cause a rash or dryness, "for some of the people some of the time", but I'm only one person. I don't think it's that common or so big a risk for most people. I wear this watch 24/7 (as it can shower or swim with me and I'm not connected to a phone). Love it still. Time will tell, but so far, so good!

Title: Made in China not japan
Text: This is made in China,  feels ok but not like the japan model

Title: This has become the only watch I use.
Text: Very durable. A couple of times I thought I broke it banging my wrist against something but wa la, it didn't break. I've washed it, got it wet several times and it hasn't damaged it. It looks rugged enough to wear for sports activities and fancy enough to wear for business casual.

Title: Sexy old-school Casio G-Shock
Text: This watch is a classic. Looks slick on the wrist, good basic functionality with no frills, comfortable enough to wear as a daily watch. I say comfortable "enough" because I find the strap to be slightly uncomfortable on my own wrist (I'd give the strap a comfort rating of 7.5 or 8/10). However, keep in mind that the watch is new, and because I just started wearing it, I want to give the band some time to mold a bit to the shape of my wrist. That might improve my comfort rating (and if it does I'll give this watch 5 stars as well). Other than this minor issue with the strap, this watch is great. I don't wear bulky watches and what I really like about this G-Shock is its conservative size: it fits great on my smaller wrist. Not too big, not too small. I can wear this watch with confidence with anything, like t-shirt and jeans or with a suit and tie. Some highlights: - Classic timeless design that I really love. - Time, day, day of the week are all displayed on the main screen. - Current time is displayed in both the stopwatch and countdown timer mode. (Great to be able to see the actual time while I'm jogging.) - Has one alarm that will ring for 20 seconds. The volume is not very loud but no weak either. (Loud enough for me.) - The top left "Adjust" button is recessed. Many people (especially those with larger hands and fingers) report having a hard time pressing this button. (Not a problem for me.) - Bright light. - Keeps accurate time. - Solid build quality. If you're looking for a great looking basic digital watch, this is a great choice.  If you're looking for a watch that gives you more functions, get a different watch. I needed a simple but solid watch that delivers accurate timekeeping. I also needed a stopwatch feature to time my jogging routines. That's why I chose this model. Glad I did! --------- UPDATE: November 20, 2014 - I'm still enjoying the watch. But keeping it at 4 stars due to my continued discomfort with the wrist band. The strap is noticeably uncomfortable on my wrist...even a bit more so than when I first got the watch. I'm downgrading my rating of the wrist strap to 5/10. I plan to get a more comfortable strap for this watch (one that makes my wrist feel like I'm not wearing a watch).

Title: Overpriced buy the Casio DW290 instead
Text: For anyone searching for a basic Casio digital quartz watch you may want to avoid this DW5600E-1V. I purchased one recently directly from Amazon and here is what I found. The good: Yes, it is a G-Shock, it does have a comfortable strap, it fits a medium sized wrist very well, it has a low profile (easy to wear a long-sleeved shirt over the watch), and the medium font size is easy to read. The very bad: The watch is overpriced at $75 (retail). This watch should retail for $35 due several issues.  The four control buttons are a joke, the mode button is unusable (required a pen tip or the like to operate), the other three buttons are nearly unusable, they are not user friendly at all. The green backlight is not bright enough. Also, the display/glass does not appear as clear as another Casio watches I own. I would expect this watch to be durable and last for years if not decades like my 28-year-old Casio DW290-1V. After owning both and comparing both side by side I wish Casio would combine the good features from each watch to make a great watch. Simply combine the blue backlight, display glass and the control button action/size from the DW290 onto the DW5600E case/strap, I would pay over $75 for that watch. Included are side by side pictures of my DW5600E (purchased in October 2022) and my DW290 (purchased in October 1994). The DW290 has a new replacement case and band, but the display, internals and case back are original to the 1994 watch.

Title: Old School
Text: Who doesn’t love an old school looking watch. I always wanted one of these as a kid and now I wear it daily. Great watch!

Title: El más clásico de los G-Shock
Text: Excelente reloj, es el 2do 5600 y no me canso. 100% recomendable y el menosprecio prestaciones en este tipo de reloj

Title: Great watch.  Band is short.
Text: I've been wearing this style of watch for approximately 15 yrs.  It is much more durable than the Iron Man or similar watches.  I work in a physical environment and it has taken all the punishment I could give it.  I have also worn the watch while covered in mud, snowboarding, scuba diving and all kinds of other outdoor, hot, cold wet and/or rough activities.  Again, the watch keeps working great.  I also like that it constantly displays the day of week and date on the main display.  I also like that it does not have a lot of useless display items that distract from the time/date.  It may not be a "fashion" watch, but for the money it’s most reliable and durable watch you will find. Downsides - The battery will usually last about 3 yrs.  When you change the battery it is difficult to reseal and maintain the waterproof integrity of the watch, be very careful taking it apart and putting it back together, don’t tear or install the o-ring wrong or it will leak and the watch will be destroyed. Only other issue is the watch band.  It holds up fine for a year or two, but then the rubberized band can start to crack where the buckle tongue sticks through.  This is why I eventually had to buy this watch...  I tried to buy replacement bands, but they are almost half the price of a new watch and the replacement band reviews all seem to indicate that they are all "almost" like originals, but shorter or don’t fit quite right (my old G-Shock is 4 yrs old and still on the original battery so I figured I would just get a new watch and not have to change the battery soon) and the reviews.  So I bought this watch, and guess what... the band is a full inch shorter than my old watch!  Very frustrating.  I can wear the watch, but it is hook on the next to last hole, but this barely allows the watch band tail to be tucked under the retaining loop.  I don’t know whey they are now making the bands shorter, I can only assume that Casio is trying to save a few pennies on rubber... Because of the shorter band I am giving this 4 stars instead of 5.

Title: Pinches my hairy arms
Text: Its comfortable, I slept with it on my hands numerous times and Its OK but what I don't like: 1. the straps pinch my hairy arms (this is why I took off 2 stars because it hurts!) 2. the light doesn't stay on long enough so I have to press it multiple times

Title: Great watch for $38
Text: The watch is great. It feels great on the wrist. It’s very light weight and looks fantastic. The watch strap feels a little flimsy, but is comfortable. It does fit well under the sleeve of a dress shirt. I love this watch and wear it most days. I also own a steel dive sd1970 and seiko snk809. I prefer the feel of this watch. I have purchased a nato strap conversion kit for this watch, but have not felt the need to keep it on. This strap really is comfortable, and looks retro cool.

Title: Great beater
Text: Dope

Title: Tough everyday watch
Text: This is my everyday watch. I can work, play, run, swim with it on my wrist,  knowing that it's super reliable. I got the same watch for my son too. The top left button is hard to press, but I don't mind that. This watch looks great with any kind of attire, except maybe for very formal situations.

Title: It's a G-shock.
Text: Light weight, comfortable strap, easy to read. It's a simple G-shock for everyday use. I think everyone should have one of these.

Title: Excellent all around watch.
Text: This is a great all around watch. I can read the digital numbers easily and I just push the bottom right button to light up the display in the dark. Used the watch on the job as an industrial instrumentation and controls technician to perform field checks of timing on equipment. Tough and reliable watch. Tried many other watches but returned to this one. I am sensitive to metal on my skin so I put some cloth tape on the back of the watch to protect my skin which solved the problem.

Title: Has cheaper resin band
Text: I have purchased this same watch from a different store 01/2021 and there is a difference in the resin band material. The resin band on the Amazon version feels cheaper and smells compared to the other. For a minute I thought someone had switched bands and returned the watch but I compared it to a coworkers watch that was purchased on 8/15/22 and it the same. Compare the bands in the pictures. The Amazon version says made in China on the clasp and the other day made in Thailand. You can also see the factory stamp code numbers are different. There's also a color difference I was going to return it but I got for $25 with a coupon and  plan on changing the strap but I like to have the original.

Title: Great little watch
Text: I bought one for myself, then bought 3 more for gifts

Title: It's decent for the money. Not as good as the one I had in the early 1990s though.
Text: it's almost but not quite as hefty and rugged as the one I got in about 1990. And I wish this one had the same amber light that that one did because this one has that indiglo thing that interferes with night vision due to blue spectrum. But the one I got back then was more like $80 which would be a lot more in today's money. It lasted over ten years on the same battery and when the band finally wore out and the plastic broke apart, I should have just replaced the band and the battery but I got rid of it. Wished I hadn't, that watch was epic. This one is a less robust knockoff, still good for nostalgia but I don't expect it's going to have that kind of staying power. Still, happy I bought it.

Title: El mejor reloj digital retro de la historia
Text: Este G-Shock es probablemente el mejor reloj digital de la historia. Por menos de 50 dolares puedes tener un reloj con mecanismo cuarzo japonés resistente al agua de 200 metros y que aguanta múltiples golpes.

Title: Thing HONKS
Text: Best watch you can buy. Throw it off a cliff. Bang it into things. Go swimming. It don't care what you do, it still works

Title: Maybe the only G-Shock you ever need.
Text: This DW5600 is almost perfect. The case size is right. It's weightless. It's comfortable to wear. It keeps the time right. It might be the only G-Shock that you need. I also own the G-Shock 5610 model. The 5610 has tough solar and is radio-controlled. But are these features really necessary? With tough solar, you don't have to worry about the battery. The multi-band radio makes the watch always accurate. But with these features come hassles: you have to wear the 5610 properly to expose it to light; but you can't expose it in direct sunlight for too long or leave it on the dashboard of a car. What would you do with a 5610 on a beach in a sunny day? With 5600, you just don't have to worry about anything. The cons with 5600: The day-date section could have been smaller to make space for the time display so that the time is easier to read. The display is less crisp than the 5610 or even cheaper models.

Title: Perfect Durable Watch
Text: I bought two of these watches back in 2009. One for myself and one to give as a gift. Almost three years later these watches are both in great condition. I'm very hard on my watches, and almost every watch I have owned in the past has been broken through normal daily use within a year. This is usually due to me accidentally smashing the screen into something, or from an impact due to it being dropped. This watch has survived three years, and it still looks like new. Pros: Incredibly durable - This thing has been dropped, scraped, slammed, and thrown, but it's survived everything that I've thrown at it. Perfect size - Some of the watches on the market today look like you are wearing a wall clock on your wrist. This watch is perfect. It's big enough to read, but small enough that it doesn't look odd. Nice feature set - This watch has a nice basic set of features. It doesn't have any of the more advanced features like atomic time keeping, solar, etc. However, this means that the price is low, and the battery life is much longer. So far I haven't had to replace the battery after three years. The watch face is recessed into the watch - This for me is a huge plus. I've always had an issue with other watches getting paint on the crystal due to me accidentally scrapping them against painted walls. With this watch the screen is recessed into the body of the watch so any paint is transferred to the outer casing. This is easy to clean off, and keeps the watch screen looking great. Cons: I can't find a perfect hole in the watch band for my wrist. I fall somewhere between two holes on the wrist band. One of the holes is too loose, and the other is too tight. However, this is most likely a personal issue, and I do prefer my watch to fit a bit looser then most. Overall I am very happy with this watch. I recommend that anyone looking for a durable digital watch to give this one a look. In the future I want to try some of the other G-Shock watches available, but for now this one is perfect for my needs.

Title: Bad A**!!!
Text: I’ve wore an Apple Watch for several years. Feels great to go back basic and solid.  Al a man needs for a day to day watch.  Looks retro but so perfect.  Tuff as anvil and I catch people looking at it all the time. Lol

Title: perfect inexpensive but durable watch
Text: I am very happy with this watch. my last two watches were smart watches and very expensive, neither of them lasted more than a year and always required charging. This old school item is just right, tells me the time and date. I have so many devices that can receive texts and do all kinds of other stuff so I am finding I really like not having a smart watch, it is nice to not get notifications on my wrist.

Title: Good basic watch
Text: I had the first  / original g-shock back in early 1980’s.  Recently I was wearing my expensive tag-heuer watch but I needed something for when I went to the beach, fixed my house or car, etc..  So I got the current version of g-shock and …. I’ve stopped wearing my tag-heuer watch altogether. Also my g-shock keeps excellent time.

Title: ... this is my 3rd G-shock watch and probably my favorite. Since I'm getting older I decided to get ...
Text: So far this is my 3rd G-shock watch and probably my favorite.  Since I'm getting older I decided to get a classic time piece from Casio, you can't go wrong with the 5600 series.  Very simple design with all the basic functionality of a digital watch. I'll start off with the fitment.  If you have a small wrist this would be the ideal G-shock for you.  It doesn't look like a clock on your wrist like some of the other trendy G-shocks out there.  The watch is very light weight and the strap doesn't seem to irritate or get in your way if wore a long sleeve over it. Functionality of the 5600 is basic, keeps accurate time, has alarm, timer, back lit, count down, military time and tells you the date.  If that is all you need then this the watch for you.  Setting the watch is pretty straight forward, no need to read the manual.  I did get stump on setting the day but if you set up the year probably that will solve the problem.  Watch is very easy to read but then again my vision isn't bad.  The back lit lights up the whole screen not like some of the other G-shocks I own. Although I haven't had this watch long enough I can say that this watch is tough like any other G-shock.  I workout 5 days a week, work on cars, cook, and pretty much everything in between and this thing still looks new.  I will follow up on the review once I reach the 1year mark which I think is critical. Overall I'm happy with my purchase.  I do regret not investing a little more and purchasing the model above this one.  I think its the 5610.  I like the feature of having solar powered and atomic clock however paying twice as much at the time I didn't think it was worth it.  I did deduct 1 star but not because of the product, shipment took longer than I expected.  Not a big deal, so get get yourself one already!

Title: Nice
Text: Very happy

Title: Works
Text: I love G-Shocks. They’re tough and they’re practical

Title: hard to set
Text: hard to set

Title: Good watch for its price
Text: Watch offers day, date and month, along with a light.

Title: Repackaged.
Text: Cool watch, but it came repackaged in a crushed up cardboard box. Would have been nice to get a brand new one.

Title: Classic - Great Watch!!!
Text: Classic Casio fits my smaller wrist just fine, not as bulky as some other GShocks, that's a good thing. Update: after eight months of owning this watch I upgraded my rating from four stars to five stars. After decades of catching the bargain casinos (they work great) on sale for around 20$ I finally upgraded to an affordable G-Shock. No noticable scratches and the band is holding up just fine. I bought three and returned two I liked this one the best. I just ordered a 6900, we'll see how that goes. The other two were 9052 variety similar to the 6900, but the 6900 is supposed to fit better. This is my favorite watch, it has the perfect balance of bulk & comfort close to perfection. I liked the bulkier 9052 but it was no where near as comfortable, the only advantage was the light button front and center. The 6900 is going to have a tough time replacing this as my favorite watch, doubt it will happen, Absolutely great and closest I've seen to perfect (for me) watch.

Title: Unbelievably Durable
Text: I bought one of the early G-Shocks in the 1980's... and it lasted through 2006 -- over 20 years.  The plastic outer case finally started to deteriorate... and oh yeah I tore or lost the strap retaining loop about 10 years ago (no big deal just put on a tie wrap and kept on wearing the watch). To put this in context, I use my sport watches for sailing, boating, diving and snorkeling (usually in salt water) ...and most other watches have lasted only 2-3 years.  The amazing thing is that I never replaced the battery on this original Casio G-Shock -- it just kept working until the casing finally went. Only slight disadvantage for sailing races it that it doesn't have a synch feature for interim starting signals.  But other than that all the functionality that you really use is there *and* you don't have to read the instruction manual to figure out the watch... user interface and buttons are straightforward and obvious. Classic bulletproof sport watch -- highly recommended.  I'm searching for a yellow one just like my old one, and will buy it immediately if/when I find it (may have to settle for black though). One other thing -- I'm a lefty and unlike other watches, on the Casio G I never had a problem with accidentally tripping the buttons -- as is common when you wear a watch on your right wrist (reaching up and back with your hand can press the watch buttons against your upper arm and on some watches this causes a button-press). ********************************************************************* Update based on over four years with my "new" Casio G-Shock -- When I wrote the review above about my old original yellow Casio G, I wondered whether the then-currently available G-Shock would really be as bulletproof as the 1980's original... glad to report that my now 4 1/2 year old "new", black Casio G is running just fine, still on its original battery, and having had more use and abuse than the original in the same time-frame (including plenty of saltwater immersion).  What a rare product -- one that was great when it first came out and appears to live up to that legacy in every respect 25+ years later. ********************************************************************* Update at the 7 year mark with my "new" Casio G-Shock -- watch is perfectly fine (daily use), but as of March 2015, the band cracked on one side at the usual adjustment hole, so I've ordered a new band -- readily available on Amazon for the DW5600E and currently priced at $17.

Title: In less than a year watch function to change/update time does not work.
Text: Purchased March 2022.  Cannot change time.

Title: Great original model
Text: Great watch. I’ve been wearing one for years. I bought a new one to replace an older one but they are very durable.

Title: It's a G-Shock
Text: Build like a tank, functional, easy to read, water resistant and full of features. It's a G-Shock alright, what more could you need?

Title: A classic with a single niggle
Text: As a watch collector with many mechanical watches and a couple of G-Shocks I did want to add a DW5600 to the collection. It's a great piece, works great however on mine the adjust button doesn't work without using a pen to push it in further. Apart from that a great buy.

Title: Solid watch for everyday use.
Text: I have had several G-Shock watches over the past 30 years,  these things hold up well to everyday wear and tear.  I spend most of my day working with my hands,  these get knocked and banged around regularly and hold up.  I have fancier watches for when the occasion requires a dress watch but for everyday this is perfect.

Title: Qué más se puede decir de este reloj...
Text: Yo creo que los Casio G-Shock son, en mi concepto, los mejores relojes que tu dinero puede comprar. Baratos, buenos, resistentes, de marca... tantos y tantos buenos adjetivos calificativos que faltan para describir esta pieza clásica de arte y resistencia. Si estás pensándolo todavía, no te demores, cómpralo y ya, y disfruta de uno de los mejores y más clásicos relojes que la ingenieria japonesa te puede brindar.

Title: great watch
Text: This is a birthday present to my husband. He had a GShock years ago and loved it!

Title: Good for price
Text: Have to use a pin to adjust the time as the button is really pressed in tight. But once set it's a good watch for outdoors or work or play. I like that it's easy to read and has a classic look.

Title: Going strong since 1998.
Text: Since 1998, I've replaced a few bands, a bezel and some batteries. It's simplistic, incredibly durable and a no nonsense time piece. My old man wore the original for years and I wanted one exactly like his. Albeit it's a tad different. A true test of durability........the band broke when I was shoveling snow and I lost it in a snow bank. About 4 months later, in the spring. After the snow melted, I found my watch along the side of my driveway. It was still working. It sat outside for about 4 months in a Minnesota winter. And if you know anything about Minnesota winters, it get extremely cold. Like 30 below cold. It worked for another 5 or 6 years on the same battery after that. It won't win any beauty contests but neither will I. So I don't really care what it looks like. It'll survive anything you will survive. And probably through things you wouldn't survive. 24 yrs on my wrist nearly every day and the other day I noticed that the light and the alarm have quit working. Still keeps time just fine but I work midnights so both those things are pretty important. I just saw that they make this watch in a solar model. That will be next one. I hate change, so as little change as possible, the better.

Title: Casio G-Shock Men's Classic - The "A" button is really hard to actuate.
Text: I've worn this model of G-Shock for decades, and purchased a new one to replace the previous one that I finally destroyed.  My only issue with the new watch is that the "A" (adjustment) button seems to be much more difficult to depress and actuate than my previous ones.  I even set up a return for the first new watch I had received, because I thought it was defective.  The replacement watch was just the same, i.e., the A button didn't seem to work, so this time I tried really pressing it in with my fingernail, and sort of rocking it back and forth, and lo and behold, it did finally work.  With that technique, I could also adjust the first watch I had received.  So, it seems to be a new feature for this model.

Title: Display goes to blank screen
Text: Purchased this watch January 2020. Within the last month the display goes blank then returns after several minutes. I'm afraid it's about to crash for good. Unfortunately I'm several months pass warranty.

Title: Great G Shock watch...
Text: It arrived fast with Amazon prime shipping.  I synced it up to my phone time and it is going on 4 months and has only gained 1 second...I thought watches might lose seconds and probably do but in this watch it is still right on the money.  I have bought I think 6 of the imitation cheap ones and they are way off... Some gaining 30 seconds in a few days and some losing 30 seconds in a few days. So I guess you get what you pay for.  I don't consider my wrist all that large but the only thing I am not thrilled with is the size.  I looks like a Unisex watch....A man or woman could wear it.  I don't know why Casio doesn't keep the same look but make it larger for us slightly bigger guys and the face slightly larger for us older guys with less than youthful eye sight..But it is a great watch....I can imagine the Tough solar one that syncs to the Atomic clock would be spot on time... For $41 it will bring joy to anyone needing a tough watch that will keep them on time.

Title: Can handle abuse!
Text: Daily use for a retiree, the watch is great. I had one for fifteen years that held up to all kinds of abuse and one before that while working in a steel mill and that one worked great.

Title: Very tough
Text: I've worn used only G-shocks for more than the last (Wow) 30 years (going on 40).  Hard to believe they've been around that long.  Very dependable.  I usually replace them when the outer cover gets mangled - probably had three in that time.  This last one I wore while welding and and didn't have it covered by my glove - well lets just say it got weld splatter on the glass, but it still reads and functions fine.  You can barely tell there is splatter stuck to the glass unless you tilt it and the reflections show it...

Title: Just Perfect
Text: So far have had this watch for a few weeks and love it. I have gone swimming in it and sweat a ton while wearing it and also just got it wet in the sink. It keeps kicking and I love how simplistic it is. Would 1000% recommend and buy again!

Title: Conked out after 4 years
Text: Kept good time but buttons were always hard to work.  Lately, watch resets to Jan 1 midnight on its own.  Expected better.

Title: It's a legend, but the pushes are just too stiff
Text: I thought I would add a classic G-Shock to my cheap watch collection, but I found the pushes, especially the one at the upper left, to be too recessed and just too darn stiff.  I could only press that one with a pen or a punch.  How useful is that when you want to reset your stopwatch or ?  Regretfully, I sent it back and ordered a Casio Men's W800H-1AV for about a third the price.  It's still more rugged and water resistant than anything else in my cheap watch collection (by a long, long way) and I don't plan on running it over with a 23 ton truck anyway!

Title: Iron clad super watch
Text: to be honest Ive had allot of g shock watches and  Timex watches in my lifetime. I really love them. I bought this watch because of the great ratings it had received and it was only $40. I  normally use a GWM850-1cr for the atomic /solar features to keep time dead on everyday. Im a medical courier and i need to have exact time especially for clocking in because we have only a 1 minute window to swipe our cards, also it helps me keep on track as far as my route.  This batch of watches are  2011 models and i found out the batteries last more than 2 years so when i got it, it was very easy to replace the battery.  since i received the watch on feb 19th 2013 I have been checking  it against the atomic watch i have and in 20 days it has NOT lost or gained one second. this is by far the most accurate non atomic watch ive ever had and ill be turning 45 this year. It has a great  24 hour timer, a multifunction alarm that i really like because it has such versatile settings and it works everyday. This watch also features a bright green back light , 200meter water resistance, a stop watch and a very nice thin rugged design that gives me the assurance it wont break even if you abuse it. I think the only con is the adjustment button takes a little getting used to because it is seated a little deeper than it should be. I love the watch so much im wearing it everyday now. i would recommend it  to anyone without reservation .its just a plain simple, easy to operate g shock watch  that you would have to out right abuse to  tear  it up so it gets 5 stars from me. If it every goes bad im buying another one immediatly.

Title: toughest watch ever
Text: first got one when I was 18 back in 1987  lasted until I was 42 in 2012 watch still worked but case around watch had broken off over the 25 years I had it.  Threw it away because it was pinching my skin.  Have tried many other brands last 10 years Timex, Invictia,  and citizen all have died over the years.  Just gave up and this year I just bought the orginal G shock only difference is the Glo back light. (the one in 1987 had a light bulb).  love it today for an every day watch as much as then

Title: Adjust button is way too hard to push
Text: Love the look of this watch. Classic, square design and it wears well. Unfortunately, the adjust button is so hard to push that I have to use a pen or other object to set any functions, making the watch only suitable for wearing if I only need to see the time and date, and not use the stopwatch, alarm or countdown timer. Otherwise it would be perfect.

Title: James Bond should have had one of these.
Text: I now own the toughest, most popular G Shock watch, which has all the functions I need, and will most likely outlive me.  I was able to set it up without referring to the manual, with just a few functions like split time etc that might need a bit of study.  Thank you to Amazon for selling it to New Zealand, most Casios are off the menu here, and we have to pay ridiculous prices.  But your price is good value.  This might not be perfect - my W 215H has a clearer screen for example - but one look and you know everything you need to know.  No fancy altimeter or barometer, or digital compass, or anything else that can go wrong and put you in danger.  Anything I can possibly imagine doing, and many others besides, I know this watch will take a beating and be there for me. But... I have to admit, since the arrival of my Casio W800HG, that little rascal has hardly ever been off my wrist.  It is smaller and less noticeable than the DW5600E, but has the same sort of presence, and the gold accents make it stand out visually.  I still can't get over the fact that my watch tells me what year it is!  The alarms work well, the buttons are easy to press (unlike the DW5600E), and it is so comfortable I wear it like a second skin.  I just leave it on and wash around it.  There is a 10 year battery so I have no qualms about checking the time in the dark whenever I want.  It has survived numerous unintended impacts without scratches or damage.  I plan to share wrist time with my impending Casio MTP1339D-7A, which should arrive later this month.  One analogue, one digital, one happy camper.

Title: Gotta love the "Classic" G-Shock look - a throw back to the original G-Shocks and simpler times!!
Text: First off - I bought this for my son four years ago.  I bought him two G-shocks, and he religiously alternates them day to day - so this G-Shock has been worn at least 182 days a year, times four, or roughly 730 days.  What is amazing, is both G-Shocks, including this one, look darned near like the day I bought them.  My other son (his twin brother) also has two G-Shocks of different design with the same result - both look like new, still working with no battery changes needed.  Plus, we are talking about boys now going on 17 years old, so they wore these from the ages of 13 to 17 - tough years for any watch, and the G-Shocks passed the test with flying colors. My son picked this for its basic, classic look.  I love it for the same reason, it takes me back to the days where G-Shocks did not come in 500 shapes, designs and colors.  This is the classic design and look, and that appeals to my son (and me).  This does not have all the fancy features like more expensive models - no temperature, no barometric pressure - but it tells time, and fits on the wrist without getting in the way.  Don't get me wrong, we have all in one watches that DO have fancy features (I personally own two Suunto, Garmin, Mudman and more) but the purpose of this G-Shock was something simple and elegant. I give G-Shocks the highest recommendation.  Kid tested, they keep ticking and looking like new for years and years.  They are literally bomb proof.  Oh, and I own two Mudman G-Shocks myself, and love them.  Same deal - they just keep working!!! THanks for reading.

Title: Good watch, but...
Text: I bought this because I needed a rugged, durable and simple watch. Nothing fancy just need to be able to tell the time and date. This is slimmer than the other G-Shcok options so it sits comfortably on my wrist and when I bend my wrist it doesn't dig into my hand. It also doesn't make a weird bunch up effect when I have to wear something with a cuff. But why the three stars? Well it is the "Adjust" button. It for some reason is recessed well into the watch. I'm guessing this is a factory defect because I don't exactly see the reason why it would be set so deep into it. I only adjust the thing twice a year so I don't see this as being too much of an issue but it does interfere with some of the functions like the alarm and stop watch. It doesn't completely stop me from using them but for those with sausage fingers (such as myself) it makes it a chore to use it. For the price I paid, I'd like some better quality control, so that's two stars subtracted. I'm not going to tell you to not buy one of these because it is a solid time piece but I'm an honest guy and this is an honest review.

Title: Keeps on tickin'
Text: This is my 8-10th G shock in 25 years, ever since this model was released.  I originally used it for SCUBA diving as the timer used as a dive timer was excellent and it did get to 130' and it kept ticking...so it is waterproof and at least to that pressure though I don't know about testing it to 330 meters! Every one has performed flawlessly.  The reason for replacement was that after so many years the rubber casing disintegrated or tore away...no issue there. These watched took a beating in gardens, gyms, diving, fixing cars...you name it. I usually replaced the battery once in a 3-5 year use before I had to release the watch. I did buy one of the camo style G shocks at Christmas this year and returned it...Couldn't see the display and while it looked cool, it was useless for its intended purpose. This G shock has all the right functions that you may want and are easy to use.  Favorite feature is the backlight which you can actually see compared to other watches. I love the stopwatch feature using it regularly.  The alarm is easy to use and loud enough to wake me up without being annoying. Casio used to have a double clock feature so when in another time zone you could set it...guess it was too expensive to add or not thought to be of value.  So, I like the time display, stop watch, timer feature.  I don't use the countdown often, although it is helpful if doing some cooking or something like that.  The watch is the correct size and is unobtrusive.  If you want to show "bling" get something else, this watch does its functions flawlessly. All in all for the $45 or so dollars, you cannot beat this watch.

Title: Nostalgic 🖤
Text: Excellent

Title: El mejor reloj - The best watch
Text: El mejor reloj que existe, debido a que es súper cómodo de llevar, la pantalla es de fácil lectura y la iluminación por electroluminiscencia es clara y cómoda. Además, es un G-Shock. The best watch that exists because it’s super comfortable to wear, the dial es easy to read and the electroluminescent light is clear and comfortable. Additionally, it’s a G-Shock.

Title: Trust Your Gut
Text: This is the G-Shock in its classic form.  Like it or not, it is as every bit iconic as Rolex Submariner and Cartier Tank, though I doubt its die-hard fans hardly care to make that comparison.  They are fiercely loyal to the watch for its own merits and rightly so.  It’s rugged and functional with nostalgic good looks and a clean, well-laid out face that is free from all the 1990s Pontiac body molding add-ons that clutter so many other G-Shock designs. And there’s something comforting about this watch.  The design has been around a long time.  When you wear it, you feel that you’re wearing something special, something with pedigree.  I guess some might scoff at that, but the revolutionary role of quartz in the history of horology is undeniable. And how many other groundbreaking designs from the quartz explosion are still in production? Is it the best sports watch out there?  No, I don’t believe so.  Timex Ironman has a more intuitive layout for athletes.  Timex’s 150 lap and 250 lap tap screen Ironman Sleek offerings are about as good as I believe you’ll get in a non- GPS runner’s watch with its enormous face and interval timer flexibility.  However, I always think twice before taking an Ironman in the water—never with a G-Shock. So should you buy it?  It’s largely a matter of taste.  It’s certainly affordable enough, robust enough, and functional enough to justify the purchase.  But the design can be a little polarizing.  Frankly, I love it, but I have a nostalgic attachment to the watch and nostalgia can be a powerful thing.  Try one on and if it speaks to you, go for it.  You’ll have to trust your gut on this one.  You either get it or you don’t.

Title: It’s a G-shock!
Text: First one for me. It’s great. It’s plain. But it’s very light and seems sturdy. Clear and easy to read. The illumination feature works and looks great. I wasn’t sure if I would like it but the more I wear it the more it grows on me. Probably going to get another one being a watch guy like I am. If you’re on the fence about g-shocks in general like I was, start with the inexpensive one like the 5600 and check it out. I’m glad I did.

Title: Great watch
Text: This watch meets and exceeds all my expectations. I've done a lot of research on this watch and with almost of a month of wear I am ready to give this a solid review. I saw a need for a wrist watch in my life so I impulsively bought a nice 150 dollar Seiko. I wore it for few days and it did look good, but I felt that I had to be careful each time I moved my wrist. I needed a watch that I could throw on my wrist and not worry about it. I returned the watch and began looking on amazon for a digital watch. I wanted a stopwatch, timer, and alarm. I almost pulled the trigger on a basic Casio that wasn't a G-Shock. I read a review that said "Not a G-Shock, but that ok!" and I wanted to see if it really was ok. Boy am I glad I did. This watch has everything I want and performs just a well. I won't repeat what functions this watch has, but I want to mention some things that are not apparent. Most Casio watches have the stopwatch, alarm, and countdown timer function, but they all differ in little things, such as some watches you can set the timer to seconds and other you can only use minutes. Some of the more expensive watches don't show the current time in stopwatch or timer mode. This is a drag! It's really convenient to just leave the watch in a mode and still be able to see the time. With this watch you are able to see the time in all modes except alarm and able to set a countdown timer with seconds up to 24 hours. What more do you need? Its a great watch at a great price that I am sure will last a very long time.

Title: Gift for my dad
Text: This is the only watch my dad wears. It got here in perfect condition. He will be excited

Title: Simple and efficient watch.
Text: I've been looking for a clean and simple digital watch and this G-Shock fit the bill.  I don't like the oversized watches since I can't wear them while I work, but this G-Shock is thin and does what I need. And it was a good deal.

Title: Budget watch exc
Text: Works great, looks good, handles water well and visible in rain/dark conditions. I wear it daily and so far it’s survived drops, spills, banging without any issues. Try it out.

Title: Great watch
Text: Fantastic everyday watch. 1 second fast after 4 months. Does everything I need it to and for the price you can’t get a better watch that will withstand the abuse this one goes through.

Title: Amazing all purpose watch
Text: I really wanted to hate this watch, I thought the whole idea of digital watchs was kind of childish but after purchasing this watch, it's the only watch I'll wear now. There is just something about it that I just can't explain. The watch tells amazing time it's never been off, the functions are super easy to use and with the water resistance of 200m this thing can do anything. It'll probably last a life time and then some. Also the resin strap and case are super comfortable. This is the watch to buy if you're looking for that one and done watch. It does everything you would need in a watch and then some.

Title: Light weigh and thin
Text: Light weight and thin

Title: Good quality
Text: Really good watch! Worth every dollar

Title: Survived Army Basic Training and Afghanistan
Text: When I joined the US Army we were given a cheap army branded watch to use. It sucked. It didn't survive a week. I wrote home and weeks later got what I asked for. A Casio g shock, the same model the I saw many others in my platoon use. It survived thousands of push-ups on pavement, dirt, rocks. It survived low crawling hundreds of meters through thick Georgia brush. It survived all the mud, sweat and moisture and bangs the army could throw at it. Now it's in Afghanistan with me. It's comfortable to keep under the cuff of my OCP uniform. You will forget it's even there. I though about swapping the band out with a nicer one but it's really not needed, it's durable and comfortable. I never take it off, wear it in the shower and never had an issue. Before deploying I swam in the ocean with it and worked fine. If you need a watch that can survive any life style this is the one.

Title: It’s a Casio
Text: Love this watch! Then again how could you not. It’s a Casio

Title: Tough everyday watch that's built to last
Text: This is the first G-Shock that I've owned and decided to purchase it based on its popularity. Not only has the DW5600E been around for decades, but the design and functions have remained mostly unchanged. It's a tough watch that's comfortable to wear and will handle just about anything you'll encounter day-to-day. It's a no-frills watch for sure, with a few functions that give you just about everything you need (12/24 hour time and date display, backlight, timer, stopwatch, daily alarm, etc) and nothing you don't. With 200M of water resistance, you can also swim/shower with the watch on and not worry about it. The only gripe I have with this model is that the "Adjust" button is a little difficult to press at times. The button has been recessed so it's almost flush against the watch housing. I did some research and found out this is done intentionally to prevent the button from being pressed unintentionally. It's a minor complaint though. For $40 or less, I think you'd be hard pressed to find a watch with as much durability as the DW5600E. Recommended!

Title: Es muy bueno calidad casio muy liviano y cómodo
Text: Es muy buen reloj liviano versátil tiene lo necesario en su justa medida, la luz es estupenda

Title: Plain Jane
Text: I don't normally review products, but I want to caution other buyers about this watch. I read the reviews and based on those that said it lasts, I was sold.  However, having received it, I see now why the cost is low.  By today's standards, this Casio is the size of a child's watch.  It is small and the read out is small.  I am a tall lanky fella with skinny wrists and this watch looks like I borrowed my 6th graders watch.  It is a G-SHOCK, so my hope lies in the longevity.  However, not sure I will be wearing it.  Great gift for a young man 12-16 years of age.

Title: Great value watch for all seasons!
Text: Excellent sturdy watch like many claim. I went with it and am very happy with solid performance. Pricing and Quality cannot be beat. Pros: Sturdy Great quality Running good so far (time values are still matching - so accurate) [no other tests ran for accuracy ;-)] Habit to keep watch on - so goes with me everywhere - showers, hiking, sports, work. screen is tough. Cons: Feels bit stodgy first on hand but I got used to it quickly. Font on screen bit small and can benefit raise by size [or my eye number increased ;-)] but cannot complaint too much as all required stuff is visible. Not auto-lit at night. [nice to have feature but does not claim to have too much bells and whistles in first place] All in all - solid watch for price - worthy companion in most normal situations.

Title: Great everyday watch, slightly uncomfortable.
Text: I like this watch a lot. It has a classic look to it and is very functional and tough. My only complaint is that is as a little uncomfortable while wearing a coat. Also, the strap is proprietary so you can't swap it out readily. Luckily there are adaptors for that.

Title: Utility Above Anything Else
Text: This watch is made for everybody, but probably isn’t for everybody. It’s functional, easy to use, durable, and can really take a beating. But, if you’re wanting something that “looks good” you might go in a different direction. Personally I have other stylish watches that I never could find reasons to wear. I have found that this watch is easy to go to day after day, and does just what I need it to do.

Title: Replacement for the exact same watch I had for more than 13 years
Text: Works just like my old one which worked fine and lasted a long time.

Title: Inexxpensive, rugged, no frills watch
Text: This is exactly what I was looking for in a watch.  I used to use $10 walmart specials and they would last a year.  I just wanted something that wasn't huge on my wrist and didn't have all the bells and whistles.  I use the alarm and timer function regularly and everything works as expected.  After getting banged around for 6 months the watch has held up great with no scratches or anything.  I would buy another one but I don't think I'm going to need to.

Title: Reasonably priced awesomeness!
Text: Comfortable & not too large..,.and with an adapter …different band options.  Original band okay, yet I prefer something other than black... Adapted my down to 20mm which has many options that are normally for smart watches.  Durable, functional and color!  Dig it!

Title: CLASSIC
Text: This is a classic standard Gshock. It's great. It looks classic, feels comfortable, and works exactly as it should. Starting with this base model Gshock to see if I wanna go for more. So far, I'm very pleased!

Title: Still a good watch after all these years.
Text: I've owned these for about 30 years now...The original referred to as the "TUNA CAN"  had a screw on back and was the best and I only had to replace that one after 19 years of use as the watchband pin broke and it fell off my wrist while motorcycling and I could not find it after I discovered it missing...I really miss that one. JAPAN does offer that one in a special edition (Must be ordered from JAPAN) but it cost's $300 now rather than the $40 I paid for mine in 1988... The second one I owned lasted 10 years and it was the newer type with screws. Not as water tight as the original and not as high quality but still decent and holds up to abuse. It eventually finally died at 10 years. So I'm on my third one now. The newest one seems slightly more accurate gaining less time than my last model so that might be an updated chip or just luck. I ordered this basic one after looking at the model that goes for around $100 which has solar power and atomic clock sync. But after reading reviews on that upgraded model a lot of people have stated they need to leave that model on the window sill to sync with the atomic clock at night due to weak signal and the solar charging seems to quit at about the 10 year point and that's what these new G-Shocks seem to be good for life-wise about 10 years so might as well go for the much less expensive basic model at under $40,

Title: Typical G-Shock bulletproof reliability
Text: Based on many reviews and YT videos, I added an ‘old school’ G-Shock to my Casio collection. This watch is simple and affordable, and has the timer, alarm, and hourly signal features that I needed. If you want to add solar charging and atomic clock synchronization to a very similar watch, you can spend about $100.00 for the GWM5610-.1, It’s got the typical G-Shock reliability, and this watch is great

Title: Muy bueno excelente precio
Text: Excelente reloj

Title: Great Diver's Watch - Highly Water Resistant and Tough
Text: I am giving this watch 5 stars because it is exactly like one that I had before (as far as I can tell).  I have been buying Casio G-Shock watches since 1982, when I first started diving in the Virgin Islands.  I had a couple of other diver's watches before, but they always seemed to develop leaks.  I bought one similar to this in St. Thomas and never had any more problems.  It is supposed to be good down to 200 meters.  I can't vouch for that, but I have had it as deep as 120 feet a number of times in the VI, Hawaii, and Australia, and it survived them all.  That watch lasted until the mid 90's, when the hard plastic started to break down and come off, but it still kept on ticking (actually, until about a year ago, and I think it only stopped because the battery died).  I should note that I am hard on watches.  It addition to diving, water immersion was always constant as my job entailed fish culture.  They also take a beating physically.  I replaced it and it's successor lasted until a couple of weeks ago, when it actually died at 14 or 15 years of age (not the battery this time). The batteries all had extremely long life, at least three or more years.  My only complaint about the last watch was that it gained a second or two per day.  The watch has a lot of useful features which I will not go into.  I did have to replace the band every two or three years. It is my fervent hope that the watch that I just bought lasts as long and performs as well as my previous ones.

Title: This a classic G-shock that every man should own.
Text: What can you say about the original G-shock? It's an amazingly tough watch for a fraction of the cost of anything comparable. This watch is a great beater watch to take hiking, swimming, mowing the lawn, etc... It does everything well and I don't worry about banging it around or getting a scratch here or there. There are hundreds of G-shocks available at a wide range of prices. I like the classic style of this watch and for the price I paid, if I were to lose it or damage it in some way, I would surely buy another one.

Title: Great buy for you money!!
Text: Great quality time piece, easy to use in all functions, water/shock resistant. This is the upgraded model of the original  from the 1980's commercial. Wore this for several years, mid 80's to early 90's.

Title: Love this watch!
Text: Classic Gshock never gets old. Got my first gshock when I was  about 15 yo... had it for about 10 years and then lost it. 20 years later I  purchse the same model with the backlit ffeature. Love it.

Title: Nice and Sturdy
Text: Although I had bought this for someone else, it's my pleasure to report that the recipient likes this watch. Casio's watches are nice and having an affordable, durable, and light option makes this a great gifting option as well as an everyday watch. That said, I'm definitely going to purchase one for myself in the future of a different color.

Title: It’s a G Shock - so how bad can it be
Text: I work in the fire service and our profession is generally rough on watches (and everything else). So far a tough watch after 3 months. I like that it’s a slimmer profile than most g shock watches. Simple with not a ton of unnecessary features. My only gripe is that the stop watch/ timer reset button is a pain in the ass. It’s recessed into the watch unlike the other buttons. Upside is you won’t accidentally reset. Downside is you need to have an implement handy to reset times. Not a great problem to have during workouts. Generally stoked about function and durability. My last one stuck around 5 years. I expect the same from this one

Title: Does What I Bought It For
Text: I bought this so I don’t bang up my better watches at my job. Functions great for that. I’m going to get a strap adapter and put a nato on it for warmer weather because the OG strap doesn’t breath. Easy to read. Back light works. Simple functional digital quartz watch. If you want something down the same aesthetic but a bit more upscale, check out Hamilton.

Title: Nice watch, but ergonomics were unacceptable. Dang.
Text: I love every thing about this watch, but it didn’t work for me. I simply couldn’t operate the upper left (“A”) button with my finger, either on-wrist or off. The button didn’t stick out enough, so I couldn’t push it in enough with a fingertip to activate the “adjust” function. Using a fingernail worked, but only if I took off the watch. Using the tip of a pen worked really well, but I don’t always have one at hand. I don’t know if I received a defective product (not likely), or my fingers are just not shaped as Casio expected. In any case, I returned the watch to Amazon (easy process) for credit and bought a GWM5610-1. Twice as much money, but the GWM5610-1 is solar powered and the time is updated every night by radio. I love my new GWM5610-1, and the return transaction was easy, but the disappointment lingers. Am I the only one to have this problem?

Title: Such a great product
Text: The title says it all

Title: The ultimate dad watch.
Text: For work and exercise I use an Apple Watch, but for EVERYTHING ELSE, this is the best, most durable, and  affordable watch you can get. The perfect ‘dad’ watch. This is the watch I’d bring into the zombie apocalypse.

Title: If you can only have one watch, this is it.
Text: This watch is perfect and has been for decades now. You can beat the heck out of it and it still looks and works perfect. I get complements on this watch constantly. Everyone loves it. You can wear it while working in the yard or to a black tie event and it’s never out of place. If you don’t have one, get one. It’ll pay for itself in no time.

Title: Perfect watch for me, but with one caveat
Text: The top left button which is the adjustment button is beveled to be made hard to press from the factory. I need to constantly adjust my timers in clinic. I needed to cut off a tiny piece of the G shock protector from the 5 o clock position to 7 o clock position under the tiny  "adjust" bevel with an exacto knife. Once I did this I was able to press the adjust button with no problem and with light pressure. Perfect watch with perfect function for me as I needed both a countdown timer and a count up timer. I have had this watch for 6 months now and it has been my favorite Casio watch ever. 6 months in my only complaint is that the alarm sound is starting to get a bit weak, but I use the alarms probably like > 30 times / day. So my watch gets heavy every day use.

Title: Does What I Need
Text: I used to use watches when I was younger but as I got older and got a phone I never really needed them. I recently got a job my first job and thought it would be good to keep track of time easier with a watch instead of reaching in my pocket all the time. I looked around and read this is a basic model that is sturdy and will last in my job. Does what I need, more than I need with the countdowns and stop watches. I like how it has pre-programmed dates that I used to have to change if the month didn't hit 31 on previous watches. Comfortable enough, I can feel some edges in the straps but they're not cutting in or anything. I thought it would be a large watch and be sort of encumbering but even while working I forget it's there and is a good size. The information says "accuracy of +/- 15 seconds per month" not sure exactly how that's measured but I synced it a couple of times with my computer and it actually gets ahead or behind 4-5 seconds in a day. I don't know if it loses some on one day then gains it back the next, but right now it seems to be a lot less accurate than that. I don't need the accuracy that much but it would be nice if my watch was more true to what the information says. I would definitely recommend this watch to anyone who needs just a base, sturdy watch with no crazy features. 11/28/22 Edit: The battery just died within the last day or two. Still been wearing it weekly and using the stopwatch.

Title: Great for smaller wrist, reliable and well-worth the cost
Text: I am now on the third one of these (5600E) watches - the first went to an avid outdoorsman/survivalist friend who was previously "anti-watch" but loved this one enough for me to give it to him, the second went to a UPS driver friend, and now I have my own. Nothing to say at this point that hasn't already been said by the 600+ other reviewers other then personal testimonials, pretty much.  As so many others have affectionately said, this watch has "just the basics" - in a good way!  It's all you need in a watch, and you can change or activate settings or modes easily on the fly. I have fairly small wrists, so in comparing the sizes of G-Shocks this one was the closest to my other watches, and so it doesn't look overly-big.  Subtle yet definitely present.  The design and color look retro-cool, but as another reviewer said, "bullet proof."  The backlight glow is also subtle but works very well. Bottom-line: This watch is well-worth the money.  I haven't used it in hardcore ways as many others have (I have a desk job) but when I have gone on camping trips it is nice to have something so reliably-solid but yet so light on my wrist, when we're out hiking with and against the elements.  It worked fine under the water in a hot tub (the backlight looks cool underwater).  It's also good for jogging.  Or if you just feel like wearing a fully-functional watch that doesn't look as pretty as dress watches but has everything you need at a glance.  You truly don't have to worry about the wear-and-tear at all, and that is very nice.

Title: Fits very well
Text: Great watch for hourly time watch

Title: Great durable watch
Text: Nice G shock for a great price. Very durable watch. Easy operation as well. I bought 2 for myself.

Title: Husband loves his watch
Text: My husband uses this watch for work days. It’s a great durable watch and looks nice.

Title: Insanely practical
Text: Right now I think that this is my favorite watch.  This stems from it being a great value, retro cool looking, and just very practical.  I believe this is the cheapest G-shock you can buy and the one that looks most like the original from 1983.  Despite the price it's water resistant, has an anti-bacterial strap, and is nearly indestructible (ok I haven't actually tested that last part yet).  However, what I'm really enjoying about this watch is that as a timepiece it is so practical.  The main screen shows you the day, date, and time to seconds.  Everything you need is there and it's all so readable.  To top it of the backlight is fantastic so you can get all the same information in the dark.  The only thing that I don't like about the watch is that when you switch out of the basic time mode into one of the other modes (alarm, countdown timer, stopwatch) the four buttons aren't well labeled so you have to remember what each one does in each of the modes.  It's not really intuitive there so I'm knocking it down one star.  That said 99% of the time I just use this as watch and for that it is great.

Title: The quintessential G Shock...
Text: I hope this helps anyone who cannot decide which G shock to buy. There are a few hundred different models of G Shock watches out there. I own a few of them, and they are all great. They are all tough as nails, extremely accurate, and are nice looking, especially if you appreciate gadgets and technology. If I had to choose only one model, it would be this one, the DW5600E. It is simple to set, and has all the information you need at a glance. No need to push the button multiple times. It's all there. It makes sense!! It looks nice with everything you wear, and the band is soft, but tough, and very comfortable. (Theres a time, and a place for expensive dress watches.) With the price Amazon charges for this model, you really won't feel bad about abusing this piece, and believe me, it can take it!! Please, do not think because the newer models have atomic/solar, multi-band, blah blah blah, they are better. I will say they are more expensive, and bulkier, but definitely not better. Interesting technology, but gimmicky at best. If you treat this watch normally, and limit the use of the back light, the batteries last 5-7 years or more, very easily. Once the watch is set, it is extremely accurate, and may lose seconds over a LONG period of time. If you want to pay more for new features (atomic) that are not necessary, go for it. I learn the hard way that sometimes less is more. In this watches case, it is. I wear all my G's from time to time, but this one is on my wrist 90% of the time. Once you figure out that this watch makes the most sense, there's no turning back... NASA and the military can't be wrong about this model. Buy one already, you won't regret it! Oh and if you have your eye on another G, go for it!! In the end you'll wish you bought this one...

Title: Reliable and versatile
Text: Comfortable fit, and versatile when considering wardrobe. I enjoy the features that are given, they are fool proof! Thanks.

Title: Bullet proof watxh
Text: This replaces the same model watch I've had for decades. The old one finally broke. I get about 10 years per battery.

Title: Quality watch, smaller display
Text: Said it all with the headline.  Otherwise a good watch

Title: Excelente calidad vs. precio
Text: Excelente para el diario, lo uso para correr, ir al gimnasio, MTB, incluso nadar, la calidad es muy buena y es bastante simple, cumple con las expectativas.

Title: Solid Performer
Text: I've worn Casio watches for more than 20 years and have always found them to be entirely reliable, easy-to-use, and very functional.  This is my first G-Shock.  In the past, I've favored the less expensive and smaller sports model.  I never had one that failed and the battery life was quite remarkable.  Their only weakness was the band which always failed in two to three years.  Sometimes a crack in the band will appear before it breaks.  Sometimes not.  Most recently, the little loop on the band broke, rendering it useless.  Given that the loop is not under any significant "stress," the materials used might be at fault.  I was going to purchase a replacement watch of the same variety (the cost is just a little more than a replacement band), but the latest model of the sports watch did not have a countdown timer, a feature that I really value.  (I fly quite a bit and like to set the countdown timer at the beginning of my trip to keep track of the flight time.) I've had this model for about 3 months and have been very satisfied with it.  It gains about 10 seconds per month, but it is relatively easy to reset.  The band is sturdier than the band on the sports model, but I suspect it will fail before the battery needs to be changed based on some of the previous reviews.  It's easy to read, has all the basic features I need, and is not as bulky as I expected, even on my small wrist.  It feels very comfortable, no less so than the model I have worn in the past. All in all, it's a solid performer.

Title: Simplicity and durability
Text: That's all I wanted, simplicity and durability and that's exactly what I found in this watch. For the price, I have no second thoughts about strapping it on and doing any kind of work or play that could damage it. Also let's face it, it's kind of fun having a watch that still looks like it's right out of the 80s. So far one of my favorite features is having an easy to use count down timer on my wrist. Sure I have one on my phone, but this is right there on my wrist at all times and it's come in handy multiple times already in the short time I've had it. Comfortable as well, I couldn't remember how comfortable the wrist straps were and thought maybe id have to buy something nicer, but nope, this feels great and doesn't dig into my wrist. I can already tell it may be a bit of a gateway drug into some of the other g-shock watches, but for now, this will do just fine.

Title: Thanks to  user reviews I picked the best watch (out of a dozen)
Text: I knew I wanted Casio (timex was my main brand before but got some absolutely rubbish watchpieces from them), I owned a g-shock in 2004 didn't realize it was casio, liked it then, so I was considering about 10 different casio's (almost all g-shocks).  I read the Perth,Astralia "personal perfect watch" review and heard about how that guy had purchased all the expensive top of the line models and I realized that makes sense, this simple one has all the featured I'd need, is fantastic price.  It's reliabel, awesome, just like the review said, fantastic interface.  It's a "junk free" watch.  No superfluous alarms, It operates exactly how woudl expect a watch.  And I don't expect a watch to have a helicoptor pop out of it and be able to cook dinner!  IT tells the time, has a chrono, countdown, alarm (impressively that can be set at ANY date and time, like I can set a monthly alarm, or an alarm for say 3:03 pm December 02 or some precise date and time which i don't recall ever seeing before on a wristwatch.  Not sure how much I'll use that, but if I do, I'll prob heed the alarm more instead of wondering which random alarm I forgot to turn off is going off? The only other features I'd like on it would be accurate temperature (this is rare on watches though because of body temperature, so I don't expect it) lunar would be a nice touch with sunrise sunset, but again those could be a headache possibly and may not be ideal. Vibration alarm I also REALLy like and would like to see that on this.  But basically zero complaints. marvelous little durable watch. simple and efficient!

Title: Building block and stepping stone to a G-Shock addiction
Text: The Quintessential small square for the frugal/economy budget minded square! Simple and as functional as it gets. You want an inexpensive watch that could last for a decade or more? well this is it. I own many Gs....GA2100/2110, GA700 and GA800 series being the best in my opinion (ana-digi) easier to read at a glance provided you have a good dial-hand color contrast. This one has all the necessary functions without solar ....which in this style of watch would be the preferred choice but you'll spend a little more. If you add a Stainless or Titanium case (a $50/$150 upgrade) you'll have yourself a watch that looks great and will likely last a bit longer....not to mention appear to be the "full metal square" GMWB5000 Series which cost from $400-$1000 from Casio but you spent $100 on it!!
