Title: SIMPLE BUT GOOD
Text: VERY NICE AND DURABLE,IT FEELS GREAT ON YOUR WRIST

Title: Runs a bit fast.
Text: Have had this watch for several years and never a problem except that it is always 2min fast. I'll reset it to actual time but somehow it speeds up by 2min and stays. But great nonetheless.

Title: Gshock value watch
Text: This watch is much lighter and it feels slightly cheaper than the more expensive gshock of this series. However, its very comfy, its a classic watch. I own 2 other gshocks.  For the price... you cant go wrong. Its a good buy.... no, great buy!

Title: Works as it should.
Text: I have been buying the Casio that uses a radio signal to set the time, but the last watch I bought with that feature no longer automatically sets the time. As there is no other way to set the time, the watch is useless.  This watch is rated for diving and has manual time set. It's what I need in a watch.

Title: G shock Value
Text: Best $45 watch you can buy.

Title: Excellent
Text: My husband has worn this particular watch for years. Battery life is excellent and band is durable .

Title: Nice for the money
Text: The watch does everything that I could want it to do and was an excellent value. I look foreword to many years of use and abuse.

Title: Crumbles Cookies Guy
Text: I used to have this watch years ago, and have purchased the same one again.  I can't seem to find a multi alarm watch that is medium sized, so I went with what I know is the best for the money.  The price was very reasonable, compared to the higher end watches that are huge and harder to read.

Title: Classic, reliable
Text: Great watch for the $.  Have different Casio's and they are all great.  Mudmaster next

Title: Very Impressive
Text: Two years now wearing this watch almost daily. It's truly an invincible piece of time-telling technology. It's simple and rather timeless in it's design (retro is always in), but is also functionally impressive and comfortable. My only advice is to take it off when you shower. Otherwise, I've taken this thing into unsavory climates and many unpleasant scenarios; it looks and operates like the day I bought it.

Title: CLEAN look. PERFECT SIZE
Text: If you work security or any job requires you to wear a watch, I HIGHLY RECOMMEND this watch. It’s perfect. Comfortable. Does what it needs to do and it’s to tell time ( both 12hr and 24hr) and date.

Title: Great if you want G-Shock but not a hockey puck on your arm
Text: Best basic digital watch there, except for maybe the non-g-shock digital.  If you want g-shock but not the girth of some of those monsters, this is a great watch.

Title: Simple appearance, reasonable design
Text: When i got the package from amazon, i am satisfied with the packing, filled with some small foam to protect the watch. Simple packing, but complete. Have a instruction, a international warranty card, a watch support and a watch. Multifunction design can meet  my most demands. But, a little bit pity, maybe the long location, a tiny trace on the watchband. Generally speaking, this is a great watch, cheap price, and best design.

Title: Casio basic diver's watch is a good value
Text: The Casio DW5600E-1V has been on the market now for a number of years.  The watch is typically accurate within about a second per week or better.  This model has good (inexpensive lithium) battery life of several years, and is highly water resistant. Swim with it, no worries!  Watch is durable and comfortable, and RELIABLE.  Price was right at well under fifty dollars, shipped to your door.  Recommended !

Title: Daily watch
Text: Purchased watch for work and I have enjoyed it so much that I wear it everyday. The watch feels very comfortable on the wrist and looks great. Would highly recommend watch if you want a durable and reliable watch.

Title: This is one of the most comfortable from all of the G-Shocks
Text: I am quite a big fan of Casio G-Shock watches. This is one of the most comfortable from all of the G-Shocks. It is a workhorse and perfect under all circumstances. Highly recommend.

Title: Great watch. Very slim
Text: Great watch. Very slim. I own a 6900; pretty much same watch. I got this because it was slip in and out of my jacket in the winter time. Sometimes with the 6900 I'd have trouble getting caught in the sleeve trying to put a jacket on. Nothing serious but I like the look if this watch. I'd love a rangeman for the summer time.

Title: Fantastic!!
Text: I've been wanting this watch to add to my collection for some time now. Not flashly not expensive or over dramatic, just a simple watch with simple functions and features. Highly recommended for anyone looking into getting a watch or a collector to add to their collection.

Title: Just Perfect!
Text: Fit, finish and quality far surpassed what I expected.  Highly legible readout. Just enough features to make this G-Shock fun and easy to use.  I highly recommend ordering one.

Title: The watch is perfect, if you perspire in warm weather & do ...
Text: The watch is perfect, if you perspire in warm weather & do any sort of heavy physical work the perspiration will kill the band, that is the only draw back.  Must have a sturdier band.

Title: A Great Everyday Tough Watch
Text: I've worn this almost daily for three years during my day job, hiking, running, working in the garden, 5 Everest expeditions and while snorkeling with rabid barracudas in Bali.  It still looks great and cleans up good as new.  If I ever lost this watch, I'd probably cry, beat my head against a wall, then immediately purchase another.

Title: Great watch
Text: Very reliable. Battery life is excellent. Very durable

Title: Great watch. Plain
Text: Great watch. Plain, simple and to the point. As stated in other reviews, the reset button is recessed in the body a little bit, does make it a little difficult to hit that button with your finger or fingernail.

Title: Good but band is too short.
Text: The watch is great but the damn band is too small. I have small wrists so i can’t imagine what some other guys are having trouble with.

Title: I Suggest One Of the Better G Shocks
Text: I think it’s probably a very good, dependable watch for the money. However, I returned it because it seemed light, and just not the hefty, impressive watch I really wanted. I very much like the more expensive G Shock I replaced it with.

Title: Perfect for Military Use
Text: I bought this watch because I need one for AFBMT and my recruiter told me to buy the simplest watch I could find that can go into 24h format. Instead of buying some $10 watch, I decided to buy one that will last me a few years. One other important detail about this watch is that it always shows the time no matter what setting you're on in a small box in the top right corner.

Title: In action
Text: Lost 1 bought another

Title: Simple and easy
Text: Hardly anyone needs a $200 watch that tells you what time it is in paris or displays what altitude you are at.  Most of the time, those functions fail to work, and anyone that is an avid hiker or traveler would probably invest a descent gps device. so that is why I chose this watch.  It is just a simple yet reliable watch with a few basic functions that are usable.

Title: Great for gym
Text: Great buy

Title: Four Stars
Text: Great watch, holds up amazingly - only issue is the lack of timer.

Title: I never have to take it off
Text: I'm very happy with my Casio G-Shock it fits my wrist perfectly and it's easy to read day and night. It is also lightweight and not cumbersome.

Title: Great value
Text: Exactly what I was looking for.  Just a tough inexpensive watch i can use at work.  Most watches dont last more than a month or two.  We will see how long this one makes it

Title: Simple and Functional
Text: I love the simple features of this watch that get you the information you want at a glance.  If I need more I'll go to my smartphone.

Title: Great Value for your money
Text: works great, water resistance for sure and looks very nice

Title: I'm rough on watches
Text: I don't try to trash them, it just happens.  This watch, however, has held up remarkably well.  I have a small scratch on t he crystal, but that's it.  It gets washed when I shower and goes swimming when I do.  Goodness knows that it gets banged and vibrated a lot, but this watch has literally put the "takes a lickin' and keeps on tickin'" back into watches.

Title: Great all around watch
Text: Very comfortable in size and to wear. A great all around watch for work or play!

Title: Coolest watch
Text: I really like this watch just feels like a retro look to It

Title: I have old eyes and it's a bit of a ...
Text: I have old eyes and it's a bit of a sstrain for me to see the time unless I put my reading glasses on.  Wist it were a bit bigger

Title: Best Watch I've ever owned
Text: Does everything I need it to, nothing I don't, perfect price point, can't complain.

Title: Serves it’s purpose
Text: It does what it’s supposed to. keep accurate time water proof It takes some decent abuse

Title: Can't beat this watch and price!
Text: Replaced my ancient Casio which I had for over ten years.  This is a tough watch, and a great price.  Everything worked great and easy to program- a little tricky to set the DAY of week, I still don't know exactly how I managed to luck onto it.  Keeps accurate time, which is the most important feature for a watch, right?  (Duhhhh) The illumination really powers this puppy up and is very easy to read in dark.  Highly recommend!

Title: First drop and it failed me
Text: Reason for three stars is because, yes the watch works and it has a nice look, but the first time I dropped in within the first week of owning it it bugged out. An alarm went off, it froze, and all the settings were reset. On top of that a weird ooze came out of the face of the watch. I'll most likely be returning it even though it still kind of works.

Title: Practical and Stylish
Text: Truly appreciate the style and features.  Nice display and accuracy.  Nice to be able to se the date and time displayed clearly and no need to analyze minute/second and hour hands

Title: Classic quality
Text: My dad had this watch back in the day and gave it to me in the mid 90s. I wore it until it got water inside and quit working. I was glad to find they are still making it so I ordered one right away. Other than the EL backlight, it is identical to the older model. It is my favorite everyday go-to watch!

Title: Good work watch
Text: I'm a welder, I wear the watch to work every day! Nice classic g shock

Title: Great Watch That Has Everything I Need And Nothing I Don't.
Text: Love this watch. Love the retro look to it. All the features are simple and easy to use. It's built like a tank and is not oversized like many of the G Shock line. I can wear it with a dress shirt in the office with ease. Excellent value. I own a Breitling Chronomat as well and since I've purchased this watch I have really enjoyed wearing the Casio every day.

Title: The Best G
Text: Excelent G-Shock, the best G

Title: Good watch - except for one issue ...
Text: This is a great watch but one big issue: It never breaks, battery runs over 7 years, works in swimming, steam rooms, sauna.  It will even survive if you run your car on it. Other than this issue - it is a great watch

Title: feels cheap. returning
Text: I already have a G-Shock with atomic timing and solar power, but I really just like number display (I don't like the clock-arm style of my current one), so I gave this one a try. It was disappointing soon after I open the package, since the materials (including the metal knuckle, the plastic band and the metal back) all feel inferior at least one level to my old G-shock.It actually feels more like the $13 Casio watch I bought for my little cousin. I am happy the size and look, but the construction makes me wonder whether it will last.

Title: Besr Quality Digital Watch for The Money!
Text: Top quality digital watch, including timer, stop watch, 12/24 hr time modes, alarum function, and backlight for night checks.  I b have owned one for decades.  Battery lasts 3-5 years.  Hard plastic band lasts 5-8 years.  Battery replaceable.  Waterproof to 200 feet.  Shockproof. Highly recommend!!

Title: Time Display Is Too Small!
Text: Nice looking watch, feels solid, quality seems OK, booklet with instructions is good. My problem with the watch is that the time display is far too small for me to read without glasses, even in daylight, (even more impossible in the middle of the night when I wake up) and the illuminated display doesn't help.

Title: OG G-Shock
Text: You can’t beat the original G-Shock. As seen in the movie SPEED. It works when fancy smart watches won’t.

Title: very nice ！ I'm a diesel operator
Text: very nice ！ I'm a diesel operator ,i work on the petroleum platform. there is oil and diesel oil around me. the watch fit in perfectly in this work environment.  just it not as big as you think.

Title: No Frills Casio
Text: I owned this model for 3 years before the band finally gave out.  I just jumped on amazon and ordered another one as most of the bands I saw were 15-30 dollars.  I'm a military guy and this watch has always performed as I needed it.  They are durable, simple, and effective.  I would reccommend and I will most likely order another one in a few years.

Title: It's a casio g-shock what else can one say.
Text: This watch i have on my wrist every other day, be side my timex marathon watch, excellent trade off, both 200 water proof.

Title: No bells and whistles.
Text: Nice durable inexpensive watch, display is easy to read and was even able to purchase a screen protector. Has every thing I need to tell time and date!

Title: Poor G-Shock
Text: Sorry, this item just is not the quality that I expected in the G-Shock line. I have two, that still keep great time, but can't find a replacement Bezel and band to replace them. Needless to say I have had both over twenty years! This one I just received and will immediately send back is not the same as previous. I immediately notice the flimsy nature of the band...HORRIBLE!! As I stated I have two others that have cracked rubber bezel and strap, so I know what it should feel like and the quality of the strap / band is very poor. I have already started the return process without any hassle from Amazon. If your an old school G-Shock person, and you buy this one because you think it will replace yours--- Please Don't, you will be disappointed. If this was Casio's way of saving money and keeping this particular line going, you fell short-too bad.

Title: buen reloj, mal boton
Text: muy buen reloj, buena calidad, diseño y funciones...lo único malo es que el botón de ADJUST es muy difícil de apretar

Title: Reliable, even after 5 years of everyday wear!
Text: I've owned and have worn this watch daily for 5 years now and it is still running strong. It's been on me through thick and thin. I work outdoors so it's endured through the elements - rain, impact, altitude, mud, dirt, you name it. Definitely worth the investment, would give 10 stars if I could.

Title: Great watch for work
Text: I have been using the DW5600 series of watches as a work watch for 15-20 years or so and they hold up well. I work in the oil and gas drilling industry and these Casio watches hold up very well, no matter what you throw at them, be it drilling fluids, oil or extreme vibration. As long as Casio makes this line of watches I will use them for my work watch.

Title: Well made watch
Text: Overall this is a simple durable watch. When i received it in the mail it was in perfect condition without issues. It took me 10 minutes to sync my watch with no issues or complaints. Granted i have not yet tested the alarm im confident it functions properly. I wear this watch to work and it serves its purpose so i would highly recommended this to anyone wanting a simple casual watch.

Title: It's a winner!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!
Text: Fantastic watch!!!!! If you're in need of a watch then Please do not hesitate. Buy this watch TODAY!!!!!  They say my review has to be longer so I'll just keep bragging on this watch. It's lightweight and you really don't know you're wearing it. Please, as I've already said, if you need a watch, BUY this ONE, NOW!!!!!!  I hope you all have a Very Blessed Life,  Jerry

Title: This is a great watch.
Text: I bought this in 2009 - still has original battery and time stays accurate.  This watch has even come back to be more of a trendy item since my purchase which is fine with me, despite the fact that I bought it for the utilitarian aspect.  I have this watch on nearly every weekend and sometimes during the week when I'm not in the mood for a dressier watch.

Title: favorite
Text: this is the third or fourth casio g-shock i've owned. Always been satisfied ... until this one arrived and i had a terrible time setting the correct time. the "mode" button (the one on the upper left when looking at the watch) is not responding when i press it. it seems to be stuck - it's not sticking out as the other three buttons. I had to use a screwdriver to press it in order to set the time. i'd send it back but have no other watch to wear at this time!

Title: GREAT WATCH
Text: Just recieved it today. Looks way better in person, was hesitant to buy, but glad i did

Title: Dependable
Text: I received my first G shock as a Christmas gift when I was 11..I’m now 46 and I’m on my third one..So to say the least they last!!

Title: It’s an Awesome watch
Text: I absolutely love this watch!

Title: Great daily if you don’t mind battery changes
Text: Excellent beater watch. I do have regrets though for not buying the solar version. But if price is something you consider heavily then this is your watch.

Title: An Ok watch.
Text: Is a good watch at a nice price.  Only have a complaint for the seller.... they need to pack this item better.  My package was a sad envelope and the box came out of shape.  It WAS going to be a gift, not anymore.

Title: Solid functionality.
Text: Great watch for work. This is my 2nd. The 1st still works after 10 years but the band is finally dying. Use it swimming, fishing, construction work, salt water & freshwater... Great value.

Title: What more do you want?
Text: It's a rugged, reliable, no frills watch. It does the job. Nothing fancy. Think of it as a tool that'll never break on you.

Title: Very durable!
Text: My boyfriend had this watch for 4 years until he lost it! He loves it so much I bought him another one!

Title: Chinese made
Text: Had this same watch for five years.  I’m a rancher and I like to hunt and fish.  It gets a lot of abuse.  This new one seems to be the exact same watch.  Gave it a 2 because it is made in China.  Didn’t realize that before I bought it again.  I will look for something else next time.

Title: Very Practical Watch
Text: I've owned this watch for about two months now and I could not be more pleased. I swim, play basketball, and weight train on a regular basis and this watch has stayed on my wrist the entire time. I agree that the countdown clock is a great feature to have, especially to make one's workout time more efficient. I strongly recommend this watch to anyone who lives an active lifestyle.

Title: Casio G-Shock DW5600E-1V
Text: First watch used during my initial US Navy enlistment (I am a retired Senior Chief Hospital Corpsman).  Most dependable watch ever owned.  I just sold my Rolex Submariner w/Date and SeaDweller (both owned for approximately 14 years) due to expense to perform periodic overhauls of these watches.  This Casio is "money", figuratively speaking.  BTW, my tours in the Navy included submarine and dive duty.  Go Navy.

Title: There was no set of "instructions" to use the watch and use the timer.
Text: No instruction was included with the watch.

Title: Great!
Text: Looks and feels great, durable as all hell. Top left button is rather sticky though.

Title: great for everyday use
Text: I buy this watch one month ago for work and I’m happy with it. It’s light weight and really heavy duty. Great for everyday use in workshop.

Title: Classic style but less accurate than expected ...
Text: Love the classic style, but it seems to run a little slow; if I had a do-over I'd buy the Multi-Band 6 version with atomic-clock sync.

Title: The functions are easy to use and adjust
Text: The functions are easy to use and adjust.  I like that is has a + and - buttons to adjust the time and timer etc.  It has all the features I need.

Title: G-Shock toughness in a smaller package
Text: Want a G-Shock but don't want a dinner plate sized disc on your wrist? You appreciate the old-school style digital watches but want the legendary toughness of a G-Shock? This is the one you want. For reference, I have an 8" wrist (See pic) This would work fine for almost any guy.

Title: then it's a good watch.
Text: It's an OK functional watch.  For those that have owned Casio watches before, for some reason the metal buttons are recessed and hard to push.  I did not know this and would not have bought the watch if I had.  It's especially hard if you want to illuminate the face to see what time it is at night.  If you don't have a problem with that, then it's a good watch.

Title: Muy completo
Text: De gran calidad, lo recomiendo. Tiene cronómetro y cuenta regresiva. Ideal para deporte muy liviano.

Title: Love it.
Text: Have owned 3 of these watches. Basic sturdy watch. They last me a couple years in construction. Just purchased another one.

Title: Good value relative to other wristwatches
Text: Nothing to dislike about this product for $40 or less. Take me back to the 80s please.

Title: It’s nice for your watch collection
Text: I love G-shock watches and for the price of this one I really like it and it’s comfortable

Title: I had one just like this one that I had for12 plus yrs
Text: I had one just like this one that I had for12 plus yrs. Good watch. Took a real beating. The battery needed to be replaced and decided to replace the watch.

Title: This IS your every day watch
Text: I've worn this daily for 4 years. I literally can not think of one complaint about this timeless watch. Classic look and so ridiculously reasonable. I use the 24hour clock, stop watch for running and hiking, timer for reminders, and the light when needed. Confirmed water resistant. No Brainer here if you're already considering this.

Title: Worth the purchase and fast delivery:)
Text: Looks awesome!

Title: Could Take His'n and Whup Your'n, then Take Your'n and Whup His'n
Text: This G Shock is solid. This watch is in my grab-and-go group of watches that I don't worry about. Just put it on and get busy. Great engineering on these G shocks! The guy that thought of this concept must be rich. He probably falls asleep watching inventory fly off the shelves. I could think of worst dreams.

Title: Nice decent watch
Text: Nice decent watch, it has all the basic functions you need In life, clean screen, rugged, I use it daily from morning to night, it takes beatings and it never fails, plus it doesn't catch unwanted attention on the street, if you like a nice low profile watch with military spec toughness this is the watch for you!!

Title: classic sports watch
Text: this is a classic watch, that isn't as bulky and the other g-shock brand watches out there. I've gotten compliments on how understated it is. I would definitely recommend it for someone that is looking for the durability of a g-shock without the need to wear a bulky watch

Title: Best bang for the buck digital watch
Text: Its the ultimate casio g shock square, best bang for the buck digital watch, will last forever, works flawlessly, easy to read even in low light....... nothing more needs to be said....... just buy it..

Title: Timeless classic but not flawless
Text: Timeless classic! The only problem is the overly recessed adjust button but it is easily replaceable for cheap.

Title: Rugged and accurate.
Text: Not much more to say...other than maybe if the band had some ventilation holes it would make it easier to wear in the heat. Otherwise, all functions work perfectly and it's a minute fast every month or so.  Very slightly annoying but better than being a minute slow every month! Probably the most rugged watch you can get for the money.  An analog watch might have issues with gears skipping or hands loosening with hard impact.  NOT an issue with this watch, obviously.

Title: Great watch
Text: Really would recommend this to anyone as an everyday watch.  Great watch overall

Title: My second one - Love it even more
Text: This is the original G-Shock. I got my first one in 1989. Finally, thie year, after 3 battery replacements; and after surviving many a whack that would have ruined lesser watches, it died during a 4th battery replacement. Maybe my own fault. This is the lightest, most comfortable, most durable, and simplest watch money can buy. Also, it's very easy to read by my aging eyes, in dim or bright light, or the dark (nice bright backlight).

Title: My G-Shock watch is wonderful!
Text: I really like my new Casio G Shock watch. This is at least the Third one I've had. The watches last a long time, and they are easy to read without a lot of stuff I don't need.

Title: A durable watch that witstood the test of time.
Text: Product was exactly as described. Delivery was prompt and as promised. The watch was a gift for my granddaughter, who was thrilled to receive it.

Title: rugged & tough for construction work
Text: i recently bought this for construction work this summer and was looking for a simple tough and reliable watch.. from jack hammering, to digging ditches, to crawling through trenches, the most outstanding thing about this watch is that it withstood the mix of sweat dust and dirt and occasional stray hammer swings. furthermore, i've enjoyed being the official timekeeper for the firm, and how the watch looks better when covered in mud. so yes, this watch will make your work more fun.

Title: Looks very good!
Text: Sturdy and beautiful watch and great price!

Title: Muy buen reloj.
Text: Es un reloj sencillo y muy funcional, además, se siente la calidad en cuanto a los materiales.

Title: It's a perfect mens work watch
Text: It's easy to use, durable and my husband thinks it's perfect for everyday work.

Title: Great watch.
Text: Number 1

Title: What can you say about the perfect watch?
Text: The only reason I had to purchase this watch, again, is because I lost my old one = ( The Casio DW-5600E is the perfect watch for me, it's rugged, durable, and has exactly what I need, a reliable alarm clock! It hasn't failed me once yet, unlike the alarm on my cell phone.  I'd recommend this watch to anyone looking for one to wear on a daily basis.

Title: Love this one
Text: Have had a cheaper Casio that was still going but needed shock proof for using power tools. Love this one! I watch a YouTube homesteader who recommended it. If he likes it I know I will!

Title: Es el mejor.
Text: Especial para trabajos de Mecanica. Tengo muchos años de usarlo y es muy bueno y barato.

Title: Four Stars
Text: My kid loves it. It's not too big, or difficult to manage.

Title: super dissapointing
Text: auto illumination function/sensor came dead with this watch, but even if it did work, at clear daylight the dial is super unreadable, for such an iconic watch casio could have given him a clear view glass their 10$ watches even have, in the photo you can see how dark and unclear he is compared to a casio watch that is not even a g-shock, at the same price, with two sensors.  i am throwing this new g-shock to the garbage.

Title: Good functional watch.
Text: Wanted and everyday watch for when I exercise or travel. This is a great watch for just that and durable as well.

Title: Good watch. Recommended.
Text: Great watch.  The one and only critique would be the "reset or adjust" button.  For someone with fat fingers and no nails this is a hard button to press; especially when running.

Title: Happy with Casios ...
Text: Had the cheap version of this watch for 15 years - it went snorkeling, swimming, diving - never had any problem, even though it was not rated for snorkeling/diving - band finally broke while kayaking and watch is somewhere in Kern river, probably still keeping time.  Upgraded to this version, which appears to be a ruggedized version. Haven't really had it long enough to rate it, but on the basis of past experience with its lesser cousin, I think it's going to be a great buy.

Title: Can't go wrong with this one
Text: I'm not even a watch person but I need one for work. I like this thing so much I started wearing it full time.

Title: Perfect Simple Watch
Text: Just what I needed. I appreciate the quality and simplicity of this watch. I love it as much as a man could love a watch. In dealing with tweakers and the uneducated all day every day I know in the very least I can rely upon this watch. If you have problems in your life, with this watch, at least you'll know what time it is.. Buy it

Title: Buen producto
Text: Hasta ahora funciona bien

Title: My six year old loves this watch! It says ...
Text: My six year old loves this watch! It says it's water proof but we still keep it out of the shower etc. because a friend bought the same model for her sons and they swam with them in the pool and the watches died in a few days.

Title: Awesome Watch
Text: I love this watch. Very comfortable and durable. Keeps perfect time. Easy to set up and use.

Title: will stick with Timex in the future
Text: My old Timex Ironman was showing signs of the hard use I put it to, so I was looking for a replacement. While looking for a cheaper Timex, I read a review which highly recommmened the Casio G-Shock.  When I read other reviews, they seemed to agree that it was a good eatch, so I decided to try it. Not happy. It's difficult to use, hard to see the numbers, and almost impossible to engage the buttons. One of the complaints about the Timex was that the buttons were too easy to engage. Well, that is definitely not a problem with the Casio. I can hardly press them. I have to use my fingernail, and press really hard to get them to work. I won't ever buy another. This one will last a long time because I don't ever wear it. I bought a cheap Timex Sports, and wear it all the time.

Title: Sweet watch
Text: This is an awesome watch, but when I recieved it  the top left button was broken and so was the plastic. Instead of sending it back I just brought it to Walmart for a refund lol. I hated to see it go. I'll buy another soon!

Title: Reliable and good quality
Text: Cheap and good quality

Title: Really nice whatch! It’s not that big so it doesn’t ...
Text: Really nice whatch! It’s not that big so it doesn’t stand out too much I bought some bull bars from Etsy and it makes the watch look a little more tactical lol

Title: A disappointing legend
Text: I've had this watch for only 5ish months and found the resin bezel which is famous for being almost indestructible has cracked around the adjust button making it almost impossible to press! If I can find a way to return it I will.

Title: Great Watch for the Price!!
Text: I've had Casio watches for decades. I first had a plain Casio stop watch. Then I outgrew it, and bought a Casio Satellite stainless steel watch. I would have still had it but I lost it at a gym. So I went back to this very reliable watch. I'm glad I bought it. It keeps good time, and very affordable. I'm sure you'll like it too!!

Title: I recommend
Text: The product is of good quality, of a normal size to be a G-Shock. It is a good watch for a daily use.

Title: Like the old times

Title: Simple and functional

Title: Not for the slightly arthritic or big-fingered
Text: I like Casio watches. I needed to replace one that had served me well for years. Too bad for me that Casio has made changes in its design. In particular, on this model, the Adjust setting button, which is used for selecting the function you want, is slightly recessed and I simply cannot manipulate it easily with my fingertips. Either the mild arthritis I have isn't letting me be nimble enough or my fingers are too big. I can do it with a thumbnail if I get it just right or stylus, but not with my finger tip. Sorry, but that is not what I want. Styling is nice, though, and I still like Casio. Wound up with one of the humongous G-Shock models that has four big buttons. Jerry

Title: Faulty Garbage.

The top left hand button (that which co trips the ADJUST function) has an obvious design flaw, being the second consecutive watch I have had with the same problem. It is depressed and has a gap of nearly 1mm allowing water inside the watch, fogging the screen and obscuring the display. I bought this watch initially discovering this and sent it back for replacement; the replacement was the same. I am deeply disappointed by this and although have been I pressed by Amazon’s customer service, I am left with a watch that is unreliable and of sub par quality

My advice is avoid this watch.

Title: The original G-Shock; this watch started a genre
Text: Although it is highly doubtful you are still reading this, I felt like I should review it anyway. I agree with the reviews that say this watch has everything a watch should, and nothing it shouldn't. I think that is true, if it were 1985. But it is not 1985 any more. I'll start with the bad things first: a) This model, with the E suffix, is not solar powered. This means that eventually, the battery is going to die and need to be replaced. When that happens you need to change it. On one hand, the back is easy to get off. Just get out your jeweler's screwdrivers and remove the four screws. If you are not coordinated with tiny parts, don't try it. Once the back is off, the seal is broken. There is an O-ring between the stainless steel back and the chassis. It is a challenge to make sure that O-ring is back in the same spot. Also, since the CR2016 lithium battery is pretty big and the watch electronics so efficient, the battery lasts a LONG time. Mine lasted 8 years, though I don't wear it every day. With daily wear, it would probably be more like 5 years. b) Next problem.... Oh wait, there are no other problems. The watch is flawless aside from that. The fact that it uses a conventional lithium battery and not solar, coupled with the fact that it is not atomic, means that this watch can be sold for a very fair price. What you get for the price is amazing: a) Ruggedness - This was the original rugged digital watch. Before this came out, the only way to have a rugged watch was to buy a diver's watch. Those were not as rugged as this, nor as affordable. Unlike cheaper and less armored models, this model has a mineral glass crystal that is not as easily scratched as the plastic crystal on the cheaper models. Also, the G-Shock has the rubber armor that protects the crystal from glancing blows. In addition to that, it is 200 m water resistant. This is enough to go swimming with, and even scuba diving. No need to ever take this watch off! b) Accuracy - I believe the spec. for this watch is 30s per month. Mine is more accurate than this. It is so accurate, it only needs to be set once a year. No need for atomic receivers to add cost. c) Features - It has just the right amount of features. The time & calendar are all visible on the main screen; most of the time I don't even need to press any buttons. Stopwatch, for those times when I want to time something. How long does it take to ride my bike to the train station? How long before my food is served when I eat out? The countdown timer is even more useful. I use it to remind myself to change laundry and for portable cook times for steak on the grill. Dual time. Came in handy when I was in Poland early this year. One alarm, but it is a very special alarm. You can set it to go off every day at a certain time or on a certain day every month, or on a certain day in a certain month. d) Not too clunky - A lot of the newer G-Shocks are much thicker and with more corners and edges. This one is big, but it still fits under shirt sleeves. My other G-Shock (the first solar/atomic model) is probably 20% bigger. It has a couple of useless features and cost twice as much. e) Comfort - Although it has the typical Casio resin strap, it is comfortable and it doesn't break. The strap is already molded in the shape of of your wrist. This is good, because it means the strap is not getting bent again and again every time you put on or take off the watch. This feature is common to all G-Shocks. Lesser Casios don't have this and folks say that the watches themselves last forever, but the straps do not. Casio needs to get on board with nylon straps, I think. Although solar/atomic is not a required feature, they make this same watch style in a solar/atomic version. It costs more, but I think it is worth it just so that one doesn't have to worry about breaking the seal to replace the battery and not getting it back right. Technically, one is supposed to replace that gasket and clean it every time the battery is changed. But no one ever does, except Casio. If you can afford it, get the solar/atomic model, unless you really want the original!

The buttons are a little hard to press with big sausage fingers like mine but that’s only really a problem when daylight saving time hits and I need to change the time. Title: I love this tough, simple, reliable, comfortable watch
Text: I've had this watch for 6 or 7 years and I really, really like it.  I love that when I'm in the 'countdown' or 'stopwatch' function that the current time is still viewable in the little inset window thing.  That's really useful when timing a run, but also keeping track of what time it is, so I know when I need to head home. I think it looks cool, but it's light weight. Tough, but not, like "Don't mess with me or I'll bludgeon you with my watch."  It feels good on the wrist- but not as good as a watch with a silicone band, like my Garmin Instinct- that's a really comfortable watch.  I love how well it slips under the cuff of a long-sleeve shirt.  The light is great.  I wish you could turn off the key-beep, and I wish the alarm was a little louder. I took the bezel off and hit it with the Dremel tool and some fine wet-dry sandpaper and knocked down some of the knobbys that make it hard to get to the buttons (see photos).  It's now really easy to get to that top-left button- and to get all the other ones just by feel.  After doing that mod to the make the buttons easier to get to, the ONLY complaints I have about this watch are that the sheen of the bezel and the strap don't *perfectly* match.  Every now and again the band gets to looking more glossy than the bezel, so I hit it with some 600 grit sandpaper- and that gets it back to more of a matte finish.  Also, the digits get ghosty on more viewing angles than other watches I have. My Rangeman and my Instinct are just viewable from anywhere.  It's a small thing, but I notice it.  I wish it had more than one alarm.  I've contemplated getting a GW-5610 for more alarms, button mute and (hopefully) digits that are bolder and viewable from more angles- but it's more than twice the price and the current time doesn't appear in the inset window when you're in stopwatch or timer mode.  So that sucks.  I don't wish it had world time.  I know a lot of people need that- and some of my other watches have that- it just feels like one more function to click through to get to the function I want. All the obvious things are there- it keeps super-reliable time, everything works, it's comfy, and people who know watches will all tell you- whatever else you've got in terms of watches, you should have one of these too.  They're right. This watch has held up perfectly to bathroom demolitions, yard work, car work, field work, hiking, camping, really, really crappy surfing, snorkeling after I found out I suck at surfing, rock climbing / rappelling and multi-day trips where it serves as alarm clock, navigation timer and 'don't forget to do 'X' reminder' thingy.  I like it a lot.  When I'm getting ready for the day, I choose to wear it about as often as my GW-9400 Rangeman, which is a fantastic watch but bulky, and my Instinct- which is also a fantastic watch, but it makes me just a little nervous to have $300 swinging around on my arm- but I LOVE that watch too. So, like I say: other watches do more.  Most of the time, I don't need more and this thing just works great, looks cool and it's solid.  If I lost or destroyed the one on my wrist right now, I'd buy another one tomorrow.

Title: One of the best all-around digital watches ever
Text: I recently found this old beast in a drawer and discovered, to my dismay, that the battery had officially died and the screen was blank.  Historically, this has been the point where I toss the old watch out or back in the drawer and buy a new one.  This time, though, I thought I'd see how hard it is to replace a watch battery and see if I could bring it back to life.  After a few errant tries and watching a YouTube video or two, I was able to and this old thing is now running as well as ever (or almost). This is my go-to outdoor/hiking/workout watch and I also wear it when travelling since I don't care if it gets lost/damaged and also doesn't advertise "rob me" to any crooks looking to take advantage of a tourist.  It's easy to set and probably quite close to being bulletproof.  I wear it when swimming, in the hot tub, or when washing the car.  At this point, I'm almost daring the universe to destroy or damage it and so far it has not risen to the challenge. The years seem to have been tough on this watch, as there is no audible 'beep' function on it anymore.  I suspect this could be because of the discount battery I used to replace the OEM version, or perhaps that circuit is dead.  No worries.  I have plenty of alarms around me on my nightstand and on my smartphone.  I also cracked the plastic "G-Shock" wrap that goes around the case, which is why this G-Shock doesn't look quite like all the others.  I like this (literally) stripped-down version better, anyhow.  It's lighter and now the buttons poke out of the sides like Frankenstein's neck.  Coincidentally, I've named this watch "Frank" or "Silent Frank" since it doesn't make any noise.  Take that, Rolex.

Title: Fix for the recessed "Adjust" button
Text: This is a great watch, but many people are put off by the recessed "Adjust" button on the top left corner.  As someone who uses that button to reset the Stopwatch often when at the gym, it became a pain to have to deal with.  I really like the watch other than that, though, so I came up with a "fix" that works for me so far.  I simply went to the hardware store and bought some JP Weld, mixed some up and -- using a small wooded toothpick -- applied a small bead of it to the recessed "Adjust" button.  Not too much, just a small amount, and let it harden for as long as the JP Weld instructions say, and it works perfectly.  I no longer have to struggle to reset the Stopwatch or the Timer.  The dark gray color of the JP Weld matches the black of the watch itself.  Note:  You might have to apply more than one bead of the JP Weld to make it "tall" enough to make pushing the button easy.  Just apply a little at a time (under do it rather than over do it) until you reach the desired result.

Title: This is almost the perfect watch.
Text: This watch is almost perfect! It is slim and compact. It can take massive amounts of punishment and still keep going on. It is extremely lightweight and comfortable. The current time is visible in all modes. The only reason that I, personally, rate it a 4? You cannot mute this watch. Otgerwise it is perfect. I do want to take some space and address some "flaws" that other reviewers have mentioned. 1. The adjust button being sunken into the case is an error or fluke. Nope, this is the way it is designed. I have rather large fingers so I must use a pen or key, or whatever I have handy. Why is this a design feature? It is so you will not accidentally change the time or other settings on your watch. 2. My watch foggs up when it gets cold and or wet. Yes, this is a pain when ot happens. Also these watches are hermatically sealed when they are assembled. But, the humidity and air pressure present at the day and time these were assembled at the factory plays a large factor. Most of the time you will not have any issues on this front. But if the watch is fogging after getting it wet is an easy fix. Simply get a small screwdriver and remove the 4 screws to the back plate and remove it. Make sure the thin gasket is in the correct position, which is the thin circle running around the back of the watch under the backplate. Leave the back off for a half hour to fourty five minutes on a normal day where you happen to live. Once you make sure the gasket is in place, and get the back back in place your watch will be fine. Now if it is fogging due to cold, doing the above can and will help most of the time. I mean for crying out loud, it's a $40 watch. Not a $400 or a Rolex.

Title: In some ways, the G-Shock sucks
Text: This watch is really lousy at many things. Women will not fantasize about how big and hard your wallet is when they see the G-Shock.  It looks terrible with a leisure suit, and worse with a tuxedo.  Donald Trump would mot be caught dead with one.  It will not impress anyone at a power meeting in a corporate board room.  Really does not go with the outfit if you are a male stripper with Chippendale's or a clown with Barnum and Bailey. The G-Shock does have a few minor benefits.  Mine has been deeper than 300' repeatedly with me on deep techical dives, working flawlessly.  I never got deep enough for the pressure to kill it, and I have been deep.  Indeed, before reliable dive computers were developed, the G-Shock was favored by the deep and cave diving pioneers because it actually kept working at extreme depths, unlike a lot of big name watches that were supposed to.  So this thing will put up with far more water than most watches, regardless of price. And there is also the tiny benefit of shock resistance, but is that just slick advertising?  Well, years ago when I was a lot younger, my buddies and I would get the idea that we should torture-test the watch to see if it was really shock resistant.  There may have been quite a bit of beer involved, but I have no clear recollection of that.  It survived falls off off 6-story buildings (okay, it was forcefully thrown downwards from those heights after the first couple falls).  My friend with the pitcher's arm threw it out the window of a speeding car as hard as he could, hitting traffic signs.  Over cliffs, over whatever.  The case would be ragged, but the watch would keep running fine . . . UNLESS something hard and pointed went through the glass face.  That was the only thing that would do in the watch, and it was not easy to have that happen. We ran over it a few times with the car, which jacked up the band but didn't phase the module. It did totally fail when shot with a .22, though the back of the case could withstand all air rifles.  Yeah, we wasted some money on the 5 or 6 watches we did in over the years trying to find what the limits were, but the beer cost more. Basically, this watch will survive depths and impacts far worse than you could ever possible survive.  Which is another failure for the watch: the coroner will not get a good time of death from your watch because it won't stop like everyone elses when your plane crashes.  He might even steal it because he is so impress that it survived . . . and he doesn't have to worry about the water hurting it as he washes your blood and gore off the watch. But it still won't make women think you have a lot of money.

Title: The Definitive G-Shock
Text: Casio has released many G-Shock variations over the years, most much fancier, but this one is a direct descendent of the model that started it all. Remember the old TV commercial that established G-Shock durability by showing a hockey player sending a DW-5200 G-Shock flying with a slapshot? I bought one way back then, and gave it a terrible beating for years and years. It was made in Japan and had a threaded back that screwed onto the case. This DW-5600 is the grandson of that one and looks practically identical. The DW5600E-1V is made in Thailand, and its back is attached by 4 screws. But other than those distinctions and a few minor text changes, it is the same watch, with the same durability. I have a watch box filled with timepieces, but this is the one I wear whenever I'm doing any manual labor because I know it can take the beating.

Title: The base DW-5600 G shock ...... or is it?
Text: The G Shock DW5600E-1V is considered the basic, cheapest, bottom of the line up of the DW-5600 series G shocks. But really is it? Sure there are more expensive of the series. Models with solar panels, solar panels and Multi-band (atomic) setting, and the most expensive are the metal body ones. Casio releases several "special limited" G shocks. They have different colored bands or graphics. They are only offered for a limited run. Here is the kicker: Some of them use the same #3229 module as the "base" DW5600E-1V. So in reality you are just paying more for a different colored band and a watch face with different colors or graphics. For example, a few years ago Casio released thier "Clean military series". They retailed for $99. They had a solid color band, yellow, white, or black and a white face. They were called clean because the face was white with minimal lettering. I have a yellow one. But it uses the same #3229 module. So for twice the cost of the DW5600E-1V, the only difference was the band, case color and the white face. I've seen some Casio limited editions which use the same module go for $140. So the question is, is the DW5600E-1V REALLY a "base" model?

Title: GWM5600-1 vs.  DW5600E-1V
Text: I'd never owned either a solar powered or an atomic clock syncing watch before but had always kind of wanted one.  Most G-Shocks are too big and bulky for my taste but having recently discovered the much more reasonably sized and classically retro-nerd styled 5600s I began to take a closer look.  I was initially considering the GW5600J-1 but the fact that it doesn't display both the day and date simultaneously was a serious drawback for me.  (At this point I'd not yet discovered the GWM5600-1.)  Then after reading reviews of the non-gimmicky DW5600E-V1 I convinced myself that it was really the best way to go and that solar power and atomic syncing were extras I really didn't need. A couple of days after ordering the DW5600E-1V I discovered the GWM5600-1 and found that it was everything  I had initially been looking for and ended up ordering it as well.  Both arrived safely and now I am the proud owner of two nearly identically looking watches.  Chances are no one but me will ever know. I think I'll call one Borden and one Fallon.  However, they are not nearly identical... Weight: My DW5600 weighs 52g and the GWM5600 weighs 48g. Size: They look the same to me except that the GWM is slightly thinner at just under 12mm. The DW is about 12.5mm. Display: This is where I found the biggest and most unexpected differences.  The GWM has noticeably better contrast.  The background (light grey) of the DW is darker than on the GWM resulting in poorer contrast making it just a bit harder to read. Also the main numbers of the display are slightly larger on the GWM. Combine the larger numbers with the better contrast and the GWM's display is a no contest winner. (Of course if I didn't have them side by side to compare I'm sure I'd have had nothing bad to say about the DW's display.) Buttons: As you may already know the top left (A) button on the DW is more recessed than the other three, actually it really doesn't protrude out at all, and can be difficult to use.  I usually have to try two or three times to get it to respond.  I understand the need to avoid inadvertent pushing and activating of functions but this seems a bit too extreme to me.  The GWM (A) button extends out as far as the others and has caused me no problems at all. The backs of both are stainless steel attached with four screws.  The DW's back is plain and round and just fine thank you very much but the back of the GWM has a bit nicer brushed finish and a more sculpted shape giving it a subtle if somewhat intangible superiority over the DW's back.  At least I think so. As far as features go, I wanted a watch that displayed both the day and date in time keeping mode.  I wanted at least one alarm and a countdown timer (one hour is plenty for me).  Either Solar or battery power is fine with me because I know that the cells in BOTH will eventually need replacing and taking the back off my watch once every several years is something that I do not consider unreasonable. It is of course cool to have your watch reset itself every night and to know that it will never be more than a second or two off the real correct time.  I live in Canada but here in southern Alberta I have no trouble getting a strong signal every night and am even able to do manual resets during the day. In the end I am happy to have two 5600s and will wear both I'm sure.  If I had to do it over again though, I'd definitely just get the GWM5600-1.  It's barely noticeably lighter, thinner, it's easier to read and will always show the correct time without manual adjustment. It's pretty much perfect!

Title: I can't wear this Casio because the band inflames my ...
Text: I can't wear this Casio because the band inflames my wrist on both arms after a few days. A new band is $14 on Amazon! No thanks

Title: CLUNKY
Text: Heavy and clunky. Does not have preset timer I expected and need for my job.  Bad choice on my part.  Junk in drawer.

Title: Large size
Text: The size is too large as it gets caught on my shirt sleeve all the time. The cheaper Casio models might be a better fit.

Title: It just will not stop working !
Text: I wrote a similar review on amazon.co.uk... To summarise - I actually bought a DW5600-E in 1998.  So it is now about 20 years old. It's had the strap replaced once (in 2005) and it is now on its 3rd or 4th battery. The batteries (CR2016) seem to last a lot longer than the advertised 2 years. It is still going strong and looks hardly any different than the day I bought it. It gets used a lot for the gym, washing the car, gardening, day to day stuff - everything really. It appears to be 100% waterproof. When I first bought it I thought it was a bit big and chunky. Nowadays with the fashion for much bigger watches than this, it doesn't seem that way anymore. Funny how your view can change - I now find it the perfect size - not too big, not too small. The display is clear and the backlight is very good. I use the countdown timer a lot ( whilst cooking, for example ). I've read a couple of people complaining about the stiffness of the buttons especially the recessed one. Well, all I can say is mine was like this too, but give it 10 years and they will loosen up. This is a long term watch! Overall, I like mine even more these days than when I bought it 1998. It could be a nostalgia thing but I can't see me ever not having this watch. Finally, on the last battery change, I took mine to a jewellers to sort out. They handed it back to me a few days later to say sorry, it's not working at all :-(  After a Google I found that there is a little contact point near the battery cage (it is apparently called the AC or All Clear) which you can reset using metal tweezers if you replace the battery and find the watch is not working or working correctly. Without much hope I tried this out myself, and the watch instantly sprung back to life! What a brilliant feeling - welcome back (for another 20 years?) ....

Title: It is not good.
Text: This watch is not good because the LCD is broken easily. I just have used it for 1year; LCD became  blurred. I do not recommend to buy it.

Title: Buttons hard to push but I still love it
Text: I use this G-shock not only as my daily driver, but also as a fitness tool (stopwatch) pretty much every day. From timing rest breaks in between sets, or a Crossfit workout, or laps on the track, the stopwatch function gets serious use. The mode toggle and the start/stop buttons work well. It's the reset button that kills me. I've used it enough that I can hit it first try 9/10 times, but the button is recessed for some reason and is far from an ideal setup for a function that I use so often. It works well enough however that even though it's not perfect I continue to love this watch. What else can I say that hasn't already been said? It's got classic, retro style. It's more or less bombproof. The cultish mystique is undeniable. What other $50 watch has this much history? Keanu Reeves wore it in Speed. It's been certified by NASA and sent to space... I'm definitely a bit of a nerd, but for a watch of this quality at this price, I can overlook the less than perfect stopwatch function.

Title: the band was too small for my wrist.
Text: the band was too small for my wrist. would have bought a larger band but could not find one(it has a funky band on it)

Title: Must for all watch collectors
Text: A great timepiece for when you want a watch that will take a beating.  I always travel with it, to supplement my nice watches...you don't want to take your expensive swiss watch into a waterpark (for example) or on any other rough and tumble activity. Unlike some of the other G Shocks this is quite subtle and thin.  Large numerals, basic operations and the illuminator make it very suitable.  My only reasoning for docking one star for this is that Casio has changed the functionality of the watch with the new module.  I have had many pre G watches which had a superior and more ergonomically sound module...like the 270 (I think).  Here, we have lost the second time zone, which was very useful and the button functions have moved about.  So if you are a old Casio watch owner, there is a bit of a learning curve to unlearn old stuff. Nonetheless this is the watch that I reach for when I want to keep something on my wrist that will tell time accurately and reliably and is "disposable"

Title: Awesome for Ladies too
Text: Yeah!  This is not just a MAN watch.  I am a lady and I like this watch because it is user friendly, durable, reliable, classic design.  It lights up evenly across the screen for a second or two or for as long as you depress the button.  I like the count down timer, not available on the less expensive models.  I Like the size, not huge, bulky, or heavy. Unlike the less expensive models, the crystal is glass (mineral) rather then plastic.  I have owned Rolex, Omega, Seiko, Citizen, Swiss Army Victorinox,  None of them have kept time as accurately as this watch.  The batteries in those watches last a year or two, while the battery lasts approx. 5 - 7 years or more in this 5600E watch.  The band wraps nicely around my wrist and i like to wear it loose like a bracelet.  As the testimonies tell, it will stand up to extreme abuse. Let me compare it to the model I purchased before this one, the W-800H which I purchased for $15.00 + tax + postage. Yes, it is a very good watch.  10 year battery, "Plastic" crystal.  Even though the watch is a bit thinner, if feels more bulky because the band does not have the same wrap around design. No count down timer, which is very useful for me. Does not have "rubberized" protection around the face (very attractive, by the way) Water resistant only to 100 as apposed to 200 meters. I think the W-800M has dual time and split timer.  I don't care about that, so I can't vouch for it.  I want my count down timer. MY VERY FAVORITE OF THE TWO is the G-Shock DW-5600 E.  If you search Amazon, then Casio G-Shock 3229, you will come up with this watch.  I don't know why they call it  DW-5600E-1V but it is the same watch. Navy Seals and other Special Forces:) wear this watch in Afghanistan etc.  and rave about its durability and reliability. I recommend this watch for everyone from Grandchildren to grandparents, from teacher to construction worker. Hope this is helpful.

Title: Spend the extra money for a good watch
Text: The watchface doesn’t work at all

I Have difficulty with some fine motor skills and the strap is just too small - and I have small wrists. It only extends about 1 1/4" past the peg. Title: I've been waiting 30 years to write this review
Text: I had a G-Shock 30 years ago that looked EXACTLY like this model. Perhaps it is the same model. I've been waiting 30 years to write this review because I'm still made at Casio. This watch is advertised as indestructible but I guarantee that it is not. At that time it was an expensive watch and I expected more from it. I was on a small craft attempting to make a beach landing in high surf when the boat flipped stern over bow, and I landed upon underwater rocks.  My watch crumbled to pieces when I needed it the most.

Title: Defective!
Text: The backlight illuminator (one of the main reasons I purchased it) does not work.

Title: Great watch
Text: After reading all of the positive reviews I decided to buy one of these watches for myself.  I have worn it for about a week, and I have come to the conclusion that it's a great watch. It's so light I really don't notice that I'm wearing it. It's simple to use with no added fluff that complicates things. So far it's very durable. I'm a Firemedic and tend to be hard on my gear and this watch had stood up to the punishment, but I need more time so see if it can hold up to my abuse. I also like the simplicity of the stopwatch feature; it will be a valuable tool on certain EMS related calls. The only con is that the reset button in the upper left corner is recessed in pretty far and can be a little tricky to push with medical gloves on. All in all, as of now I would highly recommend this watch to anyone in the market for a work or duty watch. I'm editing my review for a word of caution, and I'm taking a star away. I am still very happy with this watch. It is still very tough impact wise because I have not seen a scratch or ding, but I found out it doesn't hold up to insect repellant. While preparing for a hike I sprayed myself with off to keep the ticks away. I got some over spray on the bevel and the band. I noticed some discoloration so I rinsed it with water. The spray marks are now permanent. The crystal and the function are still fine so it's all cosmetic, but I am reminded of my hiking trip every time I check the time.

Title: Great watch for the money - Smaller digits.
Text: This is my second Casio watch, the other a $13 F91w-1 I've worn daily for over 1 year having replaced the band once . This G- Shock is large enough for me because I have a smaller wrist and don't like big clock-sized watches anyway. It has all the features I need, and the illumination is very good. The band should last longer with the screws than the pins on the cheaper Casio I still have. The only shortcoming I found is the digits are a bit smaller and harder to read than on the cheaper model. My eyesight is not what it used to be (I'm 50). This will be my daily watch for work and casual outings...that is if I get used to the slightly smaller display. For under $40 it's a lot of watch. With the proven G-Shock durability, I expect it to last many years.

Title: My personal perfect watch
Text: This 5600 has everything I need, and nothing I don't: - It tells you the time, date, and day of the week at a glance. - It has 1 alarm (not 5 like many other G-Shocks -- too fidly). - A countdown timer (with the current time shown in the upper box). - A stopwatch (again, time is still shown). That's it. If you want fancy "features" like inaccurate temperature readings, barometric pressure graph which gets distorted by temperature and altitude, 19 alarms, and world time in 7,000 cities around the world -- look elsewhere! This watch does exactly what a wristwatch should, which in my opinion is tell the time, and take an absolute beating. I don't particularly want to stand in public pressing 15 buttons on my watch, just to set a quick alarm to remind me of something. This 5600 keeps everything relatively simple (obviously go through the manual when you first get it). (I started collecting G-Shocks; they have all since been given away/sold since I discovered this little beauty. I had a Riseman, Gulfman, Mudman, and G7700 -- and none of them were worn after purchasing this. And I paid AUS$350 for the Riseman!) The design of this watch is absolutely classic. It is truly a "timeless" design for a digital watch. The best thing about it is the simplicity -- it is one of the few G-Shocks which doesn't have random circles which show the seconds, bar graphs, a bezel 2 inches off your wrist, etc etc. It's clean and simple. As far as durability, I haven't taken mine off for over 6 months; it's been swimming indoors, at the beach, smashed against shelving time and time again (I'm a storeman), it gets run under hot water about 10 times a day for hand-washing, I shower in it, sleep in it, play with my kids at the park ... It is yet to show ANY visible damage -- absolutely amazing! The buttons are fine to press. After setting the alarm, starting the stopwatch, whatever, it returns you to the time mode with a single button push. Again, there is no nonsense, like scrolling through 5 more modes just to get back to the time display. If you are also looking at the "solar atomic" model of the 5600, please consider -- the batteries in this watch will last years and years, and it will keep very accurate time (I reset it against Internet atomic time every few months and it's never been out by more than a few seconds). In my opinion solar & atomic are essentially "gimmicks" in wristwatches (no offense to those that enjoy those features, but, I see them as useless, and I have owned a solar G-Shock). I 100% recommend this watch for the no-nonsense buyer who wants a relatively slim/sleek G-Shock with all the toughness, and non of the "fluff".

Title: This watch is beyond it’s Time.
Text: I got on amazon and noticed my watch I got in Hawaii was on here. I originally bought it to wake me up for work and had no clue that a year later I would be depending on it every day. I have my timer set up for steaks and laundry, I use my stop watch when I go for bike rides, and I have never had to worry about it even once when it rains or if I go swimming. At first I was worried that hot water might make a difference but after hot tubing with this watch for a year I realized it’s indestructible. My sisters dog got ahold of it and buried it in my parents back yard, my dad found it and gave it back to me covered in mud, worked the exact same as when I first got it and none of the buttons have ever had a single problem. I kept the instruction manual in my wallet and every time I got board I learned a little more about it until I finally learned the watch completely. The hourly alarm keeps me on track at work and my daily alarm let’s me know when it’s time for lunch without any problems. I’ve never changed a single battery and I don’t think I ever will at this point.
