Title: One thing I really like about this watch is its size
Text: This is probably one of the most iconic G-shock watches that Casio has ever produced. This style dates back to the 80s and hasn't changed much since. This is a very tough watch and has many applications, from your average Joe to the military use. The battery life last a very long time and will keep you company for many years to come. One thing I really like about this watch is its size; it's not ridiculously big like the other Casio G-shock watches. I took off one star because of the band. It either fits tight or loose, but that is just for my wrist. It might fit other people better.

Title: One Star
Text: My husband is 83 and he has a hard time using it.

Title: Best features for the price
Text: This watch gets a 5 star review as it is now the best watch for the price on Amazon. I own a GW5600J-1 G-Shock Atomic Tough Solar Watch that used to be sold on Amazon for about $60 when I purchased it.  The price for that model then went up to about $85 which was "too much" in my opinion, and now that model says it is out of stock and no indications that it will be brought back at a reasonable price.  The added features of getting solar power and atomic clock syncronization were something that motivated me to say YES I would spend an extra $20 just for the novelties. So where does that put the DW5600E-1V "classic" G-Shock watch?  Well, the next step up to get any sort of atomic clock sync is the GWM5610-1 that is $123.54 (as of this writing) on Amazon.  An extra $80 or so to get solar power and atomic clock sync?  No, not worth a 3x price in my opinion.  That clock sync is 6 bands that aren't specified in the item description so I am assuming it is 2x in Japan, the USA clock in Colorado, something in the UK, something in Germany, and then two others have to fit in there somehow.  I don't travel the world enough to care about syncing my watch wirelessly in different continents. Save the money and spend the $45 or so to get the basic G-Shock watch.  NO ONE cares about atomic clock sync.  I thought I did until I bought mine but just came to the realization that wearing a quartz watch that you set right keeps you within a minute of reference time signals for over 6 months before it drifts enough to be signifigant.  If you want to be a geek about it, sync the watch manually by resetting the seconds to a time signal once a month.  Other than that, I DON'T CARE about anything in a watch other than being close to the right time, and then I value durability and water resistance.  So . . . this basic G-Shock watch meets those three criteria for $45. Buy this watch and forget about the atomic clock sync nonsense, and forget about the solar power.  Just get the battery replaced once every 7-10 years and enjoy owning a watch you can beat up and otherwise forget about.

Title: Great, but no 100% satisfied
Text: So I just got this watch for my dad. He totally loved it! Overall the watch is pretty good. The quality is great..BUT the packaging is more on the cheap side and there was some scratches on the back of the watch. The box was dented all around. The manual was also sort of difficult to read. So, while I do recommend for people to buy this watch, I'd really hope that when You purchase an item...it should remain in New shape without any scratches and perhaps better packaging.

Title: Justifiably famous--this 5600 is a really solid, well-built watch
Text: After looking at lots of G-Shock models online, I got this watch yesterday (at Target--wanted to try it before making a decision). I chose between it and the DW-9052. I liked the shape of the 9052, but the shrouded buttons were more annoying to use and the stopwatch start/stop on that watch is located on the lower right button and I prefer it on the upper right, as on this 5600. I also like the no-nonsense look of this watch without all the extra frippery of some other G-Shocks (which can be fun in its own right, just not what I was looking for with this purchase). The watch is as solidly well built as everyone says. It's a joy to hold--has a reassuring weight and sparkling clear glass dial. The strap is good for what it is. It's not as soft as cloth or leather, but for a resin strap it feels quite comfortable. The buttons don't protrude much--this is by design, especially the Adjust button, to avoid accidental presses or impacts to the buttons. They're not difficult to press but you have to use the tip of your finger or your fingernail to push them, and the Adjust button can be a little harder to get to because it is sunken in more than the others. Features are fairly basic by today's standards, but solid. It has blue-green electroluminescent backlighting with a dedicated button (lower right), and it stays on about two seconds with a quick press. There's one alarm which can be set for as a normal alarm, or to go off the same time each day of a certain month, or to go off on a particular date (month/day). There is a countdown timer that can be set for up to 24 hours and can be set down to the second. It can be set to automatically restart once it goes off. If you like, you can have the backlight flash repeatedly when the alarm or timer goes off, as a visual indicator. There is a stopwatch that can do a split time (stop and record a time while the stopwatch is still counting, then resume at the actual elapsed time) and a first/second-place finish time, but does not have lap memories like my old Timex Ironman Triathlon. I don't often need lap memories, but there are times when they are handy and I wish this watch had that feature. Perpetual calendar up through 2099, which should do me. :) There's also an hourly chime that you can turn on and off. I don't think there's a way to silence the beeping when you change modes, but it's pretty quiet. Modes cycle Time--Alarm--Countdown Timer--Stopwatch, then back to Time, with a different tone at Time so you know you're back even without looking. A useful feature is that when you go to a different mode and use that mode, the next time you press Mode it takes you back to Time. If you select a mode but don't use it (start the stopwatch, set the alarm, etc.), it cycles through the rest of the modes as usual with each button push. In Timer and Stopwatch the time is also displayed (instead of the date in the upper-right part of the display), which I really like since you can time something while still keeping an eye on the time of day and not need to switch modes to do so. You can switch between 12 and 24-hour time, but only in the time-setting mode, and it takes several button pushes. This watch does not have dual time, multiple alarms, lap memory, a timer that will count down and then start counting up, auto-backlighting when you tilt your wrist, or other special features. It's a fairly basic watch that has simple but useful capabilities. It's major selling point is that it is built like a tank. Many digital watches feel disposable. This one does not. If the bezel gets scratched up too badly you can buy a replacement bezel. Same with the strap. Although some worry about water resistance after changing a watch battery, I plan to do my own battery changes and be reasonably careful, and don't anticipate problems (it takes a CR2016 lithium if you're curious). You can buy replacement rubber gaskets if the one inside the back gets too deteriorated over time and you're worried about it leaking. The deepest I will probably take my watch is a swimming pool, and I think it will do fine even after opening and re-closing, but I won't test it until I have to. As others have mentioned, the strap attachments are very narrow for such a big watch--looks like around 15mm. Not a big deal, though, because you can buy special adapters from Casio or other companies that allow you to put say a 22 or 24mm nato strap on this watch. The strap it comes with is 26mm wide where it joins the case of the watch. The watch is pretty heavy for a digital--I do notice it on my wrist, but it hasn't been too bad so far for prolonged wear. Because the actual watch module is recessed in the case and there's some clearance behind the dial glass, the LCD can be hard to read from an angle. It only looks super crisp from head on and slight side angles. Anything more and it's still readable but much softer looking. I'm still getting used to this watch. It's not 100% love at first sight, but I find it very satisfying to wear and to use. I love tools that are built to a purpose without anything extra, and that's the feeling this watch gives me. It doesn't do everything, but what it does it does well. I believe I will have this for a long time to come. At the time of this review, Target's price was only a couple dollars more than the best deal on Amazon. With sales tax it was around $5 more than from Amazon. Of course, prices change all the time, but Amazon seems to have bigger discounts on some of the more expensive G-Shocks (where the margins are probably higher for retail stores).

Title: Ran on the first battery for 13 years. Spooky.
Text: I haven't bought one of these in years, and I'm too old to read digital watches any more. But I loved this watch. It was my alarm clock for almost two years, when I couldn't afford an alarm clock (but had to have a watch). I didn't use the light much. I was amazed that it kept "ticking" for 13 years (and a couple of years after that when I switched to analog). It was spooky how long that battery lasted. Like, Green Lantern (I said I'm old) spooky. Like nuclear submarine spooky. The buttons for switching between modes were (and are?) intuitive, and provide tons of functionality. Count-up, count-down timers. Alarms. Dates accounted for leap years (again, kind of spooky). Not sure if it passed the Y2K leap year test (it's been that long). This is a great watch. Or was, in any case. Plus, waterproof. SCUBA down to 95 feet, some of which was spent working underwater. Repeatedly. I still have this watch, maybe I should put a new battery in it. If I were in the market for a digital watch, this would be the one. Or just a new battery for my old one.

Title: It grows on you. Excellent watch.
Text: Excellent watch. Tried it on twice before buying it. First time, I didn't care for it. Second time, I liked it and bought it. Point is that when I got it home and set it and started wearing it, I liked it even more. It's comfortable. Heavier than lightweight watches but not too heavy. Able to fasten loosely without it slipping around. It still is better looking than the $89 G-Shock with Solar and MB6. You'd have to buy the $300+ JDM watch to get any better looking.

Title: Nice Watch! I recently had the Mission Impossible MTG910 ...
Text: Nice Watch! I recently had the Mission Impossible MTG910 Tough Solar Atomic lasted 10 years until the metal clasp wore out and lost it while working one day! I also have a Casio Riseman for 5 years now! I ordered this watch because of its heritage tough, reliable inexpensive! Now for a Con that has nothing to do with the watch. I bought this watch on Amazon for 45.00 and now it's 25.00 this pisses me off that Amazon pricing is so inflated!!!! Still happy with the watch so far!....Will update in the future! Highly recommended watch by a Gshock watch enthusiast!

Title: One Star
Text: 15 seconds late a day. Returned it.

Title: Tough enough for military men.
Text: I got this type of watch from PX during my basic training. I do not know anything about his watch. I just thought I needed one at that time. 8 yrs later, after 5 change of duty station and 2 deployments, it is still my favorite watch. I dug up my tough box last year and found it. Change the battery and slapped in a bull bar... Wallah! it is back to life after 13 yrs. I was thinking of purchasing the 5610. But I thought, why? I will never need a radio-controlled time clock. I will never have to deploy again. I am out of the service and I won't have to move more often. This watch is all I ever needed, except 1 with analog hand because I am a nurse now. And I ordered one that is a little bit chunky for a change GD 400-I. But personally, this is the best watch ever. Built to last.

Title: One of the toughest watches for the money!!
Text: This is one of Casio's most basic g-shocks, but it tells the time and also adds a few functions like timer, stopwatch, and alarms.  Every g-shock is made to very tough standards, so to get one at this price is really amazing.  It also has 200m water resistance, like every other g-shock made.  I've heard that if you don't use the light too often, the battery on this watch may last from 5-10 years.  The watch will survive any wear you put it through.  One nice added feature is that the light will stay on for as long as you keep the light button pressed. One note, the top left button is recessed so that it cannot be accidentally pressed.  That is not a flaw - it was designed that way.  I have never had trouble pressing it with my fingernail. This is a simple, basic Casio watch but it will serve the needs of most people, and it's hard to beat a g-shock for this price!

Title: If you don't but this watch, you've made a mistake.
Text: I wanted a cheap "beater" watch that's not too bulky, and that can withstand the elements; water, a few dings here and there,  something i can take snowboarding, mountain biking, kayaking, etc. I was hoping this can handle an extreme lifestyle and I guess time will tell if it does.. Regardless, I thought I'd only wear this on the days I'm doing something outdoorsy but this watch feels SOOO good on the wrist, and in my opinion is of amazing quality. I've worn many watches in my life, and this one is by far the most sleek and simple. Not too bulky, very retro and I like that classic look a lot, but also modern at the same time.  Easy to use. Gives you everything you need and nothing you don't. I was looking at so many other watches like the cheaper non-gshock casio's, but i'm glad this is what i decided to get. A STEAL. This looks like it'll make it through basic military training in a few weeks, and it won't be catching any long sleeve military uniform/or any long sleeve shirt/sweater. I'll be back to follow up on how it hold up! Love the 24 hour format feature too!

Title: The watch was too small for my wrist
Text: The watch seems like a good watch, but it was too small for my wrist so I can't wear it.

Title: Tough, readable and tough (did i mention it's tough)
Text: I got my first one in 1989 it lasted 8 years on one battery. That one had 23 jumps (airborne) I've had a few, none ever quit working.  Eventually they'd get beat up covered with paint or the plastic all tore up and I'd replace them. The last one I stripped the screws changing the battery and it wouldn't seal and fogs up so my wife bought me another, still works though.  So I've been wearing them 32 years and I don't want anything else.

Title: Therefore they are hard to press compared to something like the Timex Ironman
Text: THE BUTTONS ARE SMALL AND DO NOT STICK OUT VERY FAR. Therefore they are hard to press compared to something like the Timex Ironman. I returned the watch because of the buttons. However, everything else about the watch is AWESOME. It looks BA, it functions well, and by every indication is one of the most durable watches out there. If you don't mind the buttons, there's no reason you shouldn't buy it now.

Title: Personal perfect review of "Personal Perfect Watch"
Text: UPDATE: Now ponder this...of the 353 reviews herein, a whopping 94% are 4 and 5 stars and they span a period from 1/25/05 to today, 9/6/12. How many CEOS can even dream of 353 reviews...plus 94% continuous excellent ratings, plus spread over nearly 8 years, talk about customer loyalty. GREAT JOB G-SHOCK DW5600E. Perfect value/loyalty/excellence lesson for parents to teach their kids, huh? And for business classes to teach students. UPDATE: Please see very favorble review of Speidel 5600E watch band mentioned below. Also excellent for other G-Shocks as I discovered! ADDENDUM: I recently learned of a related product that some may find useful.  It is on Amazon under "Speidel 16mm Band Fits Casio GShock DW 5600E". I ordered one but haven't received as yet; $10 including shipping. Advertised as black leather band combined with either yellow or red color material. Looks rugged enough and reviews have said it is but can't comment yet. Will report back in few weeks. Please do yourself a huge favor and read G. Webster's "My personal perfect watch" review of 5600E. There is not a single mistatement of fact, no fluff, no nonsense, nothing but 100% honest and accurate evaluation. Date of his review is 2/20/09 and here I am over three years later finding it to still be the most helpful review one could find. I have owned GShocks for past 20+ years in addition to my 15 year old Seiko that I treasure. Two of my three GShocks have been 5600E's, the most recent purchased earlier this month. The 5600E is the perfect basic blocking-and-tackling watch. Full of necessary and helpful features (like your most useful and relied upon multi-tool/army knife), but no frills or wasted features to complicate things. Why am I still buying new GShocks? One of treats is to pass a used but still perfect product like this on to another grateful owner...they never forget. And for those complaining about the size and small print instruction booklet from Casio, do yourself another huge favor...go to Amazon and look up Carson pocket-size, LED light, magnifier. Mine is a couple of years in service now and I couldn't live without it. Cost less than $15 (maybe less than $10). Too bad I didn't get a new module of memory along with my purchase!! Time to climb down from the podium. Remember 5600E GShock (and if you're ready for it, a Carson battery LED pocket/purse magnifier). Thank me and G. Webster later!

Title: Built like a tank
Text: Holly moly, I had this exact watch back in the 80s and it was built like a tank then too. The design seems to be the same but I’m glad the light has been updated. Back then the light barely illuminated the screen.

Title: One Star
Text: The operating instructions were poorly written. I had to return this watch.

Title: Beautiful watch! But not as comfortable as $10 casio
Text: This watch is actually comfortable! Tho it does require half month of breaking in!

Title: Great watch but could be better!
Text: Love the simplicity, size,and function ! I bought the wrist band adapters and Zulu nylon watch band for this watch and like it even better. Only reason I didn't rate it 5 stars is it only has a 2 yr battery.

Title: The World's Greatest Digital Watch
Text: I paid retail for this watch (about 2x Amazon price) and still consider it a good deal.  I own a good number of watches and consider the DW5600E (and its variations) to be the absolute pinnacle of digital watch functionality. 1. It's virtually indestructible.  The only way to kill this watch is to destroy the display.  I put bars on mine to minimize that risk. 2. All the functions you need; none that you don't.  Time, calendar, stopwatch, countdown timer, alarm, and backlight.  99% of people will need nothing more, and the lack of superfluous functions and display complications means you aren't bogged down digging through functions to find what you need. 3. Rugged styling, but not overkill.  The watch is tough and looks tough, but it isn't so bulky and aggressive that it jumps out and looks ridiculous with normal attire.  I have baby wrists that make many other G-Shocks look ridiculous, and I can still pull off this watch. Despite the modest price point, this watch will do as much or more than many watches costing literally 200x as much.  There might be other reasons to get other digital watches (need for a particular function, aesthetics, etc) but as far as functionality is concerned, the DW4500 and its relatives are the greatest digital watches on the planet (and in space, because NASA uses them too).

Title: Durability
Text: Durable. Hefty, yet comfortable. Looks bulky, but wears smaller. Inner wrist protection-like guard won't allow the band to fully wrap around small wrists. Also, display can be hard to read from certain directions.

Title: Some damage visible...but still impresive
Text: I got this watch as a gift four years ago after going through countless Timex digital watches.  Here's a brief history of what I have done while wearing this watch: 1.) Ran every day, making use of the stopwatch and coating it in sweat.  This is just warm-up for the other suffering I put it through. 2.) Worked as a dishwasher, plunging my hands (and the watch) into an extremely hot bleach solution for a few hours every night for a year. 3.) Worked in an oil refinery, exposing the watch to chemicals and frequent impacts from climbing ladders, etc. 4.) Worked in a lab, frequently using 100% acetone and 100% alcohol to clean things.  I am sure these were splashed on the watch more than once. 4.) Went sailing frequently, beating the watch against the boat and immersing it in salt water. 5.) Went diving to over 100 ft several times.  Pushed buttons underwater at that depth. I have not had to replace the battery yet. Unlike others here, I cannot say it is perfect.  The glass has one scratch on it and the band is beginning to crack.  In addition, the black rubber case shows spots (they look like water spots) from when I applied bug spray (40% Deet) a few years ago.  However, I am still giving it 5 stars because it has held up dramatically better than any of my Timex watches ever did.  I am buying a new band and then hope to get a few more years out of this watch.

Title: OK but broken case near watch band connections.
Text: Good watch but watch case cracked. Super glued it back together. Seems OK. Watch is ten years old. Sat in a drawer for a couple years. New battery and it works OK.

Title: Great watch, especially after my last one.
Text: I had one of Amazon's best sellers, the Invicta 8926, for 3 years. For 2 of those years, it was inaccurate, its brand name everywhere was starting to annoy me, and the weight it had became cumbersome after i started swimming again. On the third year i had it, it stopped working on the seconds hand and by then, I was looking at better watches for $50+. When i came to Amazon, and was looking at reviews of good reliable watches, I think the casio dw 5600e had ~4 1/2 stars with 850+ people reviewing it. That was a year ago. Just to make it clear, i bought the dw 5600e at Walmart, but i check Amazon for reviews. I'm sure many other people do that as well. Sure it wasn't as visually appealing as the 8926, but for the year i had it, it only gain +1 min. And it had date and day of week on its face, so i can easily say I really like this watch for my needs. I've seen reviews here on people who whine about the top left button being 'far too' recessed. I can reach it fine, whenever i use it. The stopwatch and timer on the watch have been used to varying degrees, but not to professional levels. I haven't used the alarm yet, but i might get to it eventually. Also, whenever I swim, its like its not there at all. Actually, when i wear it in general, i dont feel any of its weight. Overall, its a great change to my previous watch. Invicta may have better watches, like its Reserve line, but i think I'll stick with this watch. It's a simple watch with the accuracy that one would need for everyday life and strength to take anything you dish out to it.

Title: Rugged, yet simple.
Text: The G-shock DW5600E-1V is perfect for everyday usage. It is very rugged and can survive many smashes and drops. Not only can it survive a drop, but it is also waterproof. Usability: This watch can be used for anything. Whether it is going to school, to work, or even to something more elegant. Like a wedding or even something smaller like a date night with your boy/girlfriend. As said before, it is rugged and waterproof. Perfect for outdoor activities like hiking, rock climbing, and even swimming! (Just don't go deeper than 200meters lol) Watchface/Features: This watch is very simple. Easy on the eyes and has everything that you ever need on a watch unlike some of their other lineups that include the altitude, another clock for a different country, etc. This has the simple: time (hh:mm:as), date (XX/XX), and as well as the day of the week (Mon-Sun). The watch has very small markings along the sides that lets the user what each button does which is a very useful touch and another useful feature on the watch is the Electro Luminescent Backlight which lights up the screen allowing the user to see the time and date in the dark. If you need a simple watch to wear to whatever occasion comes along your way, then this is the perfect watch for you. - Nick Salvador

Title: Like a rock
Text: I have had the Casio DW-5600E-1V G-Shock Classic Watch for over seven years, and it has lasted through all of my experiences. It has been the first thing on in the morning and the last thing off at night. Just because the price is cheap does not by any means qualify it as a cheap watch as far as quality. For the last three years, I have been swimming in a pool with it on for hours at a time. I have exposed it to hundreds of hours of being underwater. This watch takes all of the abuse that chlorine and other harsh chemicals expose it to. If you put it back together incorrectly or mess up the gasket that seals the cover, it may fog up a bit when underwater for a while. As long as you don't clumsily close the cover after replacing the battery, this watch is ready for any water experience. The weakest link is the watch band. I had the original one on for about four years, but eventually the harsh pool chemicals greatly degraded its strength. Putting a new band on is easy to do and should only take ten minutes. Other than that, the G-Shock will last. I have replaced the battery twice, and it is very easy to do with just four screws on the back. It gives a very nice warning to replace the batteries before it completely dies. For example, if the light is dim when turning on the illumination, then it is time to replace the batteries. If you don't use the light often, then you will not need to replace the battery for a very long time. I have found one feature especially useful. One night while camping, I had to find my way back to camp. It was pitch black out, and I forgot my flashlight. Luckily I was wearing my G-Shock that night. The light on this watch was actually powerful enough to illuminate the path for me to avoid tripping. You shouldn't replace your flashlight with this watch, but it does an excellent job as an emergency light. I won't soon forget the survival abilities packed into this watch. If you are concerned about the stereotype that G-Shocks are not classy to wear, then this watch is for you. It is very thin considering the nice construction of it, so you don't need to worry that it will be bulky and obtrusive. The width is about the same as any other typical men's watch. The color is black, so it could go nicely with any color shirt. I wear it to every occasion because it is quite versatile. Overall, I would recommend this watch to any man who wants something that will last without costing a fortune.

Title: All Time Best Hunter Watch
Text: I tried one other Casio G-Shock model since owning this one for years.  It was a solar watch, which was terrible.  The G-Shock and mud resistance were fine, but the solar was always flashing Low Batt.  I wear it UNDER my wrist, so it never saw the sun and therefore was useless.  This G-Shock model is the best I've ever seen for compact size and features.  I'll never use another model and this one should last as long as I have left to live.  Great for hunting and fishing, in that it doesn't drive you crazy with eye candy on the dial and useless features.

Title: Very impressive
Text: I bought this to replace my old G-Shock that I bought in 1989, which is still running fine but the side of the face broke off.  I glued it back in place but it does not look the same.  I thought it was not possible to get an exact replacement but I did.  I hope to get 30+ years out of this one like I did with my my old G-Shock.  Overall, this is the most reliable watch I have ever owned.

Title: Old School and Outstanding
Text: I have owned one of these watches continuously since about 1987, my current watch was purchased in 1991 and has only had the battery replaced once! If you don't use the alarm and light the battery lasts a long, long, time. There are so many choices in a G-Shock now that I wouldn't try to say that this older design is the best but I can say it sure does last. Recently, I ripped the plastic bezel enough that I simply removed what was left. After 20 plus years, the plastic seemed to break down and was not as resilient, now I'm planning on spending the $18 and just getting it fixed instead of buying a new one. To me the watch is a link with my younger self, as many of us wore these watches in the Marine Corps, more than 20 years ago, because you couldn't break one except for perhaps the pins. We all pulled the watch heads off the lousy plastic bands and put them on cloth or Velcro bands. Timex makes a nice, cheap, Velcro Expedition band that works well on this watch. The Timex band has elastic loops where the pins go, which helps to keep from breaking a pin if the watch gets caught on something. Funny, in the mid-eighties, the lithium batteries for these watches were more than $20, and buying a new watch at the base exchange was the same price as getting the battery changed. We would just get a new watch if we wore the battery out using the light for map reading, etc. The reason I am relating that story is that we "stress tested" one of the watches who's battery was running out and nothing short of smashing it between a helmet and a concrete floor would kill one. Also, when I changed the battery on my current watch a few years back, I found out the batteries are now around $2 and instructions on replacing the battery are easily available on the Internet. So, in summary, I recommend this watch.

Title: Every serious watch collection should have one...
Text: This is the only non-Swiss, non-automatic watch I own. I have a beater 2824-2 that I wear when I need to have something rugged... And I have this Casio DW5600 for when I need something bomb-proof (outdoor sports, working on motorcycles, digging in the dirt, doing plumbing jobs, etc). Ask our military personnel. This watch can take extreme abuse and is the most accurate timepiece I own despite having spent THOUSANDS on other watches. Every serious watch collection should have one of these.

Title: A no-brainer purchase
Text: The first time I bought this watch was in '83 and I was 13. I thought the commercial showing the goaltender catching the watch in his mitt after getting hit full-force with a slapshot was the coolest thing I'd ever seen on television. 36 years later? I've had 4 copies of the exact model ever since. This thing takes some serious abuse. Put it on and forget about it. The light makes it incredibly easy to read without being obnoxious and it doesn't look like a dinner plate on your wrist - it's just the right size. Waterproof and rugged. At this price, and with its storied history, you can't go wrong with this purchase. Buy this watch.

Title: Take it Deep
Text: Purchased this exact model back in the early 80s. Used it as my primary dive watch after much more expensive ones failed. Made many deep dives both free and scuba. The day I got severely bent I was wearing this watch. Spent two weeks in recompression undergoing repeated pressurization simulating depths to 200 feet. Watch never failed! Used it for years afterwards until it somehow got lost. Thought it was forever gone until I happened to see it again on Amazon. Go Casio!

Title: Great value for money
Text: Rugged and superb value for money.

Title: 7 Year Review (kinda)
Text: I remember I got this because it looked cool back in the day (2013). I wore it everyday for about 2 years and then stopped wearing it and put it away. A week ago I found it in my closet and I was completelly blown away at the fact that this is still running, the display hasnt dimmed, and to top it off it has the correct time and date.... thats impressive. Cant believe the battery lasted this long

Title: Indestructible, takes mud, grease, dirt.
Text: I have used DW-5600E G-Shock watches for decades, perhaps 40 years. Typically the battery lasts 7 to 10 years. I use it for an everyday time piece, including scuba diving, and back in the day, cave diving. This watch is virtually indestructible. It takes mud, grease, dirt, salt water, sweat, etc. When it gets muddy, just hose it down. My current DW-5600E, with the battery failing after 10 years, gains a second every few days and the numbers are fading. This might be because of low voltage. This watch is not jewelry. It's rugged time piece for harsh sports and dirty work environments. The watch may outlast it's band. Aftermarket bands are available.  I just purchased a replacement DW-5600E. The battery can be replaced, but at $40, it isn't worth the trouble.

Title: The only watch “you’ll” ever need!!
Text: I got my G-SHOCK in the 1980’s... it has been faultless!! I’ve owned any number of prestige watches in the almost 40 years since I was given my G-SHOCK... today I wear it daily and receive more laudatory comments than any other watch I’ve owned (Rolex included)! I clean it regularly with an old toothbrush and mild detergent. It has been with me through the worst of times and the best of times; it has my unreserved recommendation... get one! It will be the only watch you’ll ever need!

Title: My EDW (Every Day Watch) - Love it
Text: My wife gave me this Casio G-Shock watch 13 years ago. I am a one-watch guy and put it through heck everyday working on my ranch, swimming, hunting and general banging around. It finally quit working after swimming for hours in a lake. My bad, not the watch's fault. I sent my wife the Amazon link for this, the exact same watch after she asked me what I wanted for my birthday next month. HIGHLY Recommend? You Bet!

Title: Simple and nice
Text: Simple design. Basic features. Only the needed features. I like it. the only thing that bothers me is the up left button. it's hard to press it. This is annoying when using the stopper as it is used to reset it.

Title: Simply the best cheap Casio G-Shock
Text: This is my first G-Shock. I have used at Junior High 2 Casio watches (the basic ones) and I stopped to used them because one ran out of battery and the other one the resin just ripped. So right now (after college) decided to get this one. No mistake. Simply the best. Just one complain: I have a small wrist. So at the beginning I found it a little annoying, it hurt sometimes, but after one month looks like it fit very good. No hurt at all. If you love the Casio brand because of its quality and durability, just get this G-Shock. You won't regret.

Title: This is THE Watch
Text: G-Shock DW5600E- the watch I always come back to. This watch has been with me through 2 deployments and on 5 continents over the past 5 years. I have rolled down mountains, laid in gravel, swam in 3 oceans, ran 3-5 miles in it daily, been rained on for 30 days straight, and hit it on every door knob that I have passed. The watch face is not scratched, and I am still on my first battery. The backlight on mine is green and is the perfect amount of time and light, and the watch has all of the basic functions I need while still remaining slim and classic looking. I own several dive watches along with dress watches, but this is the watch I wear the most. And after all of this beating, along with daily showering, the watch looks brand new. This is because you can replace the rubber strap and rubber cover easily and affordable. I love this watch. I tried a rangeman but found it way too big and complicated compared to the sleek design and ease of use of this watch. I would definitely buy another.

Title: Similar to the old classic
Text: My first exposure to a G-shock was in the engine room of a USN destroyer, on the wrist of a gas turbine technician while we were standing the midwatch.  "That watch looks tough," I said.  "I don't know...let's find out," he replied, then took it off, picked up a rubber mallet and started pounding it like a madman.  It bounced around on the deck plates but never cracked or broke.  I was sold. This watch looks identical to that watch but is deficient in a few ways.  The second time zone feature is gone, and perhaps as a result the functions of the buttons are rearranged in a way that feels screwy.  New purchasers of the watch will probably like it just fine.  Users who bought the old version for $25 twenty years ago from the commissary will have the unpleasant feeling of talking to a best friend who's been lobotomized. It's still a solid product--excellent for all manner of outdoor activities (though too thick to fit inside a standard dress shirt sleeve cuff)--but I'm frustrated with Casio's poor headwork in redesigning it backwards.

Title: 100% perfect.
Text: My wife purchased this watch for me and I just wanted to check in and say I love it! I have a higher-end G-Shock (GW7900B) but I love the DW5600E much more because it's not as thick, it's more comfortable to wear and it's easier to read. It's really a perfect watch in all respects. Secretly I love how nerdy it is too.  ;)

Title: Great watch
Text: Excellent watch classic design ,you can't beat for the price.

Title: Simple design but great qualitywatch
Text: Simple design but great quality watch.  I didn't need all those extra dials and buttons which only confuse and frustrate me.  I'm very happy with this simple digital dial, with date and time and a nice back light when needed.

Title: An Updated Version Of An Absolute Classic
Text: The CASIO DW5600E-1V is a 1996 update to the DW5600C that made it's debut in 1987. The original had a few features that were omitted later. These were: Stainless steel case Auto-calendar 1985 - 2029 (the update spans 1995 - 2039) Dual time (I kinda wish they hadn't gotten rid of this one) Reminder mark Backlight (tiny incandescent lightbulb) The 1996 update, which is what is being reviewed here boasts: Composite-polymer case (30% lighter) Shock resistant 200 meter water resistant Alarm (daily or monthly functionality) Electroluminescent backlight (blinks during alarms & hourly chimes - can be turned on/off) 1/100 second stopwatch Measuring capacity: 00'00"00-59'59"99 (for the first 60 minutes) - 1:00'00-23:59'59 (after 60 minutes) Measuring unit:  1/100 second (for the first 60 minutes) - 1 second (after 60 minutes) Measuring mode: elapsed time, split time, 1st-2nd place times Countdown timer with auto-repeat function (A-R function can be turned on/off) Measuring unit: 1 second Countdown range: 24 hours Countdown start time setting range: 1 second to 24 hours (1-second increments and 1-hour increments) Hourly chime Auto calendar 12/24 hour formats Approx. battery life: 2 years So, what can I say or write about this watch that hasn't already been said or written? I mean, seriously. This watch has been around for 24 years (15 years in it's current configuration). In many ways, it IS the perfect watch. It has everything you need and nothing superfluous. In fact, CASIO calls it the "quintessential G-SHOCK". I couldn't agree more. For almost a quarter-century, this watch has been worn by people engaging in just about any task imaginable, in just about any condition imaginable. Even NASA has qualified this particular watch for space-flight missions. If you need the ultimate piece of all-condition gear, the incredibly simple, functional and TOUGH CASIO DW5600E-1V will more than fill that need. It's a true masterpiece.

Title: Durable beyond belief
Text: Bought this in the late 90's for about 80 bucks. Lasted for about 10 years. I used it snorkeling in sea water 4 times and that eventually took its toll, and the elevated face peeled off. Even then the watch was functional. I bought another solar powered G-Shock, that failed within 2 months - time kept going off completely. Will probably go back to this classic.

Title: Best watch I've ever owned
Text: I'm on my second one now.  First one finally gave out after 18 years of hard, daily use and abuse.  (I wish they still ran the original commercials where it showed the watch strapped to a hockey puck being hit with a slap shot and working just fine afterwards.) Simple and easy to learn to use.  Features: - It tells you the time, date, and day of the week at a glance. - It has 1 alarm, not numerous worthless alarms. - A countdown timer. - A stopwatch. - 12/24 hour display options. - Hour alert. - Strong backlight. - Time display while in other modes - a real nice feature. - Not as bulky as other models. The only thing I dont like about this model as compared to my first one is the back plate.  It now seems cheaper and not as reliable as the first one I owned that screwed on.  The current one attaches with 4 small screws that when overtightened, will distort the oring.

Title: A reliable friend
Text: This watch is a throwback to the 1980's. It is basic with no distractions to just telling you the time, day and date. No automatic anything except that it knows how many days are in each month up to 2099. Ruggedness is its main trait, which has been described in many of the previous reviews. The worst I have done to it was upon opening the package the watch and hangar flew out and landed on our hardwood floor - no issues resulted. My watch had a very stiff Adjust button. It required a ballpoint pen to press it in enough to begin changing the time. I thought about returning it, but decided not to. The next time I used it, the adjust button pressed in fine without a tool. Speaking of time, it is an accurate watch, gaining about 10 seconds per month, within expectations. The band is comfortable, better than some other G-Shocks I tried that had sharp edges.  The display is clear and the numbers are an adequate size. It would be nice if they brought back the dual time feature for this watch. It is a strong, basic watch. The funny thing is I have several nicer looking and much more expensive watches, yet I usually prefer wearing this plain, rather clunky Casio. Why? I don't know - maybe because it is comfortable, light weight, and easy to read. It is like an honest reliable friend I can depend on. Five Stars, Recommended.

Title: Great bootcamp watch.
Text: Bought this watch at the small NEX at Great Lakes last year when I went through bootcamp. This is a great little watch that will survive just about anything. Gave mine away to a P days recruit after graduation, but bought another maybe a month later. So far has survived Japan, Thailand, and most of the Asian Pacific.

Title: How long can it go?
Text: You caon't argue with the quality of something that has "ticked" for quarter century. My DW-5600 was originally purchased in the beginning of 1991, in a hole in the wall store in New York City. 27 years later, it still works. The only changes: new strap (metal) and one (1) new battery. Back then, it was made in Japan, and contrary to what someone posted, it did say St. Steel rather than Stainless Steel on the back. Maybe the interim version had Stainless Steel, but the grandpa doesn't. Just about the only thing I'd wish for is the illumination glow. Grandpapi has a minuscule little light for the display. Still, one of the best purchases of my life.

Title: Guaranteed to make you run faster and jump higher.
Text: This watch is by far the best asset I have when it comes to timing stuff. For example, I tried using an egg timer for laps in the pool and i couldn't hear it under the water, this watch was not only is super loud if the alarm goes off under water but it has an auto timer loop feature that goes down to the second. My iPhone doesn't even do that! Some of the annoying things, it is always on time, the timer seems to go fast while trying to get my mile time under 4 minutes and the black color goes with everything. All in all this is a great watch, only thing it doesn't do is feed you and take your heart rate.

Title: old school, 1980"s look
Text: this is a cool ,watch if you are a 80"s baby like me or mid 80"s baby or not this is. a cool watch it is  cool  got.a old school look, to it just like i remember. it back in back in the day.

Title: The Volvo 240 of Wristwatches?
Text: You know the 240, that uber-boxy wagon,(usually), middle-class families drove for 15 years then gave to their kid for college because it was safe and they realized they couldn't kill it! These days it's a minor/cult classic, loved for it's longevity and kind of cool as it's so unfashionable. This watch is kind of similar. It's a direct ancestor of the first G-Shock Casio launched in 1983 and hasn't changed much since it was introduced in 1996, except for a movement update to extend the auto-calendar to 2099 4 years ago. It's small compared to most current watches and kind of a curio as you probably haven't owned anything like it since the 80's,  I've had a more recent G-Shock (GW500-A) for about 5 years now and have come to really appreciate it. I bought it to wear at work as I'm a C/O and didn't want to subject my other watches to life in prison. That watch has held up extremely well and recently the G-Shock bug has bitten as I found myself looking around for another. This fits the bill perfectly. No Multiband 6 atomic timekeeping or Tough Solar here, just a big battery and 1 alarm, 1 stopwatch, and 1 timer. It's very simple to set up and I like the low-key look. I hope all the stories about indestructible build quality and mammoth battery life are true. I'll let you know, hopefully in about 15 years time. . .

Title: Timeless?
Text: I was just going through some boxes in my storage unit when I ran across my G-Shock which I purchased from the PX on Fort Drum, NY in 1988! It is still going, with the original battery, it has only lost 13 minutes and all of the plastic that was around the case body and the free loop on the strap. Thirty one years. Amazing.

Title: Durable! Effective water resistance! A nice gift for husband.
Text: My husband loved it! I bought this in 2013 and he is still using it now. According to him, the watch is very durable. It withstood the falls and bumps all these years. Water resistance is as described. We've been to a lot of swimming escapades, both here and in the US and in the Philippines, and still it delivered in the water resistivity department. He never had an issue with it.

Title: One Star
Text: lost...

Title: Survived Basic Training
Text: From the riggers of basic training to my civilian job as a mechanic this watch has endured it all. I have worn it for 1 year now and have taken it off maybe 3 or 4 times this watch is perfect.

Title: Fantastic Watch!
Text: Fantastic watch. Literally my only complaint is that you cannot operate it in the dark. You can activate the backlight, but the second you press another button to say, set an alarm, the backlight turns off. Not a huge deal, and I am sure that the more expensive models don't have this problem. Overall a great watch and I plan on having it for years.

Title: Great price and fantastic product
Text: I like casio products, you can always count on them. I needed a new g shock after almost twenty years. The price was great and shipping was fastg

Title: No Joke
Text: Excellent, no nonsense watch. Does all the stuff you need and no extra junk.

Title: Solid Watch
Text: I found this watch in the mud during jungle warfare training in Okinawa in 2014. I have no idea how old it was when I found it but it is still ticking 5 years later on the same battery. It is simple with a relatively low profile face. I will definitely replace it with the same make and model when it dies on me.

Title: Get It!!
Text: I did not buy @ Amazon, but that should not matter. I have had mine for about 3 years now. I totally love it! This watch has been Beat and Banged. I shower with it on. I do dishes with it on. I am looking at a G Shock with hands, and not having much luck with those reviews. In all likelihood I will get this watch again, as I gave my current watch to my son. I almost forgot. The watch looks exactly as it does in the picture. Men or Women can wear it. Not too big, not too small. Back light, lights up the entire display.  It says 8 year battery, depending on use. My battery should have died long ago, as much as I use the back light. You will not be disapointed.

Title: Blast from the past but with a major design flaw
Text: Like the majority of the negative reviews state, it's impossible to adjust the stopwatch and timer without carrying around a tool (toothpick works) so that you can push in top left button which is overly recessed. I don't want to impale myself when sitting down, so carrying around a sharp object in my pocket all the time is out. Otherwise, a great blast from the past (i.e. the 80's) when I last owned one but can't recall what happened to my old one. Think it needed a new battery but I didn't have the cash at the time, so traded it to a friend for something else a didn't have the money for (perhaps an Atari video game cartridge or some floppy disks for the Commodore 64). Bought the Casio DW-5600E for the big 50th birthday, but ended up returning it (very sad!). Casio ended up upselling me, as a soothed my disappointment by purchasing the GW-S5600-1JF (Carbon fiber band, milled titanium back, atomic time, & solar) at 4X the cost. You only live once and now that I'm getting up there in years and have a good career, figure you can't take it with you.

Title: Casio Classic- Simple, Does Everything Well
Text: G-Shock is a solid value. That said my Skmei, at under $10 feels like and looks like a much better value. 1) Skmei strap is softer material 2) Skmei is larger more masculine presence on a larger wrist 3) 50M Water Resist is sufficient for my purposes. So why did I purchase a classic G-Shock? Why not!

Title: A viable step-up
Text: A viable step-up from the classic Illuminator, I really like it.

Title: Best watch I ever owned.
Text: I'm 42. When I was 12, my dad bought me this watch. I wore it swinging a hammer all day in the summer. I dropped it off a roof. I stepped on it, kicked it across the room, and left it in a mud puddle overnight. 20 years later, it still worked and was running from the original battery! The light still worked as well. Eventually the casing rotted off, but the watch still worked. I don't know if they still make this with the quality they once did, but this watch was a beast!

Title: A Mindbogglingly Durable Watch
Text: I bought one of the original Casio G-Shock watches in 1989 for about $69 when I was 17-years-old.  I wore it every day for years.  It endured every adventure, every activity and every life-changing event with accuracy and aplomb.  After over a decade, I began to wear the resin casing out.  At some point, the entire case crumbled away.  So I stopped wearing the watch and tossed it into a drawer.  Over the following years, I would occasionally be digging through the drawer looking for something else and I'd stumble upon the skeletal remains of my original G-Shock.  To my amazement, each time I found the watch not only functional but still keeping time... with the ORIGINAL BATTERY.  I'm now 39-years-old.  My wife and I just moved.  While going through our belongings, I came across my G-Shock and couldn't resist showing off the still functioning watch to my wife.  After 22 years the original battery was still going strong!  The mindboggling simplicity and endurance of the original G-Shock represents the benchmark of sturdiness and reliability.  If you're planning to dive to the bottom of the Mariana Trench, to trek though the Sahara, to ski to the South Pole or to pilot a spacecraft to Mars, you won't find a better suited watch than the original G-Shock.

Title: Amazing Watch!
Text: I have had this watch for over three years and have worn it almost every day since. I have a few other watches for when I get all dressed up and when i just want to wear something else but this watch has always been my favorite. Its sleek and just about indestructible. I have done contracting jobs, I have done a lot of service, and I have also worked out with this watch on and its still in top condition like the first day I received it. The buttons are a little weird how they're sunken into the watch face and hard to press but it's not that bad. To sum it up, if you're looking for a digital watch that looks great, can take a beating, and you don't want to hurt your pocket this classic Casio is the one to buy.

Title: Best value for the price, every watch fan should have such in their collection.
Text: Looked for it and waited for it. Happy to have it, its most epic watch one of all G-Shock series, nothing fancy just everything the real watch needs, and its one of the tuffests watches in the world.

Title: My 2nd G-Shock: Not Because I Broke my First, but as Insurance in Case the Batter Dies
Text: My father purchased the original "tuna can" G-Shock DW-5600 as a bus driver back in the 1980's.  Until a few years ago when the incandescent light bulb burned out, it worked perfectly.  I received a Casio G-Shock DW-6600 back in Middle School as a birthday present over ten years ago.  I have taken it camping, hiking, swimming, white water rafting, sea kayaking, mountain climbing, zip lining, SCUBA diving, geology trips, and every other activity where I would question any other watch's survival.  The watch still works beautifully.  There is a reason this is the watch of choice of EMTs, Police, Fire Fighters, soldiers, Army Rangers, Navy SEALs, the Delta Force, Team 6, etc., and the G-Shock has been flight qualified by NASA for manned spaceflight. I purchased my second G-Shock, a DW-5600, not because my old 6600 is broken, but as insurance in case the battery dies.  I like how the 5600 is thinner than my 6600, does not get snagged on long sleeves, and does not have the progress meter.  However, I prefer my 6600's 5-button interface over the 5600's 4-button.  For the stopwatch function, to reset the counter on the 6600, I can simply press the reset button.  On the 5600, I must press the recessed adjust button, a much more annoying and trickier step. My only complaint is with the G-Shock band.  The original on my 6600 broke after a few years of use.  I have replaced it with two other generic rubber straps, and a second G-Shock band, all of which have failed.  I now have it on a 16mm NATO strap.  This seems to be working better.

Title: Unbeatable!
Text: Owned mine since 2002, still going strong and excellent shape! Battery lasts for years and extremely good value and tough! I work outside every day in Minnesota and it works excellent no matter the weather!

Title: Soldier's Watch
Text: I was an infantry paratrooper for 3 years. This watch was in the mud, water, heat, and very cold. I jumped out of planes with the watch, wore it in the desert, in the jungle, and during live fire missions all over the hemisphere. The watch never failed me and kept great time. I wore it until the battery gave out, and bought another. This watch belongs in the pantheon of tough workhorse watches, and I recommend it to anyone that wants a hardcore timepiece that can resist extremes and deliver no matter what.

Title: The perfect watch
Text: This is the perfect watch. Reliable, durable, every function you need, and nothing you don't. Beautiful arrangement of time, date, and day on the main screen. Full-featured alarm, timer, and stopwatch functions. Pleasant backlight. Crystal face is super scratch resistant. (Still looks brand new after 7 years) Reasonable price hits the sweet spot: cheaper watches are flimsy and lacking in features, more expensive watches have unnecessary bells and whistles. Replace the battery and wrist strap every 3-5 years (very easy) and this watch will last a lifetime.

Title: dad loves it
Text: papi swears by this watch. he has worn them for over 50 years. the battery seems to last forever and its very sturdy. great product.

Title: This would withstand a nuclear blast!!
Text: This watch will literally fall apart before it ceases to stop telling time. But this is actually a good thing. I bought this model over 22 or 23 years ago and was able to proudly wear it for around 10 or 11 years without a battery change or anything. I had to replace the band many times but it was worth it just to see how long I could make it last. Finally had to give up on it after around 11 years because the plastic casing around the body fell apart...so I put it's remains respectfully in a box which ended up in storage. About 2 weeks ago (probably a good 10 years since I retired it) I was digging through my shed for something and heard this faint but familiar beeping sound from years gone by. I opened the box from which the beeping was coming and there it was...the metal sleleton of my old CASIO beeping it's alarms ass off. I felt like I was reunited with a long lost friend. I couldn't believe it. I checked the time on it and it was off by maybe 20 minutes. I put it back in the box and will check up on it again in another 10 years. I was so impressed though that I felt compelled to buy another G-SHOCK CASIO. I just ordered it today and am looking forward to it's arrival. It's a different model though with analog hands. But I'm sure it will be another "good friend" to me for another 10 years. Maybe my old friend will have a new friend to hang out in the shed with until my 3rd one is ready to retire in 20 years : )

Title: There's something about this time piece that makes me feel like a real man
Text: First off, I Just wanna say not really a watch guy but lemme tell ya. There's something about this time piece that makes me feel like a real man. Weather its the all-purpose rubber strap or the practically in-your-face luminance features this watch has literally changed my life. When Caio says "G-Shock" oh man do they mean it because literally this watch has "shocked" my life to new meanings I had previously never thought possible. In all seriousness, buy this watch if you enjoy smoking hotties, ripping waves and pretty much just being substantially better than everyone else you've ever met in your entire life. For real.

Title: I really like this watch
Text: I just received this watch yesterday, so I can't comment on longevity, but so far, I really like this watch. I usually don't wear digital watches, but I wanted to add a simple, rugged watch to my collection. This watch just made sense. It's very easy to set up, I set mine within 30 seconds out of the box without looking at directions(and I'm not that smart :)) it's a G-shock, so it should be able to handle anything I dish out. It's easy to read the time and date without pushing any buttons. I like the simplicity. I have much nicer watches that I enjoy wearing, but this will get some wrist time too. Oh, and I will add that my wife says it's ugly and she hates it, so I'm pretty sure it's not a watch to wear if you're trying to impress the ladies, but if you just want a watch to tell you the time, and not worry about messing it up, it'll definitely work.

Title: Durable, but dated
Text: This classic model of Casio's G-Shock line holds up quite well in a variety of conditions. I've had mine now for about 4 years and it's amazing that it only has a few scratches to show for the abuse it's been through; Rock-climbing, swimming in fresh, chlorinated and salt water, water skiing/wake boarding, snow boarding, the whole gambit of outdoor sports. Additionally, it's even had a few 50 - 100 pound servers land on it with no effect. It's comfortable, cheap and dependable. On the other hand; the undersized buttons are a bit of a nuisance, especially so when your struggling to turn your alarm off after a night of rambunctious debauchery. The button size coupled with the fact that a newer model G-Shock that comes with over-sized, easy-to-press buttons will only set me back another $10 - 15 is the main reason for my average rating, and also why I will be upgrading. I hope that the newer models are as durable as this one is. Also, I've been complimented/made-fun-of by the hipster cred this watch brings with it. Wasn't my intention when I bought this, but I can see how it could fit into the whole "faux-geek-chic" that some hipsters strive for, what with their Triforce Tattoos and lens-less glasses frames. Be wary!

Title: Outstanding Value!
Text: With the advent of the original G-shock DW5000 in 1983 Casio set the benchmark very high for shock resistance, precision and durability in its digital watches.  Since then, millions of these watches have gone around the world and have provided amazing longevity on the wrists of their owners.  The updated model is now the DW5600E-1V which came out in 1996 with a few modifications.  The current model has the night illuminator feature and 4 small screws holding the back in place instead of the original screwback design.  This makes for a lighter, more comfortable feel and the resin still holds up extremely well to the elements.  Some die hard original gshockers love the older models because they had a heavier, more solid feel.  However, with the current price point for this gem of a watch, in my mind, you can't find any better value anywhere for a no nonsense, bomb-proof daily wear time piece.  After all, who can argue with millions of satisfied customers, including police, armed forces, emergency responders and firemen??  They seem to gravitate to these and other models of gshock. To sum it up, it's an amazing watch at an amazing price with a proven track record of nearly 30 years with very few design changes.  Very impressive!

Title: my old Casio is still working
Text: I still have a DW-5700 with the original battery still working. The bezelis gone and the band keeper is gone but this watch has gone the distance for at least 30 years. I'm going to not replace it but add a 5600 to the team. I have many Casio's and I thought I'd lost this one. These are all great watches. I highly recommend any of them.

Title: Excellent watch
Text: This is my 6th g-shock. Bought my 1st one in Feb 1989 when I was in the U.S. Marines. I wear them until the band breaks, which usually takes about 5 years. They have handled all the use & abuse I put them through with zero problems.

Title: Perfect
Text: ..it does lose some seconds in a month or so, but it is negligible, and very easy to set back to the right time. I used it (intermittently) for more than 6 months now, wearing it constantly at the swimming pool, and it works just fine, no scratches, no nothing. Just great!

Title: A great deal !
Text: After owning a Casio DW 240 for over 20 years & diving over 100 ft. with no problems , My only problem with this watch was reading the face at night , due to vision issues. When I was given the DW 5600E by a friend, my problems were solved. I purchased this watch as a Christmas gift for a longtime friend who was admiring  my watch this summer. The Casio reputation as a great workhorse goes without saying. I've put over 8 watchbands & probably 5 batteries in the DW 240. I guess this watch will probably be the last one that I'll have to buy, if you can go by the quality of the old 240. The watchband was replaced on the DW5600E for $18 on ebay. It seems to be a better, sturdier band than the DW240, so , as I mentioned earlier, Batteries & watchbands are all that should be needed for many years of service. The extra protection on the buttons was a great idea , as the old DW240 would sometimes get banged against something under normal wear & I have had to free-up the post. This is all the watch anyone would need, & makes a great gift.

Title: ABOUT the IRRITING WRIST STRAP
Text: I have given this only one star so that may be found. this is for the Casio DW5600e G-Shock. I may also apply to other Casio G-Shock watches too. Somewhere a reviewer complained about the strap irritating their wrist to where they could not use it.  SOLUTION? cut a piece of quality Gaffer's tape. longer than the band plate to extend beyond the beginning of each strap, narrower than the two sides (so not visible). apply. cut second piece the same if needed. WHY Gaffers tape? 1.) it can removed without making a mess (NOT duct tape..) stays on. including in water (I doubt underwater diving in slat water) 2.) when you need to replace the battery gaffers tape comes off without a mess. 3.)illuminates the irritating spot (which is due to the strap edge connected at the watch side. After 3 years I am happy. It is not the same as the original. Timer and Light buttons are reversed. reset button is inset and requires my fingernail to press. strap is not same material, but the original one went brittle and broke off soddenly. and the crystal is a hardened plastic. It will scratch if hit onto something hard enough.. So, if you are looking at this and want to replace to the original, get over it. Just looked for the original used anywhere. It starts at $239.00  !!! It was a wonderful watch, but that was over thirty years ago Since them dollars have depreciated. $250 is today worth about the $40 back then. Good glass costs more, the diving limit was 300 meters, now 200meters (DE560e). And everything is made in China, each Japan's auto industry sub-contracts parts from Thailand and China. Times change. If you want the original, go find a used one and spend the $200 or more $$. otherwise, this one is fine, just take into account the flaws. About the wrist strap. You can find replacements for these newer Casio watches. just look. There are watch distributors that carry the whole line of the various types. in the USA. enjoy. Oh, and the different models have different color background light LED colors. Find one with back light on before buying

Title: A classic, but incredibly tough.
Text: I received my G-Shock for graduation a few months back. Since then, I've managed to get it covered in mud, dust, go swimming, shower with it daily and drop it probably a thousand times. Only difference between now and then? Absolutely none. This watch is tough. The functions are rather simple (date, time, stopwatch, alarm, illumination), but do you really need eight alarms and time zones for every country? Honestly, my G-Shock does what I need it do which is to be a reliable and tough watch that I can use in everyday situations. If you're looking for a classy watch that will go well with a tuxedo then you probably need to look elsewhere. If you're looking for a watch that can handle everything you throw at it and keep on ticking then this is the watch for you. I'm on my first one and I imagine I'll own several over the years due to how tough this one is.

Title: The last watch you'll ever need
Text: After so many detailed reviews, I will keep it simple. The classic Casio G-Shock is the horological equivalent of the Swiss Army knife and the Zippo lighter. It's a mass-produced marvel of industrial design, absolutely reliable, extremely durable even under harsh conditions and astonishing value for money. It's one of those quintessential Japanese high-quality products that conquered the world in the 80's. Do I need to say more?

Title: Over 1500 reviews and counting
Text: Over 1500 reviews! What does that tell you? A classic watch that's never going to go out of style and not going break the bank. I have many other Casio g shocks but this model will always be my all time favorite. A great everyday watch that is extremely durable and easy to wear.

Title: Bang for the buck
Text: Best size of all the g shocks. Everything you could ever need in a $40 watch.

Title: One of my best friends
Text: I have owned one for over twenty years now. Changed the battery three times. It has been run over by bulldozers, tractors and dump trucks. I submerged it in ice cold water during hurricane Bob. It has been through every weather condition I can think of. I built a golf course and continue to build hardscape structures. A few years ago the black shell around the watch finally pealed off. The setting buttons are sticky and I replaced the band five years ago. The dang thing still keeps perfect time and every function works. LOVE THIS WATCH. It will probably out live me.

Title: 25 year-old G-shock still working -- ON THE ORIGINAL BATTERY!
Text: I bought this watch in 1988 or 1989 at Jacks Surfboards in Huntington Beach CA, wore it around the world  and surfed with it for decades. The original yellow plastic case and strap have faded and cracked due to UV exposure and the light no longer comes on --  but it is still working and keeping perfect time -- and I have NEVER replaced the battery! Geez, what a tribute to brilliant design. And my Apple iPhone can't even make it through a single DAY without the battery running out! I Googled this and discovered that there are also others who have reported similar battery life in this watch so it's not a one-off, freak occurrence.

Title: Casio G-Shock - Transatlantic
Text: I have used the Casio G-Shock Classic for over 15 years as a transatlantic commercial airline pilot. I also had a titanium Breitling available. The Casio was my first choice for work. Over those years, I changed the battery twice (never because it failed) and I changed the plastic band three times (cracked due to rough use in woodworking - I kept an extra on hand). The time piece NEVER failed me - accurated to about 25 seconds per month and EASY to adjust to the precise second for on-time departures. If the styling fits your desires, this watch should be your first choice.

Title: Get Because You Won't Regret It!
